    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>Robert Prior writes:
>>
>>> A light sail module takes up one space. At GTL8 it has an area of 15 sq
>>> miles, at GTL9+ an area of 240 sq miles.  It provides 10 tons of thrust at
>>> GTL8, 160 tons of thrust at GTL9+.  Mass is 50 tons at all tech levels.
>>
>>Note that in GVE2 the thrust is 5.26 lb/square mile (9e-6 newtons/square
>>meter) or 0.63 tons for the above sail.  Assuming a solar flux of 1,400
>>watts/square meter the actual value is 9.3e-6 newtons/m^2, which is
>>reasonable enough.
>
> True enough. I was using the GURPS Space version originally.  It _does_
> need correcting.

Actually, there\'s another problem (potential). You need to sanity check
the figures for the sail mass.

I just checked and plastics seem to be around 1.0 density. But you need
to aluminize the plastic. So let\'s go for a density of 2.0 and a
thickness of one atom or so (Al ions seems to have a radius of .39 to
.54 angstroms, so we\'ll go for 1 angstrom).

1 angstrom = 1e-10 m.

So, 1 square mile = 2.59e6 m^2. Which means that 1 sqare mile of 1
Angrstrom thick sail has a volume of 2.59e-4 m^3. with a specific
gravity of 2, that gives a mass of about 518 grams per square mile (Yow!).
Or 18.3 pounds, or 9.134e-3 tons/mi^2. 

Note that I seriously doubt this would work as a sail, even if
assembled using nanotech. And that I\'m ignoring the shroud lines and
any required "tensile fibers" (required to keep the sail from ripping
apart from the tensile stresses).

>>A 1-space (50T) sail is 250 square miles with GVE2.  Thrust is 0.66T.
>>Maximum area is 360,000 square miles (1440 modules).

And mass has to be above (way above!) 2.28 tons per space (250 mi^2).

>>A 1-space (490T) TL-8 sail is 15 square miles with a thrust of 0.038T (it
>>has marginally lower thrust); maximum area is 3,600 square miles (240
>>modules)

And it must mass above .137 tons per space (15 mi^2).

