    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> From: ehenry@newberlin.org (Eric Henry)
>> .001 kiloton?  why not just drop a WWII bomb?
>
> Because it would burn up in reentry?

Not if it is designed properly. Missile warheads reenter *fast* and
survive. 

I\'d point out to the powers that be that the "slow down for re-entry"
only applies to anything that wants to *land*. Kinetic kill weapons,
and even "normal nukes"  *won\'t* bother slowing down, it makes it too
easy to nail them before they impact their targets.

>> This is certainly not in the planet busting category although it might
>> stop an armored fighting vehicle.
>
> I would hope so!  35,000 (2) points of damage is nothing to sneeze 
> at.  That\'s enough to take out a 20,000 dTon ship with 30,000 points 
> of DR.

There\'s a simple "rule of thumb" used in estimating damage from meteor
strikes and the like. 

At 3 km/sec, an impacting object releases energy equal to its mass in
TNT (ie a 100 kilo projectile impacting at 3 km/sec will make the same
sized hole as a 100 kilos of TNT). 

The energy goes up as the *square* of the velocity. Thus, a 12 km/sec
projectile will have *16* times the blast effects. So a 100 kilo
projectile is equivalent to 1.6 tonnes of TNT. 

I picked 12 km/sec for a reason. First, it\'s just a bit above escape
velocity (11 km/sec) and it is exactly 4 times the 3 km/sec figure
above, making calculations easy.

Why is being close to escape velocity important? Because not only is
escape velocity the speed to need to "escape to infinity (ie never
fall back), it\'s also the speed an object free-falling from infinity
would have at impact (if there was no atmosphere). 

The Earth\'s orbital velocity around 20-30 km/sec. At 30 km/sec our 100
kg projectile will release 100 times the energy it would at 3 km/sec.
Or about the energy of 10 *tons* of TNT.

Now consider that a 100 kg projectile like this, could simply be a
chunk of properly shaped stell with a ceramic or graphite coating to
ensure it survives to hit the ground. And it\'ll have a volume of 1/80th
of a cubic meter. Or a bit over 1/80th of a cubic yard. 

So let\'s consider one that\'s an entire cubic meter in volume. It\'ll
mass 7.8 tonnes. And again the impact energy will be *100* times that.
So we are talking about the equivalent of 780 tonnes of TNT. That\'s
over 3/4s of a kiloton!

