    'body' => 'Via electronic medium on 12/1/99 2:38 PM, ingram@airmail.net wrote:

> In a recent discussion the subject of Bribery came up. I don\'t use it as a
> skill
> in MTU. How difficult is it to bribe someone anyway?!?  Is it like electronics
> or medical, or even gun combat? How much training or experience is actually
> involved to advance to a higher level. I accept it as a task, but not as a
> separate skill!  I assume that anyone with Streetwise would be successful at
> bribery. Any opinions out there?
> 
> Alex
> 
I hadn\'t thought of the link between streetwise and bribery, but I would
still keep them seperate, allowing streetwise to default at a small penalty
to bribery. I agree it is not a complex skill, but I usually use some
gradiation in skill types, and would place bribery at the lowest, cheapest
rank. Consider also that it can be used not just to actually bribe someone,
but for determining if a bribe attempt is likely to be risky or readily
accepted, what type of incentive would be best (cash, contraband, favor,
etc.), to communicate to another that you are bribable, spot a bribe taking
place, etc.

As far as medical, I have long ago given up generalizing such a complex
field into a single skill. Anatomy, diagnostics, surgery, pharmaceuticals,
it\'s  a huge ball of interlocking disciplines. Perhaps R. O\'Conner can give
some pointers to help flesh out that area of game mechanics. Monitoring the
physical condition of characters during combat, hostile environments,
disease, etc. has always been a weak link in many systems. Most, IMHO.
