    'body' => 'From: Jason T. Barnabas <cybernaut@netzero.net>


> True, some of the best scholarship has come from those
> who were biased against the book, but not dogmatic in
> thier bias.  This is actually true for those scholars who
> were biased toward the book as well.  Dogmatism has
> no place in science (or IMHO, in religion).

This\'ll be my last comment on the subject, as it is very far afield from
Traveller. I simply want to say here that not believing that the Bible is an
accurate historical document *does not* mean that one has a bias *against*
the text. Strauss, for example, was strongly biased toward the book, but had
little belief that it was accurate as a historical document. Bultmann was
similar. The allegorists of the 18th and 19th centuries believed in the
Bible as a history, but believed that those historical events were placed as
they were by God for the purpose of instructing man. Further, a belief in
the historicity of the Bible is not binary. There are many different shades
of such a belief, from those who believe that the Bible is a true and
accurate history from start to finish, to those who think that any
historical accuracy contained is sketchy, and not terribly important
compared to the "essential truths" that may or may not be found within.

One thing that\'s important to keep in mind that the very notion of a history
in antiquity was quite different from what would be called a history today.
Moral lessons and rules for living were frequently encoded within a
framework of a history.

PS: Personally, I think you\'re right on your interpretation of Theophilos.
