mass of the world itself from rotating, and not the hydrosphere, 
atmosphere or anything upon it. Considering how heterogenous much
of the planet is, why does the weapon not affect the people, the water,
and the air the same way it affects the planet? 

It would be bad to go from normally rotating to tidally locked all at once,
even without mile-high ocean waves and such.

SPI\'s _Freedom In The Galaxy_ had an orbital superweapon the
bad-guy Empire could use, called the Planetary Stabilizer. It could
instantly stop just the core (and maybe the mantle) of a planet from
rotating, throwing the crust of the planet into space as the thin crust
absorbed all that rotational velocity at once. Everything on the planet
dies, and everything in orbit (including the Planetary Stabilizer) gets
destroyed as well. As a bonus, the Imperial terraforming engineers
have a clean slate to work from, and it\'s probably in a habitable zone
of the star system to boot...once the orbit clears up a bit.

Walt Smith
