    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'ef583',
    'body' => 'Chris Seamans writes:
>From: Ian Ferguson <ian@vax2.concordia.ca>
>>Just my Cr 0.02: There are differences in power generating
>>plants around Terra, but most of these are either minor
>>variations on the same technology, or based on resources
>>that vary considerably in availability.
>Well, yes and no. The same idea may be at work with nuclear
>plants and coal plants, the two are very different animals.

	This would be an example of approaches based on differences
	in available resources.  Also, while the source of heat may
	be quite different, the turbines and electrical generation
	will be quite similar.

>>details of some foreign cars, but almost all of them use
>>metal frames, rubber tires, and internal combustion
>>engines.  That despite the wide range in environments in
>>which these vehicles must operate.
>I know you said "almost all", but if you head up north where
>there\'s a good deal of snow and you\'ll find lots of vehicles
>which use a combination of skies and treads, not rubber tires.
>These vehicles fill the same role as cars, but they\'re not cars.

	Yup, but space is mostly the same wherever you go.

>To go a step further than that even, Buckminster Fuller designed
>the Dymaxion (sp?), a three-wheeled car that was quantifiably
>better than most cars of the time, but an unfortunate accident
>caused funding to dry up. While the Dymaxion was not radical in
>the sense that the difference between, say, using solar power on
>a starship and using fusion power would be, it\'s still a design
>which is different enough to be notable.

	I\'m right with you here.  I try to work in minor differences
	in tech, novel approaches to using the same tech, etc.  It\'s
	just that if your neighbour has starships that are demonstrably
	superior in every way, I expect that eventually you will adopt
	that technology.  Just how much of a time lag there is may be
	subject to debate.

>To stick with automobiles as an example, even with very similar
>technology, cars themselves can come in a variety of different
>shapes and sizes. Sometimes, as with the popularity of compact
>and sub-compact cars, the change is a result of *function*, while
>at other times the change is purely a result of aesthetics. Take
>a look at the rise in popularity of the SUV among America\'s
>"soccer moms".

	I agree.  This should be the most fertile ground for 
	generating differences in starship designs.  Of course, even
	Imperial designs should vary considerably (Presumably 4 dtons
	is some sort of minimum for staterooms, but larger ones could
	be installed. If one wished to complicate the rules further,
	one could introduce drives that are cheeper but have lower
	performance, or some saving in tonnage for skipping grav=plates
	in the hallways).

>To further complicate issues, you\'ve got things like motorcycles
>on the roads as well, which look and feel very different from
>automobiles. If everybody in America started to drive motorcycles,
>for whatever reason, the country would look and feel quite different.
>So, even using the same core technology, you can have any number of
>permutations which, in most cases, are functionally different in a
>quantifiable way.

	I am in complete agreement.

>These are above and beyond *mere* differences in tech levels.

	Yup, a whole \'nuther kettle of fish.

>One thing that\'s interesting, which nobody has mentioned yet,
>which is not surprising given the rational and optimization-happy
>nature of this list, is that something which may be functionally
>and quantifiably better may be, for whatever reason, unpopular, or
>the idea might not catch on. Look at the Betamax / VHS brawl, as
>an example,

	Consumer goods are driven by a number of things, not least
	of which is standardization.  There is no doubt that this
	consideration would influence the use of technologies, but
	there are limits.  Can you imagine an airline insisting on
	using propeller-driven aircraft for transatlantic flights?
	At best, a very small market might be found for \'nostalgia\'
	flights, but jets are the way to go for long-distance
	travel.  The fact that prop planes are still practical for
	short hauls does not mitigate this.

<snipped>
>Fax machines owe their popularity in the 80s and 90s not to their
>being "better" than other forms of technology,
<snipped>

	I don\'t follow this.  To what other forms of technology are
	you refering?

>So, even on a single planet it\'s quite possible to have many
>different approaches to a problem. People\'s priorities can also
>be very different. While many on this list may lean toward
>optimization, most people *don\'t*. Tradition and industrial
>inertia are very powerful forces, even for those of us who aren\'t
>Vilani.

	Agreed, but I still don\'t see radically different technologies
	being dominant in different areas on Terra.  Sailing vessels
	are not widely used to transport goods.  Nor are derigables.

>In some cases, even very brilliant people can\'t think far enough
>"outside the box" to see that there may be a different way of doing
>something. The rise in popularity of "alternative medicines" in the
>West is a good example. Acupuncture, which just came up on the list
>in another discussion, is quite different from other methods of
>dealing with certain medical problems.

	Hmmmm... let\'s not go there.

>Similarly, the difference between the therapy dominated field of
>psychology and the empirical approach of psychiatry are really
>very different. I could go on and on, but I think that I\'ve made
>my point. ;)

	Me too.  ;)

Peez
