    'ts-index' => '1999-12-02.ef590',
    'body' => '- ---- Jason Kemp <Jason.Kemp@tdh.state.tx.us> wrote:

> What would happen if you could suddenly stop the world from spinning 
> on its axis?  Assume that all physical laws remain intact, beyond the
> one exception that someone or something could stop the Earth, or a 
> planet of your choice, from spinning.
> 
> First, the obvious answer that most people come up with is "Everybody
> falls down."  Yes, and so do buildings, vegetation, certain terrain 
> types, etc.  Suddenly the world stops, but inertia keeps you going at
> an incredible rate.  (My best friend quoted something around 900 
> miles per second, but I don\'t have the figures to back it up.  
> That\'s one hell of a skinned knee.)

My rough calculations indicate a more "sedate" rate. On the equator,
the circumference of the Earth is 24854.848 miles, give or take. The 
Earth rotates once in about 23.933333333 hours. So I figure the 
speed at close to 1038.503398 miles an hour. 

Unless I am totally offbase. <g>

And as you move away from the equator, the speed will drop. At the 
poles, the effect would be almost negligible. 

> Creatures and/or technological devices in flight would be tossed, 
> tumbling, through the air in the direction of the previous rotation 
> of the planet as the atmosphere suddenly scoured the planet\'s 
> surface, continuing to move that direction due to inertia as well.  
> Assuming that aerodynamic flight could not be reestablished once the 
> device starts flipping nose over tail, wing over wing, in a chaotic 
> tumble, most of these devices would probably crash.  I\'m not sure how
> well gravitic devices could recover from the disorientation of being 
> slammed by an atmosphere that was suddenly moving at the planet\'s 
> former rotation speed while the planet has stopped.

I am not so certain that craft in the air would be affected so badly.
The air around the craft would still be going the same rough speed 
in relation to the craft. The ground stopped, not the air or the craft.

The ground would whiz by though and flying objects would be a hazard.
That and mountains. <g> The effects would be more pronounced near 
the ground.
 
>  One of the effects of this would be the pushing of the planet 
> outside it\'s former plane of orbit about its primary/star.  For 
> Earth, that means that the world would start moving in a northerly 
> direction, out of the plane it used to orbit in.  Someone on the 
> south pole at the time the world\'s rotation was stopped would be 
> launched into the air, as the world started moving north out of the 
> plane of revolution at a high rate of speed, relatively.  Someone of 
> the north pole would be slammed to the ground at a relatively high 
> rate of speed, for much the same reason.  (This is according to my 
> friend.  I personally have doubts on this point, at least as far 
> as the person standing on either pole being so dramatically 
> affected by the shift in direction of planet movement.)

North? If it moves out of its orbit at all, which I will have to 
think about, I would expect that would change perpendicular to the 
actual plane of that orbit, ie the equator. Thus, no matter what 
direction, in or out, it would depend on where things were in the 
day/night rotation. I do not have any facts on if the rotation of 
the earth adds or subtracts from it\'s orbital period but I would 
feel safe in saying that it does not add/subtract enough to change 
the orbit very much at all. Everybody? Am I off base on this?
 
> My apologies if you do not find this an interesting diversion or
> thought exercise, at least momentarily.  I now return you to your 
> regularly scheduled thread of choice, already in progress.

I like the mental challenge that this one provoked. Thanks.
 
Terry

