    'date' => 'Thu, 2 Dec 1999 12:13:20  0500',
    'body' => 'Some ways I try to make ships of different races (or even regions)
vary from each other: customs and regulations. Here are some examples
of ways I\'ve used to make ships different, from different regions,
species or organizations:

All vessels above 200dtns (or some other arbitrary limit) must have
sufficient lifeboats to carry all passengers and crew, or cannot be
licensed to carry passengers in Imperial(or other) space.

All jump-capable ships, even small ones, must be unstreamlined
to prevent their landing on planets[1], or because the particular variant
of jump drive technology used behaves badly when exposed to 
planetary landings[2]. (I have a 200dtn, jump-1 trading ship design that
carries a 95dtn shuttlecraft for when I was experimenting with this idea.)

Misjumps are to be feared. Only the most desperate crewman will serve
on a ship unless it has sufficient low berths/emergency low berths
available at all times to allow everyone to go into hibernation in the rare
case of a misjump to interstellar space or a fuelless system.

Passengers with criminal intent are a very serious threat to the safety
of a starship. Passenger areas are on seperate decks, and are widely
seperated from areas containing any important ship functions. There are
no vital areas a crewman needs to access during flight that require a 
crewman to enter the passenger areas, unless the crewman is specifically 
seeing to passenger needs. The passenger area probably also has 
it\'s own exterior access (airlock or small craft dock), so the passengers
can board and disembark from the ship without ever entering most of it.

No one boards a starship unless they are in the same service or company
as that operating the starship, or are there as allies of the starship
operators (such as contract employees or hired specialists). There is
virtually no distinction between passenger areas and crew areas, and
"passengers" are usually given appropriate shipboard duties during
the voyage.

While most starports have sufficient support craft, no serious merchant
vessel will place it\'s cargo handling ability entirely in the hands of each
planet\'s shuttle service. Nearly all merchant vessels will have their own
small craft, with at least some ability to transfer passengers and cargo
from orbit to planet. Your High Passengers want to disembark *now*, not 
when the local shuttle pilot strike is over. Also, if enough merchant
vessels have some small craft capability, it will help control the power of 
each planet\'s shuttle pilot groups to increase rates.

Some manufacturing, engineering or facilities limitation places a
maximum practical size on ships that can be landed - perhaps 1000dtns
or so. Even when the limitation is overcome, it may be some time
before shipbuilding customs or common landing facilities make larger,
landable ships a useful design philosophy.

Just some ideas...variations in design philosophy, rather than 
strictly the technology involved.

Walt Smith


[1] Say the polity in question is surrounded by worlds that lack jump
drives, and wants to ensure that a jump drive will never be landed
on a planet and seized.
[2] In Alan Dean Foster\'s Flinx(sp?) series, no ship with a stardrive
could land on a planet without wrecking the drive and a good chunk of
the planet. Everyone knew this to be true. Then the hero met some
aliens who didn\'t know it couldn\'t be done, and their mathematical
prodigies made it work, but only made one for Flinx...
