    'index' => 'ef626',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => '<Steve>
  While we\'re on the subject (or at least close), would anyone care
to explain why SF games almost always assume that anti-matter is a
power supply system that doesn\'t need an ultimate source of fuel?

  I mean that presumably there\'s a honking big fusion reactor (or
other cheap power source) running as cost-efficient as possible a
conversion method, but AM itself as a resource is absurd, unless
you postulate that suddenly at TL x it becomes easy to obtain (?!).
</Steve>

As you point out, the problem is not using antimatter.  We could probably
assemble an AM-using plant today.  The problem is obtaining the fuel.  I
think the notion is that at some point you gain the capacity to magically
"flip" the charge of matter and thus obtain AM cheaply.  This violates
conservation of energy I think, but then that\'s why AM power is generally
in the "glittertech" domain.

The thing is that anything that can produce AM the "old-fashioned way"  is
going to be producing gobs of energy already, so you might as well use
that as your power-plant technology (unless there are limitations to use
aboard ships, such as size, radiation or whatever). 

One possibility is a dyson sphere[1] of close-orbitting solar power
satellites converting significant portions of a sun\'s output into AM.  In
this case, you\'ve got massive infrastructure producing AM, which is then
used in ships and other installations because of it\'s small size and high
efficiency.  This is akin to the situation with gasoline today. 

Charles C.

[1] Note that I mean a Dyson sphere as originally conceived:  A bunch of
seperate structures, not a single solid structure.
