    'topic' => 'Medicine in the 3I (longish)',
    'body' => '* Overview
The Imperium exists because of, and to maintain, interstellar trade.
Certain overarching standards are in place to ensure that trade between
the 11,000 member worlds can continue smoothly. These are enforced by
the Ministries of Commerce and Justice, through the Starports Authority
and the Imperial Navy, as well as ministerial personnel.
	Provision of health services is an essential adjunct to development and
therefore the fostering of trade.
	As the only Imperium-wide organisation with the necessary
infrastructure, the Medical Branch of the Imperial Navy has been charged
with other roles, beyond that of supporting its personnel and their
dependents. It :-
	- drafts disaster plans in consulation with local governments, leading
to the databasing of medical resources available in the area ;
	- compiles the section of the Imperial Data Package dealing with
pharmaceuticals (IDP-P) and medical instruments/therapeutic procedures
(IDP-MI/TP) ;
	- in consulation with local medical authorities, pharmaceutical
companies, the Technical Services Office of the IISS and the Navy\'s
Technical Branch, controls the addition to, or deletion of items from,
the IDP-P and IDP-MI/TP ; and
	- advises the Ministry of Commerce and the Starports Authority on
appropriate standards of handling, storage and transportation for
non-procedural items (the conduct of procedures being the province of
professional bodies and the occupational health and safety regulators).

* The IDP-P
"Pharmaceuticals" are defined as : "Those chemical compounds, tailored
organisms or nanotech constructs designed to produce a predictable,
specific effect or effects when administered to a given organism by the
route(s) and in the dosage range(s) specified."
	Agents are listed in alphabetical order, by system of action.
All have an approved IDP-P name ; the most common brand names and
manufacturers are then listed, as well as the Tech Level of
availability.
	The chemical structure of the compound, or hyperlinks to details of the
genetic sequence or ultrastructure of constructs, are then listed.
	Subsequently, all records contain the following fields :-
- - Origin of Agent
- - Pharmacodynamics (what the substance does to the organism)
- - Pharmacokinetics (what the organism does to the substance)
	Data is given in the categories above for all of the major races, and
most of the minor ones.
- - Known Adverse Reactions, Interactions, Precautions and
Contraindications to Use
- - Indications for Use
- - Dosage and Route of Administration
- - Presentation, Handling and Storage Data (including Materials Safety
Data).
- - Typical unit cost, in Imperial Credits

* The IDP-MI/TP
A "medical instrument" is defined as : "Any organism or artefact
primarily used to facilitate diagnosis, monitoring or therapy, that does
not fall into the definition of a \'pharmaceutical\'."

(So a scalpel is an instrument, whereas intravenous contrast agents are
pharmaceuticals).

Entries are divided into the following fields :-
- - Device name :- IDP standard, then eponymous or brand names with
manufacturer are listed. (Room for confusion exists. Robert\'s vs. Dever
retractors? DeBakey or Kielland\'s forceps? etc.)
- - Device type :- diagnostic, monitoring or therapeutic
- - Tech level of manufacture
- - Indications for use
- - Precautions and Contraindications to Use
This field also includes information about the sensitivity and
specificity of diagnostic and monitoring instruments. 
- - Presentation, Handling and Storage Data (including Materials Safety
Data).
- - Typical unit cost, in Imperial Credits

A "therapeutic procedure" is defined as : "Any course of action whose
primary purpose is to identify, limit the progression of, or cure,
pathological processes taking place within a patient, either with the
assistance of medical instruments or via the intercession of the
treating clinician(s) alone."

Entries are divided into the following fields :-
- - Procedure name, type and tech level are as per medical devices.
- - Material requirements (divided into a hierarchy of \'optimum safety\',
\'average risk\', \'emergency/field\').
- - The \'Indications\' section discusses the risk-benefit profile, as well
as the assembled evidence for or against the procedure. Evidence is
ranked according to the usual hierarchy of \'benefit proven via
meta-analysis of large randomised controlled trials\' through to \'on the
strength of a few case reports in the [relevant] literature\'.
- - Precautions and Contraindications

* Searching the IDP-P (-MI/TP)
Any reasonably sized starport (III/C+) should contain the relevant
databases (or the system\'s computer networks, if relations with the
Imperium are cordial).

* Illicit pharmaceuticals
Normally the Imperium does not intervene in the traffic of these
materials, except at the level of the local Starport Authority. Each of
these is advised by the government(s) of the system what items or
substances cannot cross the extrality line.
	However, the right to search and seizure where threats to the peace are
perceived to exist (e.g. bioweapons) is reserved by the various Imperial
agencies.

* Who Can and Can\'t Heal
Local medical authorities nominally regulate this, via licensing and
other requirements (exams, mandatory education, nepotism, bribes, etc.).
Through arranging reciprocal treaties with similar groups in
neighbouring systems, some uniformity of practice quality may exist
across subsectors, or even sectors.
	The latter situation is more likely, given the presence of the IN\'s
Medical Branch and the information it has compiled.


Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
