    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Likewise, Portland, Oregon, really is six cities under a municipal
> government. (And crossing at least two counties). I don\'t recall seing
> local police there (Portland Metro, plus two sherrifs departments, those
> I\'ve seen). Detroit is an extreme of the US system.

Not really. It may have been such at one time, but it\'s definitely
*one* city now. East Portland, St. Johns, etc survive only as
neighborhood designations. 

We do have such oddities as the City of Maywood Park, where an area
about 6 blocks on a side incorporated so the could force the re-routing
of I-205 (which would have gone right thru the middle of their
neighborhood otherwise). 

Portland has annexed several smaller suburbs in the 20+ years I\'ve
lived here. And had a few others tell them to go to hell. There\'s even
a chunk of "unincorporated" territory that\'s successfully fought
annexation at least twice. Even though they are now *surrounded* by
Portland! 

Portland isn\'t going to expand much farther, except in a couple of
areas, simply because it\'s now up against former suburbs that are now
big enough to fight back. Gresham, Beaverton, Tigard, etc. 

The Police are definitely *Portland* police. The Sherriff\'s departments
are Multnomah county, Clacakmas county, and Washington County. Though
I\'m not sure if any of Portland is *in* Washington County. I\'d have to
check a map to be sure, but I think they finally "adjusted" the city &
county boundaries to be more rational. 

We *do* have an "agency" that spans the entire Metro area. But it
doesn\'t "do" police functions. Metro tends to go more for things like
land use regulations.

- -- 
