    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>   While we\'re on the subject (or at least close), would anyone care
> to explain why SF games almost always assume that anti-matter is a
> power supply system that doesn\'t need an ultimate source of fuel?
>
>   I mean that presumably there\'s a honking big fusion reactor (or
> other cheap power source) running as cost-efficient as possible a
> conversion method, but AM itself as a resource is absurd, unless
> you postulate that suddenly at TL x it becomes easy to obtain (?!).

True enough. Unless (until?) you find large amounts of *natural*
antimatter, AM is "merely" the most efficient known method of *storing*
power. 

Actually, baring some major breakthroughs, it\'s not even that
*efficient*, not if you consider the amount of power it takes to *make*
a given amount of AM. It\'s just the most *concentrated* storage. 

In Traveller, we know of at least one source of "natural" AM. 

