    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> Not quite.  Tidally locked worlds still rotate, they just do it in step
>> with their orbital motion.  Of course if you want to specify that the
>> world has been reduced to a tide-locked state from a state of
>> rotating every 24 hours or so, the effects would be almost the
>> same.
>
> Point conceded.  In the event of a true cessation of rotation, does 
> that mean, then the the day now equals the sidereal year?  Still has 
> nasty effects on the ecology and weather patterns, but after the 
> melting of most of the planet\'s surface, what does it matter, right?

Since rotation is an *absolute* rather than a relative (that is,
unlike velocity, all observers will agree on your rate of rotation, as
adjusted for their time rate), "stopped" means stopped with respect to
the entire universe. 

Thus your your sidereal rotation period will be *zero*. Your year will
be the same as your solar day.

