    'date' => 'Fri, 03 Dec 1999 15:39:09 +1100',
    'body' => 'I was not going to comment on this (but heck, worse wastes of bandwidth
have been posted to the list).

Leonard Erickson wrote :-
> > Any significant installation would be damper screened to prevent \'fun
> > with nukes/nuke dampers\' in any case - because nukes are so common.
> 
> Which leads to fun when a VIP from a TL-9 world enters the building and
> suddenly keels over. Why? You neutralized the Pu in the powerpack for
> his heart pacemaker! (real technology, folks!)

Some real world data, folks.
	RTG driven pacemakers were proposed in the late 1960s. An occasional
few examples were built in the following decade.
	Improvements in the energy density of chemical batteries, plus better
understanding of the electrical requirements for a pacemaker (only
microampere currents are required), have led to the situation today,
where said batteries get electively changed every 2-4 years.
	Clinical expertise has also developed over years of long use to the
point where pacing is a last resort treatment. Cardiac disease severe
enough to mandate pacemaker placement is nasty. It is equivalent to
heart failure, which has a long term outlook comparable to many
malignancies (e.g. 5 year survival rates of about 20%).
	Some improvement on this grim statistic is being made as our
understanding of ischaemic heart disease and the best ways to prevent
and treat it grows.
	So on risk-benefit grounds, having a chunk of plutonium in your chest
is unlikely to shorten your life expectancy from radiation-induced
malignancy. In any case, such a power source hasn\'t been necessary for
at least a decade for this application.
	Pacemakers can be interfered with by other things, which will probably
be even more common than nuke dampers in tomorrow\'s built environment.
Any sufficiently powerful source of EM interference will
cause pacer failure, either via induced currents or heating(!). MR
scanners, diathermy machines and multi-watt radio transmitters are 
example troublemakers.

	Our VIP should have medical backup (either imported or provided by the
host) in order to provide prompt, competent resuscitation in the event
of pacemaker failure (ranging from resetting the pacer with a magnet to
external pacing to circulatory assist
devices and low berthing, etc.). Anything less would be criminally
stupid, especially for such a simple and common emergency.

Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
