    'body' => 'In a message dated 12/2/99 6:03:38 PM Eastern Standard Time, 
robocon@idx.com.au writes:

> Jon, have you a copy of two documents from the Missouri Archives which
>  may partly offset this effect? Namely, Harold Hale\'s discussion post
>  from 1995 which attempts to assign Real Universe(TM) nearby stars to the
>  sector map, and the algorithm for correcting dodgy canonical stellar
>  data?

Interesting.  I was already familiar with Harold\'s "real stars list," and for
local color I intend to point out some of the more famous stars in the
capsule writeups I\'m doing.

I wasn\'t familiar with his algorithm for correcting the stellar types, but in
fact I have done something similar "on the fly."  I\'ve converted all Type IV
and Type VI stars to V, for example, and I\'ve turned some of the white
dwarf stars into main sequence members (mostly M-class).  I also turned
M9 V stars into M8 Vs.  None of this was done particularly systematically,
but as a first approximation the results don\'t look too bad.  If any of the
playtesters howl in protest I can always go back and hand-tweak a
couple dozen stars to fit a more reasonable distribution.

On the other hand, I don\'t have as much trouble with having Earthlike
worlds around the tinier M-class dwarfs.  What I\'ve been doing is deciding
on a planetary climate and then computing the orbital radius from that.
I\'m not limiting myself to the old Book 6 method of having the orbits fall
into the fixed Bode sequence.  Those Earthlike worlds near M8 V stars
just orbit *very close in*.

(Of course, I\'m glossing over the fact that tide-locking causes its own set
of problems, but this is Traveller, after all. . .)

There\'s one world in the sector circling a D-class primary, but that world
isn\'t particularly Earthlike anyway -- I plan on writing it up as a "cryo-
world" with an ambient temperature not far above absolute zero.  And
a population in the tens of millions, of course :-).

