    'body' => 'Steven Hudson writes:
>>explain why SF games almost always assume that
anti-matter is a
> power supply system that doesn\'t need an ultimate
source of fuel?>>
Well, they do need fuel, but the real bulk is the
containment, not the fuel. One gram of anti-matter
contacting one gram of matter will give 1.8 x 10^17
joules of energy, a lot! Antimatter is produced all
the time by natural decay, as in uranium ore deposits
(or thorium, radium, etc), just very very little, and
it doesn\'t last long, soon bumps into matter and zaps
it and the matter into a burst of gamma rays. Small
amounts (a few atoms) of antimatter have been stored
in our time, but they require huge magnetic fields. 

Anyhow, the point is that a very small amount of
antimatter will keep you going a long time; the
aforementioned one gram of antimatter would keep a 100
MW reactor going for 57 years! (assuming 100%
efficiency, even at 5% efficiency you still get a
whole year)
Who wants to worry about refuelling with a gram?

However, I do wonder about those containment fields,
what if they fail? This suggests either unimagined
technology or another reactor giving power for those
fields. Suposing that fails... I guess this is why
anti/matter reactors aren\'t yet on ships until very
high TLs?:)


