    'body' => '> I give, what was the big deal about TNE that nobody liked it?  

	As usual, the number of opinios about TNE equals or exceeds the 
	number of people talking about it. IMHO, :

	Bad things:

	The rules used 1d6 as damage dice, which allowed characters to 
	absorb huge amount of damage before dying.

	Skill system... well... I just did not like it. We began to use
	CORPS system after first few TNE sessions.

	Good things:

	Damage rules include penetration value, which makes it possible 
	to design various low-penetration and high-penetration 
	ammunition. (shaped charges, "bean bags", etc.)

	Armor and damage was based on one set of rules, so that the same 
	amount of damage could be applied against a starship, vehicle or 
	a living creature. It is possible to calculate the amount of 
	damage inflicted by a falling rock, ramming ship, etc.

	The reactionless thruster was replaced with fuel-consuming 
	rocket engine. This change made it more difficult to accelerate 
	ships into ridiculous speeds.

	FF&S technology rules allows the design of a wide variety of 
	equipment with some detail. (some portions of FF&S are still 
	oversimplified)

	Brilliant Lances has enough detail to make starship combat 
	interesting. Since normal character skills are used in combat 
	tasks, a high-skill PC can make difference in some situations.

	Starship combat is done on long ranges. Since it is possible to 	
	hit a starship-sized target within 4 light seconds (40 hex), 
	space combat resembles more submarine warfare than aircraft 
	dogfights.


Luther Martin wrote:

> Has anyone out there played Brilliant Lances or Battle Rider?
> If so, what did you think of them? Good? Bad?

	BL is very good, but requires much preparation. It is better 
	suited for a small number of "small" or "medium" sized ships, 
	and the game bogs down quickly is large number of ships are 
	used.

	BR is simplified version of BL, intended for large-scale 
	battles. With some rule fixing, it was quite fun to play.

- -- 
      Antti Lahtinen                lahtinen@ee.tut.fi
      Researcher, MSc (Eng)         http://www.ee.tut.fi/~lahtinen
