> dadams@parracity.nsw.gov.au writes:

> > As well, Terrnas did not realised that Jump could be used for interstellar
> > travel. It was used for microjumping, and it took a lot of effort to use it
> > to go interstellar travel (supply caches et al).

> Which is weird, because you can always carry 2 jumps worth of fuel on a
> J-1 ship, which is enough to reach alpha centauri or barnard\'s star.

Not really when you look at the actual circumstances of the invention. The
team that developed Jump drives were infact trying to produce maneuver
thrusters. It was as if the Terrans were trying to build a better mousetrap
and ended up with a spice rack. So the Terrans get this niffty new drive with
no real idea of how it actually works. So they don\'t understand the theory
behind the extremely complex calculations involved in plotting a course
through jump space and instead base their calcuations on some rough and
ready rules of thumb based on obsevational evidence. Hence these
calculations become hidiously inaccurate as range increases, drastically
limiting the range of the early Terran jump drives. Only when their equations
increased in accuracy were they able to get anything like sufficent range for
interstellar travel. IMTU I limit 1st generation J-drive to around 30 AU, and
2nd generation (the ones used to reach the stars) to about 1 LY. Only when
they contacted the Vilani did they realise that their equations were totally
stuffed and finally get things right.


Andrew etc
