Exactly! I mean, can you really say something like

"discovered it by accident while mining the asteroid belt"

(which was most likely caused by the FInal War)? Sheesh!

Anyway, there is a certain amount of play here with regards
to how you interpert this little bit of canon.

Certain parts of the various Traveller books are obviously
meant to state absolute reality in the Traveller universe.
The amount of damamge from a shotgun, for example. Other
bits are obviously very much "in-game" and need to be 
interpreted as such. The description of events during the
rebellion, for instance. The description of these events
is meant to be subjective, biased and subject to interpretation.

Other bits are, however, much less clear.

Is the Terran discovery of jump drive meant to fall in 
the first category or the second? Obviously many of
you feel that it falls in the first - it\'s simply a statement 
of fact to help the ref understand the universe and set
the scene. I think it\'s in the second category - it\'s what
the characters, not the players, understand to be reality
and it\'s not necessarily 100% true. As a matter of fact,
I sincerely hope that no one runs a campaign where the
players know anything with 100% certainty. :)

While it may be true that you\'ll probably never invent
jump technology inside 100 diameters of a major stellar 
body, don\'t you find it a bit odd that in Imperial space
alone, out of the several dozen human races and the 
countless non-human races, only _2_ races actually
"invented" jump? While at the same time at least one 
other human race (and maybe other non-human races) actually
did copy jump drive off of an Ancient relic? What about
the infamous "black globe"? According to canon, the Imperium,
even at TL 15, in its most advanced research labs, can\'t
build the damn things - most of the black globe units
come from Ancient sites (there is a canon ref for this,
but I don\'t know it off the top of my head...).

And the fact that almost every race (except the Hivers 
and perhaps the K\'kree) had evidence of extensive Ancient
facilities on their homeworld? I mean, on Zhodane and
Vland there are basically gigantic buildings and broken
down Manga-style monster robots sitting there with gigantic
pictures of Grandfather on the side! Do you really believe
that hundreds of generations of humans just looked at these
artifacts and just said "eh, old junk - I think I\'ll go
mine some asteroids"????

Anyway, maybe I better stop before I start frothing at the 
mouth (again).
