    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'ef762',
    'body' => 'Kurtis\'s recent post on 3D mapping got me thinking about the issue of the
2D map in Traveller again.  The most appealing solution to this, IMO, is
to assume that the 2D maps represent "jump space" and that "real space" is
still 3D.  Some problems with this:

- -Canon discusses long-range STL colony ships that travel "coreward" from
earth to the Marches, suggesting a large-scale correspondence between jump
space and real space.

- -Canon also mentions several shorter-range phenomena, such as small
STL-based empires and the shock wave from the Darrian star-trigger, which
suggest a small-scale real-to-jump correspondence.

- -Mapping between 3D and 2D is complex, though there are (As I understand
it) and infinite number of solutions to the problem, mathematically.

So, what we need is a scheme that satisfies all these things and relates
2D jumpspace to 3D real space in a relatively simple manner.  A
possibility I was considering recently is that jump-space constitutes a
ripple-pattern with its origin at the galactic center. Picture a "rock
dropped in water" kind of ripple, but tighter, with a wave amplitude of
about 2 subsectors and a frequency of about 1 parsec.  Thus, you get a
picture of realspace by folding your sector maps up like an accordion
along the spinward-trailing lines between every odd subsector.  This would
only be the general pattern, there would be disruptions and "noise" in the
system (due to high-gravity objects like black holes perhaps).   

The advantage of this is that it allows jump space to move through normal
space and occupy all points in normal space.  It also explains why the
maps don\'t use directions like "galactic north" or "galactic south", as
these are relatively meaningless (since you\'re effectively travelling
coreward or rimward while travelling along these directions in realspace
anyway).  With regards to STL ships, these can travel by "cutting through" 
the maps, but still generally travel in the directions described.  It
works less well for short-range things, as the small STL empires should be
able to access worlds several parsecs away, but one can accept that they
"happened" to go after worlds along a plane in jump space.  Certainly this
requires less suspension of disbelief than a 2D star map.  The Darrian
disaster should also have affected worlds several subsectors over, though
one could shift cannon a little to say that either it did or that the
disaster only affected Darian itself, which then dragged their
