    'date' => 'Fri, 3 Dec 1999 08:36:27  0800 (PST)',
    'body' => 'Hi there!

Sorry for the delay in replying, I am just in the
process of rendering unto the modern medium of
computer that which has been in scrap paper form for
some years. When it\'s pretty much proofread, I\'ll send
it on. I assume you\'ll be able to handle an excel file
or similar...

I\'ve not read the traditional traveller books. As I
alluded to in that post, I based it all on the rules
suggested in Gurps: Space. In fact, IMTUIIRT (In My
Traveller Universe It Isn\'t Really Traveller). I
wanted a different, grungier flavour to it all, more
like "Aliens" or "Outland."

The basic "science" works like this:

Two kinds of engines: reaction drives, requiring fuel,
and hyperdrives, requiring two big bursts of power,
one to enter hyperspace, one to leave it. These big
bursts are so big that capacitors are required, the
consequence being that most ships take a few hours to
get ready to jump, and because they need to recharge
can\'t use their h-drives to teleport just a few miles
(which would make space combats a nightmare!) The
calculations for a jump are complex, requiring several
hours on a computer, though they can be done ahead of
time, the last details at the last minute. 

H-space can only be entered far from a star\'s gravity
well, etc etc, thus there\'s a fair bit of travel time
involved in-system.

Average "speed" depends on the rating of the H-drive
(compared to the mass of the ship in real tons), but
most ships get 0.25 parsecs/day. Courier ships manage
ten times that, bulk freighters 0.05 parsecs/day.
Naval ships get 0.25 p/day because they don\'t give a
damn for expense, or the comfort of their crews (ie,
not much space left after engines, h-drives,
capacitors and reactors...)

Things in H-space cast a "shadow" in real space which
can be detected, and since H-space is not homogenous,
but there are easy paths and difficult paths (a bit
like wooded hills), and the ship\'s computer calculates
the "easy" path, ships tend to come out in roughly the
same area of space in each system. And so there exist
Inderdictor class Imperial Commonwealth ships which
can pull a "passing" ship out of h-space. Most
embarassing if you\'re smuggling arms to rebels.

I also use a 3-d starmap, just to keep things
interesting.

Kyle

