>From: "Kurtis Rodgers" <kurtis@fastlane.net>
>Subject: 3D Star Maps
>
>I\'ve been poking around with one of the "bad penny" Traveller issues, the
>star mapping system.  Certainly not one of the hot button issues, but one
>that pops up on the list occasionally in various forms (a 3D mapping thread
>appeared recently).  Every Ref who questions the artifice of the rectangular
>A4 subsector hex maps may wonder if there isn\'t a "better" way.  Of course,
>"better" depends entirely on what you value in a system.  In my opinion,
>anyone wanting to run a Spinward Marches campaign, for example, would be
>more than amply rewarded for accepting the old hex maps due to the wealth of
>available source material in that setting.  It certainly never bothered me
>in high school when I first played the game.  In those days, the paperwork
>required to use a three dimensional system, or even a simple non-hex
>determinate grid, was simply not worth the trouble.
>
>In some ways, mapping is only an issue if you contemplate the Way of the
>Heretic, and are starting with a relatively clean slate.  After looking at
>the existing map data, I decided that for my own campaign, I would need to
>redo most of a sector or two.  This opens the door to speculation about
>other changes to the mapping scheme.  Also, the casual power of the software
>at my fingertips today is quite a bit different than it was in 1980.
>
>I am familiar with the practical problems with attempting 3D star mapping
>for Traveller.  (Anyone who isn\'t should refer to the sidebar on page 47 of
>GT:First In for a good summary.)  Still, the idea holds some fascination,
>and has a certain \'cool factor\'.  Another way of thinking about this
>problem, aside from geometric issues, is the degree to which real-world
>astrography can be used.  When I create an Earth-like planetary setting
>(i.e., a fantasy world), the first \'world builder\'s handbook\' I reach for is
>a World Atlas.  There\'s nothing like using the real thing, at least in bits
>and pieces.  I am sure I\'m not alone in this practice.  I wondered what the
>results of applying Traveller jump travel to a \'real\' star map would be.
>
>["Go for it!" says the little red guy with the fork on my shoulder.  "It\'ll
>never work," says the bored cherub, opposite.  "A hopeless quagmire!"]
>
>So I decided to at least explore the possibilities of a 3D TU, roughly based
>on real astronomy data.  : P
>
>What would be the real practical problems, rather than merely the speculated
>ones that get discussed?  How \'dense\' would star travel be in this
>environment?  Do stars naturally occur in J1-2 mains, and are there really
>rifts or other distribution phenomena that might \'stretch\' out travel and
>political boundaries?
>
>Since I happen to have both tools and skills that can be applied toward
>these questions, I am spending a little time on it.  Unless I get a Big Yawn
>from the list, I\'ll share my results with the TML.  Anyone let me know if
>I\'m reinventing the wheel here.
>_____
>
>Source Data
>
>I\'m currently using the Hipparcos star catalog for my source data.  I have
>only imported the data from hip_main.dat file, which contains 118,218
>records.  A *very* few of these records lacked parallax data, and were
>discarded.  The rest were plotted into a Cartesian coordinates table, with
>Sol at 0,0,0.  A record was added for Sol at 0,0,0.  : )
>
>A destinations child table was compiled from the main Cartesian reference
>table.  Due to the projected processing time required for finding J1-6
>destinations for every star in the catalog (well over 30 hours on my P300
>server), I decided to limit myself (for now) to a sample set of data: all
>the catalog stars within 60 parsecs of Sol.  This comes to 9946 records, a
>very reasonable sample data set (just under 10% of the total catalog).
>_____
>
>Destination Counts
>
>In order to get a feel for Traveller-style interstellar travel in this
>setting, I am running queries against this database that count the available
>destinations from each star in the sample.  These destination counts can
>then be compared to those in the OTU (for amusement only - please, no
>wagering!)  : P
>
>For the purposes of this model, all stars are assumed to be useful refueling
>points, and thus potential destinations for star travel.  (This is *not* an
>assumtion I would make in an actual campaign.)
>_____
>
>Total Destinations at J6 or Less
>
>Let\'s cut to the chase and see just how bad the destination-inflation is in
>3D Traveller.  This result set is rather long, so I have snipped portions of
>it for brevity.  There\'s enough here to get a feel for the data.  The first
>result column is the count of destinations available to a star at Jump-6 or
>less.  The second column is the number of stars to which the destination
>count applies.  The third column is the percent of the total sample that the
>star count makes up.
