No apology needed.  There should be no dispute that
what you said is true.  A small amount of the legal
work that is done involves threats to life -- death
penalty work, some immigration/deportation cases, some
family law situations (spouse/child abuse).  A smaller
amount involves immediate threats.  So we tend to sit
and stew over problems, do research, talk to
colleagues, write letters and motions, etc.  So tv
totally mischaracterizes the length of time needed to
resolve legal issues.

>Medicine, especially in my current area of 
>employment, has lots of problems that need fixing 
>within an hour or two. In fact, most of them
>need solution within five to ten minutes.

And "need" is not a rhetorical device in those two
sentences.  If the problem isn\'t fixed, the person
with the problem may die or suffer some grievous
physical harm.  

Ob Traveller (you guys were waiting for the ob
Traveller, weren\'t you?):  I think tv is misleading
about the career of a space traveller.  Some problems
will have to be solved in minutes or an hour ("we have
major damage to life support systems"), but others
will take much longer ("if Ensign Smith makes a pass
at me one more time, I\'m going to report her ... or
accept it; I haven\'t decided").  We won\'t get rich
easily.  We won\'t all have cool spaceships.  Alien sex
partners will be plentiful, but they\'ll be really
weird.  

- --Glenn
