OK, I have been out for a while and (as I parsed my digests) figured this 
one would die quickly, however comma

There are many fine religious scholars out there approaching the bible from 
a number of angles. In my old department (Religion at the University of 
Michigan)a great deal of the Exodus story was being studied by a specialist 
in ancient Egyptian belief systems (looking for \'cross over\' during the 
Semitic residence in Egypt) and the Gospel of John was being studied by a 
Women\'s Studies doctoral candidate looking for evidence of the status of 
women in patriarchal cultures of the Second Temple aera and possible strides 
to improve their lot. The Chair of the Department was a prof of Archaeology 
and his assistant was a Comparitive Lit prof. And we (they and I) were 
managing the Anchor Bible Dictionary project, where each book of the bible 
was being studied by a specialist in that book, be they Christian, Jew, or 
Whatever. The Book of James (about 9 pages) is an 850 page volume.
So, the bible is probably the most studied work ever. To assume that 
everyone studying it is biased beyond objective reasoning fails the test of 
Occam\'s Razor.

ObTrav: A Scholar patron *really* wants a copy of the holy canon of an 
obscure world in an attempt to prove pre-Vilani interstellar contact. The 
characters arrive and learn that only someone who has undergone 30 days of 
complicated purification rituals (including dietary, behavior, and hygiene 
restrictions) can even touch the canon without serious backlash. And if you 
want to *buy* it!

