    'body' => 'In a message dated 12/3/99 4:31:29 PM Eastern Standard Time, 
rboleyn@paradise.net.nz writes:

> > The gist was that:
>  > 
>  > 1) I capped jump ranges at about 9 light-years, and assumed that this
>  > represented Jump-2.  I used a linear relationship between jump number and
>  > range, so that jump-1 was 4.5 light-years.  That kept the expected number
>  > of destinations reasonable (i.e. greater than zero, but less than ten or
>  > so).
>  > 
>  > 2) You won\'t get "mains" of jump-1 accessible stars.  With the range
>  > assumptions I made above, though, you\'ll get "chains" of jump-2
>  > accessible stars reaching in several directions outward from Sol.
>  
>  You mean like 2300AD?

A little bit more so.  The "jump range" in 2300AD was about 7.7 light-
years, and I found that a bit unsatisfactory.  With that range, the "arms"
are kind of thin, they tend to peter out at a certain distance from Sol,
and the path to some important nearby stars is very indirect.  Indeed, 
there are some good stars near Sol that are completely inaccessible
(61 Cygni and the Draconis-Cassiopeiae cluster, for instance).

Stretch the range out to 9 light-years and you get more direct access
to all the nearby stars, and the "arms" are thicker and more interconnected.
Better for the Traveller-like feel I was after.

- ----
