    'body' => 'Just to clarify a couple of points

<snipped web site details>
> From this I would interpret that while one hundred km3 of material was
> erupted, most of it didn\'t go "into the atmosphere" except in the sense of
> flying upwards or sideways a few meters.

I agree, although most of it went a hell of a lot more than just a few
metres, the Chatham Islands, which were covered  in a layer of ash 11cm
thick, are around 800km away.

> If a typical eruption speed was the  600-900 km/h described above,
>the highest altitude the debris could  reach would be 3000 m or so,

That was the speed of just the "liquid flow", not the speed of the fragments
ejected into the atmosphere, in other words that was the speed of the stuff
still in contact with the ground !

The airborne stuff, including the superheated steam, exceeded the speed of
sound (i.e more than 1km/sec or some 3600 km/h )

>so I\'d be interested to see the "other sources"
> suggesting several km3 made it into the stratosphere. (Elsewhere the
> website does mention a column 50km high, so some fraction does make it
> into the stratosphere.)

I _think_ this was covered in the following reference, but as I no longer
have access to it, I can\'t confirm. It definitely has a pile of further info
on the largest eruption. ( the 181AD eruption was a _lot_ smaller )

Wilson, C.J.N., 1993, Stratigraphy, chronology, styles and dynamics of late
Quaternary eruptions from Taupo volcano New Zealand. Phil. Trans. Roy. Soc.
London A343, 205-306.

> More fundamentally, how long particles persist in the atmosphere depends
> strongly on their size. Even if several km get into the stratosphere, if
most
> of it is pebbles of pumice, they\'re going to fall right back down again.

Actually, anything that get\'s into the stratosphere can stay up there for a
very long time, even quite large bits of debris, due to the effects of the
air speed at that altitude, and the temperature inversion layers.

> It\'s the ash and similar tiny particles that count; figuring out the ratio
of ash
> freed up by nuclear explosions/fires vs volcanoes is non-trivial

True, but it\'s also largely irrelvant, it\'s the amount of smaller particles
reaching the stratosphere that is importnat, not the overall amount of ash.

> and a direct comparison of material volumes isn\'t helpful.

It is helpful in that volcanoes are the only current evidence we have on the
effects of large amounts of ash in the stratosphere. In order to show that a
nuclear war is likley to cause a "nuclear winter", one has to show that it
is likely said nuclear war will inject _more_ ash into the stratosphere than
previous volcanic events.

Currently, the only direct evidence we have shows that in the case of
nuclear explosions only a very small amount of it ever gets into the
stratosphere, in fact in most of the atnospheric bursts carried out so far,
_no_ material other than steam reached the stratosphere.

While I agree there are a lot of variables, including the altitude of the
explosion, the nature of the ground, and the weather, there has yet to be
any real evidence that a nuclear war could create a "nuclear winter".

Cosmic scale events, such as asteroid impacts, have been shown to have
caused a "nuclear winter" effect, but they have much greater capacity for
injecting materiel into the stratosphere than nucleear weapons.

Frankie
