While I am not a volcanologist, just a sedimentary geologist, what I suspect
is being referred to in the "liquid flow" is the "glowing cloud" of
suspended pyroclasic debris and hot gases. There is a French phrase for it
but "glowing cloud" is the literal translation.  There are density flows in
the deep ocean called tubidity flows that represent an analogous phenomenon.
The concept is fairly simple, a dense liquid suspended and flowing along a
solid surface within a less dense fluid.   In the case of volcanoes these
density flows are "glowing clouds" which represent a dense "gas" flowing
within the atmosphere down the slope of the volcano.   There is little or no
friction at the interfaces of the flow, especially at the leading edge.
Picture an "air hockey" puck and you can get an handle on the concept.
Regarding their velocity over the surface of the earth...    well I do not
have any examples I can cite but it is my understanding that they can be
quite rapid and utterly devastating.

Dan
