    'from' => 'Glenn Grant neo@total.net',
    'body' => 'Kurtis,

Interesting data, even if kinda skewed by Hipparcos sampling criteria.

If you\'re sharing, I\'d be interested in receiving a copy of your star list
with coordinates.  Are the stars named?  I seem to recall reading (on the
Starmap mailing list) that the Hipparcos data didn\'t include star names,
just catalogue numbers - and not the same numbers used in Gliese, IIRC.

Something to consider:  on top of the red dwarfs missing from the Hipparcos
data, there are probably lots of rogue brown dwarfs out there between the
stars, unobserved by current telescopes.  Some astronomers believe that
brown dwarfs make up a good portion of the "missing mass" of the universe.
They might outnumber red dwarfs by an order of magnitude.  Many of them
would be paired with companion stars, but some believe there will also be
large numbers of brown-dwarf singletons.

If you can jump to these dim infra-red stars (and why not?), then the
number of J-1 destinations for each system will increase dramatically.

[BTW: (shameless plug) There\'s a terrific hard-SF story, "Halo" by Karl
Schroeder, set on a frozen planet orbiting a brown dwarf; it\'s in _Northern
Suns: The New Anthology of Canadian Science Fiction_ (Tor hc, 1999), edited
by David Hartwell and --gosh-- me.]

I\'d love to use 3D star maps, but I don\'t have a laptop for running a
CHVIEW map during gameplay, and 3D maps on paper present too many practical
problems.  You can\'t cover a large area without the stars and labels
overlapping each other.  The \'deeper\' the map, the worse the problem
becomes; I doubt you could fit your entire 60-parsec Hipparcos list onto a
single map.  So a 3D map has to be limited to a relatively small region of
space (max 7 or 8 pc across?).  And say you have several 3D maps of
adjacent areas of space; figuring out routes between the maps becomes a
major headache.  It\'s a pain just to visualize the 3D relationships from a
2D map, let alone work out jump routes.

I wonder if a possible solution might not be a program that could generate
a separate map (preferably scalable, in postscript) for each and every
star?  Each map would show all stars within, say, 7 or 8 pc of the star,
with all Jump-6-or-less routes from that star delineated and distances
marked.  Or it could generate a distance table for each star, listing the
distances to its reachable neighbors.  This would save a lot of time
working out routes during game play.

Does this sound at all do-able?  If I were a programmer, I\'d try to write
it myself.

Thinking out loud,

 + GMG +

               Glenn Grant  <neo@total.net>
_Northern Suns: The New Anthology of Canadian Science Fiction_
          Edited by David Hartwell & Glenn Grant
           now in hardcover from Tor Books
