    'body' => 'Date: Sat, 4 Dec 1999 15:17:07 PST
>From: shadow@ (Leonard Erickson)
>
>In mail you write:
>
>I seem to vaguely recall reading somewhere that due to folks like
>Roger, many writers and artists have a standard clause in their
>contracts to the effect that if the work isn\'t published within some
>period of time (2 years? 5 years?) it reverts to them.

Sometimes that exists, but it isn\'t really standard in the rpg game
industry -- I\'ve only ever seen it once, and that was when I wrote the
contract. Most game companies (for example, SJ Games) have standard
contracts that they don\'t like to change.  In addition, it sometimes _can_
take a while for a company to publish something, due to shifting
priorities. GURPS Book of the New Sun and
GURPS Space Atlas 4 are examples of books that were "sat on" for a couple
of years before they came out. The best thing to do is to get an advance
for the work, payable on submission of first draft.  This sort of
encourages the publisher to print it, since he has already put money into it.

- -david pulver
