    'index' => 'ef922',
    'body' => 'I wanted to find out if there was any truth to the Pepsi and American
Express stories. Unfortunately, I couldn\'t find anything that was concrete
on either one. However, all of the references I could find about Pepsi\'s
possible error cited the Chevy Nova / no va story as an earlier example of
this sort of pitfall, and that legend has been debunked for years now. As
far as the internet goes, I haven\'t found any reliable cites concerning the
other stories, which really causes me to doubt their accuracy.

Do keep in mind that the assumption that these stories make is absurd. Since
the dawn of the mass-market advertising campaign, multinational corporations
have relied heavily on local firms and expertise for advertising. They have
to, not just because of possible translation errors, but because it would be
too expensive not to.

Still, stories like these find a wide distribution in respectable
newspapers, magazines and even classrooms. The Chevy Nova legend was one I
heard in a high-school history class to illustrate what happens when
cultures clash.

I\'m surprised that nobody\'s mentioned Coca-Cola and "bite the wax tadpole"
yet.
