> I find this *highly* suspect, given that said star is *Sol*. If it
> isn\'t, either your database or algorithm is broken.

Your right.., it is Sol.  I hadn\'t actually bothered to look at the Sol
destination results yet.  Here they are - if they\'re wrong, then I
definitely made a mistake with my cartesian coodinates:

J1dest      J2dest      J3dest      J4dest      J5dest      J6dest
- ---- ---- ---- ---- ---- ----
0           4           3           15          18          26

> > Also, exactly 8 stars with 8
> > destinations means they\'re all clustered together, right?
>
> No. I don\'t think so. Each of the 8 stars that are available as
> destinations from 1 of those stars may have *fewer* (or more) stars
> available as destinations.

Yep.  Just sloppy/wishful thinking in my part.  Still, the idea of a
discrete J1 cluster of 8 stars could be intestesting from a worldbuilder\'s
perspective.

<snip>
> > Youch!  Over half the sample lacks any J2 destination at all.  This
knocks
> > the average down to 1.  Hmm.  This definitely needs more looking into -
to
> > make sure its not a mistake, if nothing else.
>
> It is a mistake. Since you aren\'t counting J-1 destinations you get
> this sort of "artifact". You need to be searching for J-1 destinations,
> J-2 *or less*, J-3 *or less*, etc.

Um...  <sarcasm deleted>  My intent was to show the \'J3 or less\' numbers
first, and then break that out into specific jump detail.  That was the
point.  The exclusive J1 & J3 numbers did not exhibit any such "artifact".
I still think its fishy given the plethora of J1 destinations.  It was my
gut feeling that either the J1 or J2 numbers had to be off, becuase they
don\'t make much sense combined..., and I now know why!

It turns out my J1 destination counts were royally screwed by a flaming f-up
on my part.  The algorithm that compiled the J1 destination counts neglected
to excluded the source star itself, inflating all the J1 counts by 1.  This
explains the ridiculous disparity between the J1 & J2 counts.  The numbers
for Sol did not reflect this error because I added those records with a
different query.  Thus the false uniqueness of Sol\'s lack of J1
destinations.  DOH.  Sigh.., a thousand lashes with a greasy wet noodle for
me!  : )  Sorry folks.

The bogus destination records are easily corrected (delete destinations
where source = destination).  Lo and behold, the corrected J1 numbers are
much more in line with the J2 counts.  I\'ll repost the result set in a
subsequent email.

> Another thing. Given the way Traveller maps things, you may hant to be
> looking for "Less than J-1.5", "Less than J-2.5" etc.

This is a very good point.  I should have specifically pointed out one of my
assumptions in measuring jump factors was Jump-1 equals *exactly* one parsec
or less.  Thus, a displacement magnitude of 3.00000001 parsecs would yield a
jump requirement of J4.  This, again, points to a need for finer granularity
in my destination analysis.  This is exactly the sort of thing this test
database was created to vette.  Thanks.

Kurtis
