What you do is create the tables so that you have the next page (assuming
same sizes) gover another table. Realistically, such tables typically can
be put about 20 entries per side on A4/Letter portrait, more with smaller
point sizes.
A sample of the index assuming the above table is max size...
A-E:G-K, A-E:L-P, F-J:G-K, F-J:L-P, K-O:L-P

How you use the index is to look up the lower ID\'d point, then, within it\'s
range, the higher ID\'d point, regaurdless of origin or destination. I\'ve
not done this recently, but I once did this for the 2300 NSL, and it was
rounded to nearest 0.1LY. It can be done in Excell or nearly any other
spreadsheet which can hold the whole of the dataset. Mind you, you wind up
entering the data twice... once across and once down. A fairly simple C
program can do it, too.

These type tables are used in StarWars RPG... but they do not correlate
directly due to background assumptions there...

You may want to set your data display to autobold the results.
