    'topic' => ' 3D to 2D mapping',
    'body' => 'A few notes on some replies:

>It would take an infinite 2d area to fill a 3d volume unless you have
>places that aren\'t accessible in Jump space.

This is not true. You can make one-to-one mappings between 2D and 3D 
space without gaps or overlap. There was a big post about this a few 
months ago.

>Sorry, I wasn\'t clear.  I don\'t mean that jump space is actually 2D,
>but
>that it is a "thin sheet", about a parsec or two thick that runs
>through
>normal space in a "crumpled" fashion.

You can do that, but it isn\'t necessary. You can declare that jump 
space really is 2D, if you can accept jump distances and directions 
don\'t correspond to real 3D distances and directions. Note that canon 
says they do.

If you are going to say that jump space is a "thin sheet", you don\'t 
need to come up with any weird mapping or crumpling. Just declare 
that only systems near a flat plane are accessible by jump. The 
distances and directions in jump space are exactly the same as those 
in real space, only there are a lot of real space systems that aren\'t 
accessible by jump.

- --
