    'topic' => ' OT: Must buy game',
    'body' => 'From: Matthew Bond <mgb@akira.swinternet.co.uk>


> IIRC, when Coca-Cola was first advertised in Mainland China, the slogans
> used translated back into English as "Let your teeth rejoice!", and "Bite
> the wax tadpole!"
>
> <g>

It wasn\'t the slogans that they used, it was the characters that made up the
name itself. In the 20s when Coca Cola was entering the market in China,
they had to sift through many possible character combinations to find the
right one to register as a trademark. They were trying to find a relatively
"neutral" combination, which was difficult, as the only character for "la"
translated into wax. However, Coke was a big hit while they were looking for
the right combinations, and local store owners made their own signs to
indicate that they had the soft drink. These translated into things like
"bite the wax tadpole" and other nonsense phrases.

It\'s important not to underestimate the intelligence of the Chinese here.
They understood these signs to read, phonetically, Coca Cola.

In the late 20s, Coke registered a specific set of characters as their
trademark. These characters can be translated, when together, as something
along the lines of "brings joy to your mouth". The folks at Coke are quite
proud of this fact, actually.
