    'body' => 'From: Alex Ingram

>I\'m in need of technical advice. I\'m attempting to break down and

<much snippage>

>Am I missing something. Thanks!

Off the top of my head, you\'re missing "primitive" communications
technologies which you may or may not wish to consider:

runners and messengers

homing pigeon networks:

These networks were an extremely common method for long distance
communication up until the introduction of the telegraph. However, pigeons
were still used in a military capacity after the invention of the telegraph.

Visual forms of communication:

Fire and smoke signals (the torch telegraph, etc)
Heliography (reflection of the rays of the sun [or moon] to signal)
Flags, kites and semaphore
Optical telegraphy

Aural forms of communication:
Stentors (shouters, wailers, etc. have been arranged in relay fashion)
Drums

There are many, many others. These are just off the top of my head.
