    'body' => 'Via electronic medium on 12/5/99 4:31 AM, mark.s.peace@dunelm.org.uk wrote:

> This is no. of destinations within 1 parsec but more than 0.1 parsecs. (This
> last restriction will hopefully stop binary companions showing as Jump-1
> destinations.)

Good thinking, but what about destination binaries? If you are at star A,
and stars B and C are within .1 parsecs of each other, won\'t your system
consider both to be valid destinations? And they could be a binary (or
trinary, given a star D.) Only way I see around it is to go through and
cluster all stars within .1 parsec and treat them as singular destinations.
Sounds like a heck of a lot of work.

On the other hand, First In seems to imply that companion stars can have
their own planetary systems. Depending on the orbital position of the main
worlds around either star, a single jump exit point may be equally
attractive to visit either world. but on other occassions you will need a
separate exit point for each world.

Just thinking, I wish you success in your endeavor. And keep posting, this
is very interesting.
