> it would take an infinite area to fill a 3D space folded.

> However, if you assume that the 2D plane has a certain thickness (>0),
> then it can fill the 3D space.

> /Jens \'Spacejens\' Rydholm

He is not mistaken.

The number of points in a three dimensional space is of the same order
as the number of points in a two dimensional space and the same order
as the number of transendental numbers (which is the number of points
in a straight line).

Unless space is quantised, when the order is reduced to the same as the
number of integers (I think)

What was also proved is that this fact is unhelpful since it breaks
a key concept in canon - namely that there is a correspondance of
jump number and coordinates with actual distance and direction in
normal space.

