He said "map", not "fill". The concepts are not the same in
mathematics. 

You can declare a "rule" such that any identifiable point in 3d space
maps to a *unique* point in 2d space. But doing so causes adjacent 3d
points to be non-adjacent on the 2d map. But there\'s still a one-to-one
correspondence between points in 3d space and points in 2d space. That
satifisies the conditions of "being a map" *mathematically*. 

