> Looking through literature that I have available these technologies
> and terminologies keep showing up (I know basically what they are but
> I am unsure as to exactly where they fit):

> POTS

Plain Old Telephone Service. Either analog with a 300-3000 HZ
bandwidth, or digital, with a 64kbps channel carrying ??-4000 Hz audio
digitized at a sampling rate I\'d have to look up. 

> Satellite 

Can refer to orbiting communications relays *or* it can refer to
equipment packages well seperated from the phone exchange (Central
Office) that carry out many of the functions of the switching gear. 

As an example, a lot of small towns are non serviced by "satellite"
mini-switches. These handle the switching for calls inside the town
without needing to relay anything back to the central switch, but calls
leaving town go to the central switch and are passed on (possibly to
another "satellite" switch in the next town over). This prevents having
to dedicate an entire 10,000 numbers to a town that is unlikely to ever
have *1000* numbers in use, and avoids having to run cables for *every*
line (or a high speed trunk line) between the twon and the switch.
Instead, the trunk only needs to be able to handle the maximum number
of calls entering/leaving the town at once. 

Think of it as a sort of glofified PBX.

> Laser/Maser, Infrared, Microwave Radio, Copper Cable, Wireless
> (Cellular), Lightwave (Fiber Optics, SONET, FDDI), VHF/UHF, ELF, AM/FM,
> TV/Video (CCTV/NTSC/PAL), ISDN, ADSL, T1, Global Networks (TCP/IP,
> SNA, X.25, Frame Relay, ATM), Enterprise Networks.

Here you have a bunch of communication "technologies" (delivery
systems, aka "hardware") mixed in with a bunch of communications
*protocols* (aka software/firmware). 

Laser, maser, IR, Microwave, copper cable, fiber optics are all ways of
moving a signal from point A to point B. "Point to Point Link technologies"

Cellular is a multi-point technology. 

ELF/HF/VHF/UHF are all "band designators" for radio transmission.

AM/FM/PM are modulation types, though to most folks AM refers to
"commercial broadcast radio" (In the US, in the 560 to 1600 kHz range),
and FM refers to "commercial broadcast radio" (in the US in the 88 to
108 MHz range).

TV is usually a broadcast commercial service in the VHF/UHF bands,
using 5 MHz bandwidth channels to carry visual and audio info. NTSC/PAL
and SECAM are the (currently) most popular "protocols" for encoding the
visual signals in TV. CCTV is "closed circuit TV"

I could go on, but the basic point is that you need to seperate the
*media* (what is "physically" carrying the signal), the protocol (how
the signal is "encoded" onto the media, and the *content* (what sort of
signal is being sent). 

Content is fairly simple. "text", sound, image. Morse code and teletype
are both simple "text". Fax is the simplest "image", and telephone is
about as simple as you can make "sound".

Media are fairly simple too. 
1. wire/cable
   a. copper wire
   b. optical fiber
2. EM signal
   a. Radio (ELF thru microwave)
   b. Light
   c. Gamma/X-ray?
3. other 
   a. sound pulses thru water
   b. meson beam pulses
   c. modulating gravity?
   d. ????

Protocols are just ways of getting content encoded appropriately for
media. And they can actually be pretty much *ignored* from the point of
view of both players and refs. The only time they might affect play is
if you had a situation where the ref *chose* to have the players run
into incompatible equipment. In which case either there had better be a
place where they can buy a protocol converter (like the ones you can by
so you can use a PAL VCR to display a PAL tape on an NTSC TV) or they\'d
better be willing to wait a *long* time while their electronics whiz
tries to get the specs on both protocols and *build* a converter. Which
should take weeks to months. 

> Possible future and fictional technologies:
> Meson, Tachyeon, Subspace, Proton, Warp, etc. Am I missing something.

These are all "media" (ie "what is being used as a medium of
communication"). 
