My input:

A communiucation system has to solve a few general problems including:

1. How are signals created, sent,and received
3. How management functions, like how point-to-point links are managed =
and how end-to-end links are managed

Part 1 is where the sci-fi stuff comes in. Meson beams, etc. You can =
basically send information by changing either the phase, frequency, or =
amplitude of a signal. The details of how this is done varies a lot from =
technology to technology, but the very same mathematics which governs =
one governs them all. If you understand the basics of electromagnetics, =
quantum mechanics (the Fourier analysis is rolled into this), =
statistics, etc, all of these technologies are very similar. So if you =
understand the workings of a TL9 *whatever* you can probably pick up the =
workings of a TL12 *whatever else* system without too much difficulty. =
Math is math, and Fourier Analysis is Fourier Analysis.

Part 2 are really part of the protocols used. The technology here is =
probably similar enough so that a person with experience with one =
protocol family can understand another family with minimal training (at =
most a few days). These skills are different enough that you could argue =
that another new skill needs to be created, say "networking," which =
covers this stuff. Although mathematics does not come to your rescue and =
make all of these technologies similar, the fact that you will always =
have the same problems to solve makes the solutions understandable to an =
experienced network engineer.=20

People who Part 1 things may know about Part 2 things, but don\'t need =
to. Similarly, people who do Part 2 things don\'t need to know or =
understand Part 1 stuff. I say make it two separate skills =
"communications" and "networking." This will make sense to players for =
at least the next 20 years or so.=20
