links are=20
managed and how end-to-end links are =
managed</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Part 1 is where the sci-fi stuff comes in. Meson =
beams, etc.=20
You can basically send information by changing either the phase, =
frequency, or=20
amplitude of a signal. The details of how this is done varies a lot from =

technology to technology, but the very same mathematics which governs =
one=20
governs them all. If you understand the basics of electromagnetics, =
quantum=20
mechanics (the Fourier analysis is rolled into this), statistics, etc, =
all of=20
these technologies are very similar. So if you understand the workings =
of a TL9=20
*whatever* you can probably pick up the workings of a TL12 *whatever =
else*=20
system without too much difficulty. Math is math, and Fourier Analysis =
is=20
Fourier Analysis.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Part 2 are really part of the protocols used. The =
technology=20
here is probably similar enough so that a person with experience with =
one=20
protocol family can understand another family with minimal training (at =
most a=20
few days). These skills are different enough that you could argue that =
another=20
new skill needs to be created, say "networking," which covers this =
stuff.=20
Although mathematics does not come to your rescue and make all of these=20
technologies similar, the fact that you will always have the same =
problems to=20
solve makes the solutions understandable to an experienced network =
engineer.=20
</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>People who Part 1 things may know about Part 2 =
things, but=20
don\'t need to. Similarly, people who do Part 2 things don\'t need to know =
or=20
understand Part 1 stuff. I say make it two separate skills =
"communications" and=20
"networking." This will make sense to players for at least the next 20 =
years or=20
so. </DIV>
