    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'eg017',
    'body' => 'Great explanations on this thread by Leonard and Luther.

Black ICE wrote:

> BTW, what is "phase modulation" (I assume that\'s what "PM" stands for),
> and how does it work?  I understand amplitude and frequency modulation
> (comes from having a SIGINTer as a roommate a few years back), but phase
> modulation just doesn\'t ring any bells with me.

How to explain PM in a mail message ?

AM the sine wave peaks and troughs get bigger and smaller.
FM the sine wave peaks and troughs get closer together and father apart.

Now think of a sign wave going through cycles as above but with no AM or
FM modulation, a single tone.

Phase modulation would have the above pattern change.

Draw one sine wave, and then draw the inverse of the sine wave next to
it. So you would have a peak, a trough, a trough and then a peak. This
is a phase modulation.

How do you detect it ? You either run another signal next to it which
doesn\'t change (a carrier signal) and look for phase variance by
comparing the two. Or you have a local ocolator which matches the
frequency of the wave and measure the phase variance compared to that.

Hope this helps

Ewan
