>> AM/FM/PM are modulation types, though to most folks AM refers to
>> "commercial broadcast radio" (In the US, in the 560 to 1600 kHz range),
>> and FM refers to "commercial broadcast radio" (in the US in the 88 to
>> 108 MHz range).
>
> BTW, what is "phase modulation" (I assume that\'s what "PM" stands for),
> and how does it work?  I understand amplitude and frequency modulation
> (comes from having a SIGINTer as a roommate a few years back), but phase
> modulation just doesn\'t ring any bells with me.

PM can be Pulse Modulation also. :-)

But phase modulation is fairly simple (in theory). 1200 bps modems
use it.

You know what a sine wave looks like, right? Well, with phase
modulation you "displace" the wave "sideways". So instead of a peak,
you are crossing zero (that\'d be a 90 degree phase change). 

It\'s a lot easier to explain when you can draw diagrams. 

