    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Back when I was a security guard, I worked at one of the 10,000 small chip
> fab plants here in Silly Valley.  One evening, I smelled a *strong* acrid
> odor coming from the locked fab floor.  (Geniuses who owned the place
> decided the security didn\'t need a key.. )
>
> Assuming the worst, I hit the alarm and start clearing the building.  By
> this time there is a visible haze in the air.  I get to one office, where
> this woman is sitting talking on the phone.  "Ma\'am, we have to evacuate
> the building."
>
> Icy stare.  "I\'m on the phone with *Europe.*
>
> All this while alarms blare, fire engines are pulling up.. dogs and cats,
> living in sin.
>
> I reach over her desk and hang up.  "It\'ll be there tomorrow.  This
> building I\'m not so sure about.  Are we going to walk, or be dragged out?"
>
> Needless to say they fired me soon after.  It wasn\'t a fire, just our AC
> pulling in fumes from an idling train nearby.

When we had drills (and some actual alarms) you did one of two things:

A. If the machine would finish the current "cycle" on its own, then you
   just walked away.

B. For systems that\'d keep right on cycling until they ran out of stuff
   in the "input", you might take a moment to move something so it\'d
   "run out" quickly and shut down.

And in Clean rooms, you\'d use the emergency exits, even if that meant
that everyone in the room would have to change to a new bunny suit
before returning after the drill. 

Given that we *did* have a few nasties, this was a good thing and well
worth any ruined product. One of the more memorable incidents was when
something went wrong in the acid etch lab and the "scrubber" on the
exhaust failed. We started getting NOx fumes dumped into the outside
air (bad) and sucked into the air intakes for the rest of the plant
(*really* bad!). 

Another bad one was when something went wrong and they managed to spill
a few cubic meters of TCE. Seems some idiot was filling a tank from a
supply line (we had all sorts of things piped *all* over the plant) and
stepped away for a "second". His supervisor sounded the alarm when he
saw liquid running under the door of the room....

