    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'eg033',
    'body' => 'Ah!  A new debate!  Did Grandfather wipe out ALL his kids,
and if not, where are they?

Our heroes, Maldaar and Skelli, Imperial Bureau of Investigation,
have stumbled upon an organ-smuggling cartel whose operations
involve harvesting the victims of the so-called Low Berth Syndrome
and shipping the carcasses to an interdicted Droyne world.  While
approaching the world and trying to figure out how to get on the
surface without being blown to bits in orbit, Maldaar snorts deriseively
when Skelli mentions the power Grandfather and the Ancients must
have had.

Maldaar:
"Well, the truth is, Grandfather is a myth cooked up by the Khazd
- -- a special projects arm of the Imperial-Zhodani-Darrian "Special
Assembly", itself an intersection of the most powerful Humaniti
industrialists and scientists in Known Space -- to mask the experiments
being done to human victims by certain political entities with certain
dark visions of a future race of uberhuman and oberhuman classes:
the Goverened (most of the people) and the Governors (the scientists,
industrialists, and military-political elements themselves).  All the so-
called evidence for the being known to us as Grandfather is planted
by these elements to direct us into thinking these devices and bases
were built in the distant past when really the work is only now starting
to bear fruit.  Black Globes are manufacturable, even by the Imperial
military\'s own press releases; what they\'re not saying is that they\'ve
known how to make them for a hundred years and have perfected
the technique.  The great Sighting off of Vilis in 1002 confirms that
there are a number of mercenary craft with these Black Globes, and
that\'s just 800-dton vessels by the way.  And don\'t forget the phantom
"Special Arm" of the Darrian navy.  They\'re telling us that this stuff is
1000 years old.  Isn\'t it more plausible to say that these ships are
simply state-of-the-art, special military technology whose existence
was leaked to the public in order to dispel possible concerns about
our governments hiding technology from us?  Our market-friendly,
sharing-is-good government can\'t be seen hiding anything that\'s
potentially beneficial: the megacorps and major worlds would revolt.
But now you can blame it on the Darrians\' secret police and their
crack squadrons.  Problem solved."

Skelli:
"What about Twilight\'s Peak?  Everyone\'s heard the rumors about
the far traders who found an intact base, complete with warrior
Droyne, neural disintegrators, and a planetary defense grid that
dissolved several Shivva cruisers?"

Maldaar:
"Skelli, you\'ve fallen into believing these rumors because they say
what they\'re told to say and we\'re trained to hear.  Why was the base
destroyed?  Why did the trideo images show a few hours of nothing?
How come the only substantial remains of this base is a crater filling
with metal-laced water?  These traders stumbled onto a government
operation of such sensitivity that the base had to be destroyed, the
traders implanted with false memories, and the Zhodani blamed just
to cover their trail.  That proves it was a psionics research base,
which shows that the Imperium isn\'t against psionics, it\'s just against
normal people developing the skills that would enable them to see
through the schemes of the Khazd."

Skelli:
"But they said it themselves, that the Droyne activated the auto-destruct.
And the planet has metallic dust which has been shown to have static
properties that well may have erased any footage shot."

Maldaar:
"It\'s a cover-up.  There were no Droyne.  You ever been on a Droyne
ship?  It looks like a bird cage.  Their repairs are done a few moments
before or after a part fails.  There\'s no way they could have invented
anything other than a mirror with little plastic beads to play with and a
beak sharpener."

Skelli:
"You\'re being rude.  And besides, research indicates that Grandafather
was a freak mutation with a hyperintelligent, hyperpsionic intellect.  Of
course he\'s nothing like the Droyne we know now."

Maldaar:
"That\'s because he never existed.  He was made up by a conspiracy
of powerful humans with the intent of galactic domination.  Look, if
Grandfather was such a hot dude, then why is there no real proof of
his existence?  Here, key over to your galactic dictionary and search
on Yaskoydray.  There it is.  NOW, do a search on the roots of that
name.  You won\'t find any.  No Yas, Yask, Yaskoy, and no Dray
or Ray.  All you have there is "Skoy", meaning "arrival", or "Koy",
which means "drive".  There is no Droyne name that doesn\'t have a
published meaning -- Droyne are particular about that -- and even if
Yaskoydray isn\'t his real name it would be the name given by Droyne
to try to explain him."

Skelli:
"Well I was told it means \'Grandfather\'.  Perhaps it\'s a long root."

Maldaar:
"It doesn\'t and it\'s not.  I suspect it is actually the code name for the
project that\'s being instigated under his name.  Check this out:
(Maldaar scribbles on his palm computer)
"Yaskoydray.  If you convert the Galanglic letters to numbers, with
\'a\' being 26 and \'z\' being 1, you get a sequence.  It doesn\'t look like
much at first, but I searched some physics databases at the University
of Regina and found that the combination matches a frequency used
in black globe research."

Skelli:
"Maldaar, they use a LOT of frequencies with research.  The probability
of any set of numbers matching a frequency must be close to 1..."

Maldaar:
"Which is what I thought too, so I cross referenced the Galanglic name
Yaskoydray with the Zhodani and Darrian names, and came up with
two *complementary* frequencies.  Add these three up and you get
a masking frequency used in stellar physics, particle acceleration,
energy storage, Imperial linear programming, you name it, it\'s there.
This is high-tech stuff, Skelli; it touches every part of our infrastructure.
Yaskoydray isn\'t a person, it\'s a *key*.  A key to a cover-up of
galactic proportions and significance, Skelli, and I\'m going to find out
what it is."
