    'month' => '12',
    'body' => '>> I\'d be tempted to take it all the way down to .001. That\'s 200 AU
>> (well, 203, but why quibble).
>
>Still too far. Depending on the speed the ships use, more than 7
>days travel time will make it a jump, and thus a worthwhile target.
>
>Terry


In a sense you\'re right.  You could take it right down to 0.0002 Parsecs.
(If I\'ve got the calculation right a 6G maneuver drive is then about as
quick as a Jump drive).  However, if you want to compare number of jump
destinations with the standard traveller maps then I\'d put it higher.  Upto
6000 AU (=0.03 Parsecs?) would count as the same system in Book 6.

Anyway, whichever I use I don\'t seem to get anywhere near as many binaries
as I thought so I\'ll have to have a look at the data and figure out whats
going on.

Another point:  What\'s the maximum range of Jump-1?  I would have tended to
assume 1.5 parsecs rather than 1.0.  (Otherwise a jump-1 ship couldn\'t
travel 2 parsecs in 2 jumps unless they were both exactly 1 parsec.)
However this doesn\'t tie in with the Solomani Rim data where Sol as no
Jump-1 neighbours - Alpha Cen is 1.3 parsecs I think.

Mark.
