    'index' => 'eg049',
    'body' => 'From: Glenn M. Goffin <gmgoffin@pacbell.net>


> Written "Nova" still looks enough like "No va" to convey that
>meaning.

With all due respect, that\'s stretching it. Remember, what\'s at question in
this particular legend is specifically that Spanish speakers *saw* the word
Nova on cars and literally translated in as "no go" and this went on to hurt
its sales.

Not to sound too politically correct about it, but the story does make
certain assumptions about the intelligence of Mexicans, or Spanish, or
whoever the story happens to be told about at a given time. The same
assumption translated into an English speaking would be absurd. Nobody goes
to Walmart expecting to buy walls, even though when pronounced it may sound
like "wall mart".

It\'s even more absurd when you consider the fact that Nova is a word in the
Spanish language. You don\'t even have to speak Spanish, you just need to
look at the borrowed phrase "bossa nova".

Would a Spanish speaker make a pun concerning the name of the car? I don\'t
doubt it. Would Spanish speakers be dissuaded from buying a car because they
read the name literally? I seriously doubt that.

> > The Chevy Nova did fine in Spanish speaking markets.
>
> I don\'t have contradictory or supporting facts.

"The truth is that the Chevrolet Nova\'s name didn\'t significantly affect its
sales: it sold well in both its primary Spanish-language markets, Mexico and
Venezuela. (Its Venezuelan sales figures actually surpassed GM\'s
expectations.)"

Barbara Mikkelson, San Fernando Valley Folklore Society\'s Urban Legends
Reference Pages (http://www.snopes.com)

She cites the following as her sources:

Paxman, Andrew.   "Literal Translations Can Sabotage Marketing Campaigns
Selling in a Second Language."  Business Mexico.   June 1993.

Ricks, David A.   Blunders in International Business. Cambridge, MA:
Blackwell, 1993. & ISBN 1-55786-414-4   (p. 35).

Letter from Frances R. Hammond, Director Worldwide Economics & Market
Analysis Staff General Motors Corporation   (5 August 1993).

Having read the Business Mexico article previously, I can say that it
debunks the myth quite handily, and if I remember correctly it provides
figures of Mexican sales.
',
