    'ts-index' => '1999-12-06.eg050',
    'body' => 'From: William F. Hostman <aramis@gci.net>


> Chevrolet did change the name for the spanish speaking markets after
> difficulties in mexico, according to Chevrolet\'s PA person, during an
> interview for a show on the history channel. Specifically, the problem was
> with the Mexican market.

With all due respect, if you can cite a source other than "an interview for
a show on the history channel", such as approximate airdate, the nature of
the show, the name of the program itself (especially if it was one of their
regular shows such as History\'s Mysteries / In Search of History, Modern
Marvels, etc.). Alternately, the name of the PA person would be extremely
helpful.

I\'m not asking this to be picky, but in my time as an amateur folklorist,
I\'ve heard lots of people indicate that a story was indeed true because they
saw it on television. A popular legend that was circulating at the time I
was in high school, for example, was that Snapple (or Marlboro) supported
the Ku Klux Klan with millions of dollars. Frequently cited as a source was
an episode of Oprah Winfrey where the CEO of Snapple or Marlboro announced
this proudly to the world.
