    'ts-index' => '1999-12-06.eg058',
    'body' => 'At 06:48 PM 12/6/1999 +0000, you wrote:

>Actually, I\'m not sure about this.  I imagine it will be in SF (I thought
>aficionados were supposed to balk at the term \'sci-fi\'?) *until* we\'re
>doing it for real and see how \'fake\' banking fighters look.  Kind of like
>how Buck Rogers spaceships looked ok at the time (I presume) and now look
>hopelessly dated (or even classic Trek computers etc.).

But everything comes around..

In 1993, Kirsten and I were sitting in the auditorium at the end of opening
ceremonies for ConFrancisco, that year\'s World Science Fiction Convention.
We who stayed had been promised an interesting development in space flight,
so the room was wall to wall NASA freaks.  As we had already seen Arthur C.
Clarke get eaten by the Sri Lankan Death Chihuahua, anything was possible.

This new break-through has called Delta Clipper Experimental, or DC-X.
After the project director gave us a quick history of project, the light
dimmed, and video tape rolled.

We saw a boxy little cone sitting in the desert, and heard the obligatory
countdown.  At liftoff, with very little fuss, the cone left the pad, went
up about 200 feet, and stopped.

Stopped!  Hung there.  As in the way that bricks don\'t hang there.  There
was this spaceship happily floating above the desert floor.  Doing things
that usually have you looking for the string or the bluescreen box, but it
got better..

After a few seconds of defying physics, the cone tilted a bit and started
drifting to the left.  Just like any other multi-ton balloon you\'ve ever
seen, until it obediently stopped at it\'s controller\'s whim.

Then it started to land, tail first, and God as my witness four little
spindly legs came out!  Don Stewart call your office!  Every 1950\'s skiffy
epic was avenged that day in the Nevada desert!  The DC-X comes down in as
little fuss as it ascended, and at that the crowd went nuts.  We were on
our feet cheering and clapping, demanding that they run the video again
(they did, nearly twenty times!) at which point Jerry Pournelle grabbed the
microphone and proclaimed:

"This is spaceflight the way GOD and ROBERT HEINLEIN *meant* it to be!"

Which sent us off again.  There wasn\'t a dry eye in the house as we watched
this two minute long tape.

I had the chance to speak with one of the McDonnell-Douglas reps, and he
asked my why we had had such an emotional reaction to what was in reality
just an initial test?  "Because it\'s real" was the best reply I could give
him.

So don\'t be so quick to discard those cliches of yesteryear.. Today I saw
an add for a cellphone you wear on your wrist...just like Dick Tracy\'s.
- -- 

