    'subj' => 'Re: 3D to 2D mapping',
    'from' => 'Kyle Schuant kyle3054@yahoo.com',
    'body' => 'You can map it, easily. In my first sci fi game I
gmed, when I had no copies of traveller to either
confuse or inspire me, I simply set one star as the
zero point, and plotted out the others on the page
(giving their co-ordinates as +/- X parsecs coreward
from capital, +/- Y parsecs spinward from capital.
Then, next to the system names I put a number, +/- Y
parsecs above or below this plane. Yes, the choice of
what is plus and what is minus is completely
arbitrary, but so what? SO is longitude and latitude,
having 360 degrees in a circle, the centigrade scale,
etc. It\'s all arbitrary, but so long as everybody
knows the arbitrary rules, it doesn\'t matter. 

By old Pythagoras\' rule, you can easily find the
distance between two stars. Yes, Jump-x getting to how
many stars? would be a problem. But I never had that
problem, because the star drives I hypothesised would
let them travel as many parsecs as they liked, it just
took longer, and the greater the distance the greater
the chance of misjump. And they could jump to emty
space if they really wanted to (and oftne did to
escape pursuers, a la millenium falcon).

Of course, the PCs themselves will use some different
system, but just as we don\'t know how their jump
drives actually work, we don\'t have to know the exact
astrogational system used by them. 


