Kyle laughs and responds:
Not quite! But a veteran of fighting... and I know
that the one thing not shown in that movie, the one
thing that no movie will _ever_ show because it drives
a rusty salt-encrusted blad into the heart of all our
myths of our warrior past, is that most soldiers never
fire directly at the enemy. They do their damned best
to avoid it. 

Instead of eight guys fighting, you would have had
maybe two of them firing, another couple "Oh, I\'m just
loading magazines for him," another couple pointing
out targets, "quick, shoot him, Joe!", one patching up
wounds, and another one running messages. But in this
movie, they were all killers, except for the wimpy
translator, who only shot an unarmed man, and his not
killing was depicted as cowardice.

Guys pointing out targets or loading magazines
obviously are as morally reposnsible for the killing
as the firer, but it doesn\'t _feel_ the same. Believe
me.

It\'s not cowardice, but that\'s how audiences would
view it. Most men never fire, or just fire around the
enemy, to scare him off. If an officer is standing
right next to them, shouting, "shoot, damnit!" they
will, but as soon as he goes away...

This has been true for all armies through history, all
that we can study at all, or have records for. It\'s
just damned hard to look another human being in the
eyes and kill them. This is the real reason that
artillery and bombers and mines kill more people than
bullets: if all you;re doing is firing on a point on a
map, well, that\'s easy to live with. This is the real
reason muskets supplanted the longbow and the sword:
it\'s harder for a man to make the psychological
connection at a gut level between his gun and the
guy\'s wounds, than between a sword and his wounds. 

This is the real reason bayonet charges still work
sometimes: the thought that someone really is willing
to stick several inches of cold steel in your body is
quite chilling. Bullets and bombs are as deadly, but
somehow bayonets are more personal and chilling.

It\'s a very hard thing to do, to kill someone, and
most men in war do their damnedest to avoid - if
they\'re grunts. I\'ve not heard of any non-firers
amongst artillerymen, or mine-layers. 

Since people always ask for references, I refer those
interested to Col David Grossman\'s excellent work, "On
Killing", where he discusses exactly this military
problem, and how the (US) military has tried to
overcome it.

My own aussie military has not been so successful, I\'d
say. Bad for the army, good for humanity.

But non-firing will never be depicted in the movies
except as cowardice. Such men are not cowards, they\'re
simply human. They risk their lives to save comrades,
they just don\'t want to take other lives. That\'s
humanity, not cowardice. But this is rather too fine a
distinction to make for most film-makers (note I don\'t
say, "film-goers", I think makers underestimate the
intelligence of film-goers.)


