    'index' => 'eg091',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'An Encounter
by Timothy Collinson

The PCs are just entering town in slow moving evening rush hour traffic
when they witness a being assault another, hitting him full in the face and
leaving him stretched out on the side of the road having hit his head on
the ground.

1. The PCs drive on and do nothing.  Next day the local news carries
reports of the death of a being killed by an unknown assailant who attacked
him on the street in the rush hour.

2. The PCs drive on but another witness saw them see the events and got
their vehicle registration.  *Not* helping in such circumstances can carry
hefty penalties on this world.

3. The PCs stop to lend assistance but the assailant has already made
himself scarce and others are attending to the injured being.  Still, the
thought was there.

4. The PCs stop to lend assistance, any with medical skill can attend to
the stricken being, others can endeavour to apprehend the assailant and/or
his two friends.  After \'collaring\' the one who threw the punch, he will
violently make a run for it breaking the little finger of whoever has a
hold of him.  (This won\'t be realized for an hour or so and will take four
weeks in a stack splint [1] to heal).

5a. The PCs stop to lend assistance and are able to apprehend the assailant
after an exciting chase on foot.  The local law enforcers are glad of the
assistance.  The broken finger of (4) can be inflicted at the discretion of
the referee.

5b. The PCs stop to lend assistance and report what they\'ve seen to the
local law enforcers.  However, what they hadn\'t seen prior to the events
above was that the assailant had himself been attacked extremely violently
and his punch was his one act of self defence.

6. The PCs stop to lend assistance and are set on by *all* those at the
scene, including the being picking himself off the roadside, as they object
to outsiders interfering with a \'private\' matter.



OK, so this isn\'t the usual patron encounter but might be fun to add a bit
of color or to raise ethical issues in your role playing.  The reason it is
a little \'odd\' and doesn\'t give the referee the usual "here\'s all the
facts" is because, contrary to what the Readers\' Digest may say, life isn\'t
like that and this incident was inspired by real life.  In case anyone
cares my gamelife referee evidently rolled a \'4\'.

tc
I wouldn\'t recommend trying this at home


[1]  I saw the name of the splint when at the fracture clinic but failed to
make a note of it.  A quick search on the web turned up:
http://supports4u.com/finger.htm which looks like the thing, but no medical
knowledge should be presumed!
