    'body' => 'shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) wrote:

> You\'re wrong. *Trademarks* can be lost thru non-enforcement. But not
> copyrights. Also, if the copyrights were properly registered *before*
> the violation, the violator can be charges *punitive* damages, which
> start at somethging like $100 per copy.

Hmmm... this is a bit embarrassing. Now that you mention it, I may well
have blurred trademarks and copyrights in my memory.

> Among other things, if you happen to make enough copies that the *list*
> price of all of them exceeds $1000, you are guilty of a *felony*.
> Complete with large fine and prison term. That\'s due to a law passed a
> few years back and aimed at folks pirating software. But as far as I
> know it applies equally well to printed materials.

Passed where? I\'m sure that violating copyright is illegal here too,
but I doubt that the penalties are the same in Canada as they are in
the US.

> So if you make too many copies, and Roger found out, you could wind up
> facing *criminal* charges.

Well, yes, but part of my original premise is that Roger is too
poor and/or incompetent to adequately police the use of the work
he owns. And again, I\'m in Canada, which is by no means makes
me immune to prosecution, but it presents a logistical barrier
to alerting the authorities to my (not yet committed) heinous crimes.

> Besides, you are overlooking an inmportant point. Like it or not, he
> *does* own the copyright. So before doing anything too drastic, stop
> and consider how you\'d feel if someone did that to *your* material.

Well, I\'m not totally ignorant of this. I work in the software
industry and I\'m quite familiar with copyright, IP rights and
the reality that the line between legal and illegal often gets 
blurred. Frankly, I am much more sympathetic to the fact that
Roger may not actually own some of the work he thinks he owns
(re: Rob Prior\'s message) than to the fact that he has legal
right to the materials.

I have little practical interest in any mass photocopying or any kind
of reproduction of DGP materials, for profit or not. But it
does bother me that people seem to treat Roger\'s (apparent)
ownership of DGP materials as sacred. I don\'t think there\'s
any reasonable objection to using \'Fteirle\' in a GURPS Traveller
pub (which has apparently already happened).

For example, is it really a copyright violation if the authors
of G:T Starships lift the section from SoM about the lanthanum
grid patterns being different for all the different races?
Lifting the passage verbatim is plagiarism, sure, but the 
idea? And using the same names for things - is that _illegal_?

My basic point is that I think people should feel free to 
use DGP materials as "canon source" that same way they use
GDW materials. I have no idea why people seem to think that
using ideas from DGP-published sources is somehow verboten
compared to non-DGP stuff. Even if it is illegal by the letter
of the law (which I\'m not fully convinced it is), I seriously
doubt anyone will get a subpoena and a court date for doing it.

Ethan
