    'topic' => ' Have A Go Heroes',
    'body' => '> OK, so this isn\'t the usual patron encounter but might be fun to add
> a bit of color or to raise ethical issues in your role playing.  The
> reason it is a little \'odd\' and doesn\'t give the referee the usual
> "here\'s all the facts" is because, contrary to what the Readers\'
> Digest may say, life isn\'t like that and this incident was inspired
> by real life. 

Great idea. My take at it (also inspired by real life...) will not 
raise any ethical issue, but will certainly exasperate any 
action-addict PC...


Your Passport, Please!

by Carlos Alos-Ferrer

The PCs have just landed without problems in an Imperial world, well 
below Average Stellar technology. The only oddity of this world is 
that they have their own native language with its own set of 
characters. Part of the population can\'t speak Galanglic, and still 
another part can speak but not read it (think of people who speak 
japanese but understand no kanji). After contacting a patron by 
phone or similar, they agree that an initial pre-payment 
will be delivered to them by local post so that it gets registered.

They receive the communication that the money is waiting for them to 
pick it at a local office and get there. Quite naturally, the clerk - 
who speaks galanglic with difficulty - asks them to identify 
themselves. When the PCs wave their Imperial ID cards, the clerk 
refuses to acknowledge them. "I can\'t read that," he says, "and if 
you are foreigners you must present your Planetary Pass to pick this 
up."

When the PCs ask what the Planetary Pass is. The clerk explains that 
it is the document that authorizes you to travel inside the world if 
you are a foreigner. Of course Imperial citizens do not *need* to 
have it (only non-Imperial ones), but still, without Planetary Pass, 
you can not pick this up.

1. The PCs just give up and contact the patron. The patron will 
reconsider the assignment, since his "trusted" team gave up in the 
face of such a minor difficulty. Besides, the patron cannot reclaim 
the money. It will go back to him only after two months.

2. The PCs try to argue that since they do not need to have a 
Planetary Pass, it is ridiculous to have a regulation forcing them to 
use it. The clerk answers that they cannot expect that he recognizes 
an ID card he cannot understand.

3. The PCs try to get to the clerk\'s boss. He simply confirms the 
clerk\'s view and explains that he cannot change the regulations.

4. The PCs ask how can they get a Planetary Pass. They are directed 
to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, where a clerk calmly explains 
them, as if they were ignorant children, that they do not need one 
since they are imperial citizens. Still, one can be done, but it will 
take several months as a message to perform routine checks on the 
PCs identity is sent to the subsector capital.

5. The PCs try to get a Certified Translator to make an authorized 
translation of their IDs, and they find it is expensive, but finally 
the clerk accepts it.

6. The PCs discover that, astoundingly, they can authorize a local to 
pick the money up in their name by simply signing the Communication 
and writing the local\'s name. Then all they have to do is to find a 
cooperative local.
