    'date' => 'Tue, 07 Dec 1999 13:01:15  0500',
    'body' => '"Andrew Moffatt-Vallance" <a.vallance@netaccess.co.nz>
>With all due respect to Col. Grossman\'s work, it based on
>flawed research. Grossman\'s work is based mainly on the
>performance of the US army in the 2nd WW and Korea. And

Uh, say what?  Did you read the book, or are you thinking of earlier works
such as Marshall\'s Men Against Fire?  Grossman\'s work and discussion of
firing rates et al does not focus on 2nd WW and Korea.

<snip>

> The basic underlying
>problem (ie that soldiers are people not some mindless
>manpower pool) was not addressed by the US military until
>after Vietnam, by which stage the famous (and inaccurate)
>1 in 10 will fire rule had entered their collective conciousness.

Actually, Grossman\'s hypothesis, in "On Killing," is the opposite of what
you indicate.  It is that the US Army drastically improved its training
methods from WWII and Korea and, by mid way to late Vietnam, had definitely
"got it right" in that respect.  He states that firing rates went UP
dramatically (from 20-30% to about 80-100%) by Vietnam and into the modern
day.  He indicates that US military performance in Vietnam, Somalia, etc.
(on the _tactical_ level) and similarly, British in Falklands (among other
examples), indicates that modern US-Western-NATO training methods are
working in this respect by conditioning soldiers to shoot.  How many are
actually using aimed fire against their opponents is another question, but
certainly a far greater number than WWII.

Grossman\'s man criticism post-Korea is not that US forces are inefficient
in firing, but that (for various reasons) psychological support provided to
the more efficient shooters and killers was lacking (for example, as a
result of individual rotations out of battle area rather than by-unit
rotations).  He also generalizes into discussions of violence in popular
culture and so on; a weakness in his book is a lack of detailed discussion
of police experience in this respect.  Nevertheless, characterizing his
research as "flawed" for the reasons you state does not seem to be accurate.

- -David Pulver
