    'body' => 'In a message dated 12/7/99 1:24:38 PM Eastern Standard Time, lkw@io.com 
writes:

> The question has come up in house WRT GT Nobles: What does the
> fanbase want to see.

Hmmm.  Some of the things I\'d put in:

How many nobles are there?  How many barons, in particular?  How
many "honors" and "rank" nobles are there drifting around?  How many
knights or baronets?

What do nobles *do*?  Fleet command and oversight, offices in the
regional Imperial government, diplomacy, "one-man fire brigades,"
visiting the court of the Emperor or the local Archduke, sitting in the
Moot, being a tycoon, being a lazy wastrel. . .

Who do they interact with?  Their seneschal, their huscarles, their
other staff, planetary government officials, and so on.

What are noble fiefs really like?  How big, how much income do they
generate?  Maybe even some (not very detailed) rules on managing a fief
or other holdings, a la Far Trader.

How do nobles really interact with local governments?  What kinds of
relationships are common, and what are nobles expected to do to promote
Imperial interests on their home worlds?

Noble families!  Your run-of-the-mill PC doesn\'t have much family,
but a high nobleman *is* his family.  Maybe some rules such as appeared
in "Pocket Empires" for fleshing out your family connections. . .

Planetary nobility?  There must be aristocratic local governments that
tie in to the Imperial nobility without having Imperial rank themselves.

Politics!  What do nobles argue about?

Yachts -- what does your well-connected noble use to get around the
sector in?

Campaigns involving the nobility -- the noble as casual encounter,
the noble as patron, the Noble\'s A-Team campaign, the campaign
where everyone is a noble. . .

Lots of adventure seeds!

I might be interested in seeing some detailed noble characters worked
out at two pages a head, as in the "rogue\'s gallery" books, but not a
whole book of them.  There\'s too much else to talk about.

- ----
