    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'eg133',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Black ICE <wombat@premier.net> asked:
>>Leonard Erickson wrote:
>>> 
>><<snip>>
>>> 
>>> AM/FM/PM are modulation types, though to most folks AM refers to
>>> "commercial broadcast radio" (In the US, in the 560 to 1600 kHz range),
>>> and FM refers to "commercial broadcast radio" (in the US in the 88 to
>>> 108 MHz range).
>>
>>BTW, what is "phase modulation" (I assume that\'s what "PM" stands for),
>>and how does it work?  I understand amplitude and frequency modulation
>>(comes from having a SIGINTer as a roommate a few years back), but phase
>>modulation just doesn\'t ring any bells with me.
>
> It could also be Pulse Modulation (aka PCM - Pulse Code Modulation)
>
> I think that\'s a binary pulse/no pulse system.

It can be. But there\'s also *analog* pulse *width* modulation. You get
an analog value between 0 & 1 by having pulses that *start* at regular
intervals (say 1.5 units) and have a duration that varies according to
the value being sent (say 0.1 units for 0 to 1.1 units for 1). 

Or you can have fixed width pulses with the *interval* between them
being the modulation. Again, this allows direct transmission of
*analog* values.  

Both of the above are frequently encountered in telemetry applications.

Digital pulse modulation tends to be similar to what\'s used to encode
data on hard disks:

"FM" aka "single density". This has clock pulses, with data encoded as
the presence or absence of a pulse halfway between clock pulses.

"MFM" (modified FM) aka "double density". There are no clock pulses.
Instead, the data pulses are compared against a local clock, and
special coding is used to ensure that no more than X 0 pulses occur in
a row (to prevent clock drift from garbling data). For disks, X is 4 or
5 if I recall correctly.

