    'index' => 'eg142',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'The thing with SAAB was that it\'s initial season was really uneven, but it
should have been given a chance.  Every SF show, it seems, needs a season
to work out the kinks.  I tried watching B5 the first season and was
repulsed.  Started watching again in the 3rd one and was totally hooked!
Same with S:TNG. Not that it every got really good IMO, but it went from
terrible to okay by third season.

Back to SAAB Problems:

1. It needed someone with military knowledge as an assistant director (or
maybe someone who had once read a book about the military, or who had
lived within a few miles of an army base or SOMETHING! :-) 

2. The banking fighters were okay.  They were semi-realistic with the
rolling ability and stuff, but why not go all the way and do vector
movement?

3. Some episodes were unwatchable due to bad acting and writing.  The
"Little tank that could" one was terrible and the "Flickering light as
psych weapon" one was beyond horrible. 

Having said that, I thought some episodes were brilliant: "Who Monitors
the Birds" was great!  I should\'ve been given some time to get its legs
under itself...

Lesson for SF TV writers:  Keep the number of characters small so you can
actually develop them a little!  Three main characters with 3 secondary
seems to be a winning formula (Think Kirk / Spock / McCoy with Scotty /
Sulu / Chekov).

Charles C.
