    'body' => '> From: Loren Wiseman <lkw@io.com>
 
> The question has come up in house WRT GT Nobles: What does the fanbase want
> to see. One suggestion is to do a collection of PCs (a la GURPS Wizards or

Thanks for seeking our input, Loren.  

> What burning questions (about nobles) need to be addressed? 

I\'d like to see some coverage of the Imperium\'s political economy and
history.  How did the noble class arise?  What functions does the class
fulfil in the Imperium, how have those functions changed over time, and
what functions have been added or dropped historically?  What was the
role of the noble class in the Civil War?  Did Arbellatra\'s reforms
affect the noble class, and, if so, how?  How do the tensions between
local autonomy and central authority play out, and where do the nobles
fit?

> How much should be devoted to life at the Imperial court? 

Not much, although some background nuggets would add flavor.  

Here is my view on the historical development of the nobility (in answer
to one of the burning questions):

The noble class arose from the military and naval governors sent by the
conquering Terrans to manage parts of the collapsed Ziru Sirka.  Those
proconsuls, out of communication with the capital and on largely their
own for very long periods of time, decided to assume total control,
including control over their succession.  They accordingly followed
Terran models of hereditary nobility.  

No doubt there was communication among the Terran governors about
whether this was a good and defensible idea; it certainly constituted
mutiny to the extent that naval and military officers were assuming
total local control and passing on their power to their kin or chosen
successors, rather than retiring through military channels.  

So sometime during the Rule of Man, a noble class comprising Terran
naval and military officers (and probably some civilian appointees) came
into existence and imposed itself on the empire.  

Did the Vilani have a concept of a noble class that could accommodate
and assimilate this new development?

During the Long Night, the nobility acquired even more local control and
formed little empires of their own.  Many Vilani assumed Solomani names
and made themselves into nobles.  

When Cleon formed the Third Imperium, he had a pre-existing noble class
in the newly acquired territories that he could use.  He would offer
continuation of the status quo and support if they would offer fealty,
taxes, and troops.  

- --Glenn M. Goffin
