    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> This is no. of destinations within 1 parsec but more than 0.1
>> parsecs. (This last restriction will hopefully stop binary 
>> companions showing as Jump-1 destinations.)
>
> You might want to reconsider. 0.1 parsec is a LONG distance. 
> Anthing more than 10 AU is probably too far for anthing other 
> than a jump, time wise. Even that is too far for slower ships.
> 10 AU will take 9 days for 1G, 6.3 for 2G, down to 3.7 for 6G.
> For most ships, more than 10 AU means a jump. 0.1 parsec equals 
> 20626.5 AU. 
>
> 0.000049 parsec is just a tad over 10 AU. 

0.0001 parsec (20.6 AU) is a more "covenient" figure to work with. :-)
And I could argue that at 0.001 pc (206 AU) is still "in system".

parsecs  AU        light
- ----  ----  ----
0.00001    2.06     17.2 min
0.0001    20.6       2.86 hr
0.001    206         1.19 day
0.01       2.06 k   11.9 days
0.1       20.6 k   119 days 
1        206 k       3.26 years

So at 0.001 pc, you can still send a radio message and get a reply
faster than you can send a ship. At 0.01 pc, round trip time for a
radio signal is 23.8 days, which is well above the time for a jump out
and a jump back. 

So 7 light days is the point where it gets just as fast to jump a ship
as to send a radio signal. That\'s 1209.6 AU or 0.00586 pc (1/170 pc). 

So it looks like 0.005 or 0.001 pc for a "reasonable cutoff". 

