> as having several datasets downloadable directly.

Anybody have a downloadable database of *extragalactic* objects,
complete with positional co-ordinates? I\'d also be interested in
positional data for *bright* intragalactic objects and strong radio
sources. Basically, the sort of stuff you\'d use to determine your
position if you were *really* lost. As in "Are we sure what galaxy we
are in?"

If nothing else, generating a table of usable "beacon stars" that are
visible (or radio detectable) clear across "known space" would be nice.

BTW, as I pointed out in r.a.sf.s some time back, any sort of "jump"
drive with *real* range is just as apt to drop you out several
*megaparsecs* away as several parsecs. Which makes for some lovely
problems in navigation. 

The *only* SF story I\'ve ever read that used this idea was "The Galaxy
Primes" by E.E.Smith. And he sort of cheated to let them find their way
home. 

That could be an interesting thing to do to some players if you are
getting tired of the standard background. Have them test a "new"
concept in jump drives. Something that they inventor says is so
"obvious" he can\'t understand why no one ever tried it before. 

The answer is that most races *have* found it and tried it. And then
written it off as a bad idea when none of the test ships ever came
back. They never came back because until you can "calibrate" the drive,
it jumps you at *random*. And since it has a range big enough to hit
anywhere in the universe, random is *really* random.

If you want to be *really* realistic, have the first jump land them
somewhere in one of the Voids. Careful observations with the *good*
telescope they brought along (they expected to be lost, just not *this*
lost), will let them pick out the patterns of galaxies surrounding the
Void. The nearest ones may be only a *billion* parsecs away. They might
even be able to detect a few red dwarfs that are floating alone in the
Void. Still far out of normal jump range, much less being reachable
under normal drive ("No, we can\'t go into cold sleep to try for one,
there\'s no way the low berths will run for anything *close* to a
million years..." :-)

When that sinks in, the players are going to be *really* unhappy. Be
nice. Let the next jump take them near *something* they can refuel at. 
And then either there, or at the next jump let them discover a
civilization. It can even have humans, descendants of humans from other
human groups that invented and tested the drive millenia ago. As well
as species from far distant galaxies (ie you get to invent new races). 

BTW, this could explain why the Vilani never got past J2. They came up
with this drive instead, and after fooling with it for a few centuries
gave up.

In any case, it\'s a hell of a way to get folks into a new background. :-)

