    'index' => 'eg171',
    'topic' => 'GT:Nobles Want List',
    'body' => 'Most of Steven\'s suggestions for GT:Nobles have to do with order:

1. how a world or cluster is brought into the Imperial nobility.
2. how nobility is gained (types of nobility).
3. how nobility is organized within classes.
4. how nobility interacts between classes.

These are valid issues; however, what are you going to do
with the REST of the book?  Moreover, though these questions
are unanswered by \'canon\', I think knowing a \'definitive\' answer
does not improve the overall playability of Traveller.  So I tend
to not be so worried about unanswered quesions like those above.

What lights my fire is Adventure.  So what does a noble have
that is geared toward adventure?  I suggest that there are
a set of core ideas that the book could build itself around,
which can generate many a fruitful night of gaming.  Of course,
the book would concentrate on the noble as Adventurer rather
than Patron.


1. Sabotage.  Prestige is gained by sabotaging the unsabotageable
with one\'s own team, led by oneself.  Mission: Impossible.
("Just to show I can prevent it").

2. Defiance.  Power is concentrated: a noble can gain prestige
with open defiance of some strong opponent.  For example, the
very existence of the Federation of Arden is a defiance of Imperial
and Zhodani political, economic, and military power.  Obviously
connected with some noble houses somewhere, whose raw power
and connections enables them to do this. ("Just because we can")

3. The Gambit.  Nobles thrive on overcoming impossible odds,
even to the point of sacrificing safety for a chance of a more excellent
outcome.  Just so, then, will some nobles attempt impossible tasks
with as few competetive resources as possible.  Of course, what
resources they have will be the best Imperial Credits can buy.

4. The Hunt.  Call it "Scouts on drugs", where a noble decides to
play Scout and makes a beeline for some interdicted, uncharted,
or non-Imperial world in order to "discover something".


Add to this the complexity of dealing with contacts, favors, and
bureaucracy to line up all the ducks, and fire away!


For resources, Jens has the right idea: a yacht design and a sample
estate map would be useful.  By the bye, don\'t forget to make the
yacht a fine vessel, something nobles would WANT to pay big
bucks for.  And the best sensor package available for 200dtons, ok?

- -Rob
