    'topic' => ' OT/Flamebait: Starship Troopers revisited',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> I loved that show!  What were some of the shortcomings?  
>
> Note, not trying to start a flamewar, i\'m admittedly ignorant.

Try these on for size. In the episode that convinced *me* to quit
watching it, they took off from earth in their cute little "fighter
jet" clones, and rendezvoused with a carrier *near Jupiter*. 

Jupiter is 5.2 AU from the sun. Let\'s be nice and assume it and earth
are as close as they ever get and thus the trip is *only* 4.2 AU.
That\'s 630 million km. Boosting at 1 g until halfway, then turning
around and decelerating would take almost 6 *days*. No way are those
cockpits livable for *one* day, much less six.

To reduce the trip time to 1 day requires an acceleration of around 8.5
gees. Which is far too high to sustain for that long (remember, they
don\'t have inertial compensation). 

Next, we have them expecting an enemy attack that will pass near
Jupiter. So they hide in the Trojan asteroids. Unfortunately, the
Trojan asteriods are 5.2 AU away from Jupiter! Same orbit, but
leading/trailing by 60 degrees.

The Trojans may have a lot more asteroids per unit of volume than the
asteroid belt, but they *still* aren\'t as crowded as they showed.

They had Jupiter showing a visible disk from the Trojans. Sorry, it\'s
as far from them as from Earth.

They had the fighters boost to intercept trajectory and then coast to
intercept the enemy. Good idea, but again, the sheer *scale* means
they\'d be in the fighters way too long. 

Now, we have them headed more or less *at* the enemy "formation", with
velocities such that they were able to reach intercept in only hours.
Yet when the formations pass through each other, the ships are able to
keep firing at each other (visually!) for a minute or more!

And to top it off, the fighters are able to turn around and come back
for a second pass in only a minute or so. 

Oh yeah, the enemy force was moving at a speed that would let them
attack earth within "hours" of passing Jupiter.

In short, they had *no* idea of the distances involved, nor of the
velocities that those distances require. No sense of the *scale* of
space. 

