    'topic' => ' OT/Flamebait: Starship Troopers revisited',
    'body' => 'From: Douglas E. Berry <gridlore@pop.mindspring.com>


> Many of us hoped that a movie called "Robert Heinlein\'s Starship
>Troopers" would have more resemblance to the book than a few
>names and a sketched out plot.  Ginny Heinlein tried to have The
>Master\'s name removed after seeing a pre-release print.

Doug, you seem to me to be a bright guy, and I assume that you have had some
experience with watching film and television, as well as reading books.
So...

...why did you ever get your hopes up in the first place? ;)

First, a disclaimer: I\'ve never made it a secret that I think that Starship
Troopers was, at best, a mediocre book. I personally think that Heinlein has
written aesthetically and intellectually better books. I\'m not going to
comment on the aesthetics of the book nor am I going to comment on the
aesthetics of the movie. I\'m also not going to comment on the business of
the medium of print or the medium of film.

With that said, let me put this bluntly: Starship Troopers, as written,
would not translate into a "good" movie.

Keep in mind that I\'m not talking about box office receipts nor am I talking
about aesthetics here. Starship Troopers, the book, deals mainly with
abstract concepts (justice, freedom, and civic duty leap to mind), and how
those concepts relate to each other. The powered armor, the bugs, the
skinnies, the ships, these are all (as a GURPS book might say) "special
effects".

Film and television[1] have certain limitations which make both types of
media *terrible* at dealing with abstract concepts. At best, a movie like
The Thin Red Line is produced, in which case divergence from the source
material, in one way or another, is still *absolutely required* to get even
a *fraction* of the ideas in the book across.

To put it another, simpler, way: print and film / television are so
different that simple translation between them is not possible. Good books
are good books for completely different reasons than good movies are good
movies.

In other words, don\'t get your hopes up again! ;)

[1] I\'m including television for the simple reason that it is a known fact
among directors that their films will be released on video. It is obvious
from the way shots are set up in movies that this is something which
filmmakers take into account. If you don\'t believe me, rent out a
pan-and-scan (non-letterboxed) version of Ghostbusters, and any pan-and-scan
movie made after about 1990 or so. Pay careful attention to the extremely
annoying panning when all four Ghostbusters are on screen conversing, and
then look at the way more recent movies tend to clump all of the action or
conversation into a conveniently small area on the screen.
'
