> > Ditto this.  Once a large porportion of the population has travelled in
> > space and *know* how \'quiet\' it is (I\'m not sure this will be the case
as I
> > suspect that like living aboard ship it will actually be quiet noisy at
a
> > \'local\' level), then it will become very unfashionable to have whizzing
> > ships.  IMO.
>
> It won\'t even take that. Just enough footage of *real* spacecraft going
> by each other in utter silence. After all, it\'s not that the ships are
> *quiet*, it\'s that you can\'t hear the noises from another ship onboard
> your ship.

You\'re making the assumption that television and film will attempt to
accurately reflect reality. Even common, every day objects, such as cars are
imbued with qualities that they don\'t have on television and in film. Sure,
if you\'re Stanley Kubrick you can get away with a more realistic view of
spacecraft, but there was little action outside the spaceship which it would
matter whether or not there was sound.

That\'s an entirely different notion than space combat scenes on film and
television. Silence doesn\'t add to the drama of space combat, just like cars
that just sit there after they crash into a bus don\'t add drama to a high
speed car chase The only way that space combat will ever be shot to be shown
without its own *vrooms* and *booms* is if a director has a musical score
made which highlights all of the *vrooms* and the *booms* on screen.

I would wager you that there will continue to be *vrooms* and *booms*, even
if space travel becomes so commonplace that the majority of people are
familiar with it.

I would wager that, but I won\'t, since I don\'t think either of us will live
long enough to see a day when space travel is that common...
