    'body' => 'On Mon, 6 Dec 1999, Ethan Henry wrote:

> I have little practical interest in any mass photocopying or any kind
> of reproduction of DGP materials, for profit or not. But it
> does bother me that people seem to treat Roger\'s (apparent)
> ownership of DGP materials as sacred. I don\'t think there\'s
> any reasonable objection to using \'Fteirle\' in a GURPS Traveller
> pub (which has apparently already happened).
>
> For example, is it really a copyright violation if the authors
> of G:T Starships lift the section from SoM about the lanthanum
> grid patterns being different for all the different races?
> Lifting the passage verbatim is plagiarism, sure, but the 
> idea? And using the same names for things - is that _illegal_?
> 
> My basic point is that I think people should feel free to 
> use DGP materials as "canon source" that same way they use
> GDW materials. I have no idea why people seem to think that
> using ideas from DGP-published sources is somehow verboten
> compared to non-DGP stuff. Even if it is illegal by the letter
> of the law (which I\'m not fully convinced it is), I seriously
> doubt anyone will get a subpoena and a court date for doing it.

Me too!

I mean, amen.  Couldn\'t agree more.  However, if you\'re working on stuff
that may see print, it\'s perhaps a bit more to be expected that the
hypothetical publishers would be more cautious.  That\'s the problem with
the "Vilani Sourcebook" project that\'s been floating around on the
TravCult list.

Kenji
