    'topic' => ' OT Flamebait: realism of war movies',
    'body' => 'Doug Berry wrote:
> Those eight guys were Rangers, American Commandos. 
> They were they best
> that we had to offer, and in a situation like they
> found themselves in,
> everybody would shoot.  They were also veterans
> already.. obviously the
> sergeant had been in the war since \'42!

That\'s quite true, such units did have a higher rate
of firers than line infantry units - but still, it
wasn\'t 100%. They had a higher rate because they were
better trained, firing at silhouettes of men instead
of just targets, so that when they saw a figure,
they\'d fire.

The Army has learned to condition you to kill - but
not how to make you feel good about it afterwards.

If you read the Grossman book I referred you to,
you\'ll see that time in combat (like the sergeant you
mention) has no affect on whether you fire or not.
Also, neither does the situation, by which I presume
you mena that anyone will fire if their life depends
on it, if a screaming bayonet-weilding maniac is
charging towards you. You\'d think it\'s true, but it\'s
not. Many people would rather die than kill. Ask themn
before the battle, and they\'ll say, "of course I\'d
kill," but when faced by the reality, they\'re more
reluctant. I could give instances, but I\'ll settle for
a personal instance, and then leave it to the book,
which is far more scholarly and knowledgeable than I
could ever be.

Over in Somalia we had pretty scrict rules of
engagement, that we couldn\'t fire unless fired upon,
or unless they were pointing their weapons directly at
us and wouldn\'t put them down when called upon to stop
(ie just like cops). A section from my platoon was on
patrol and spotted a couple Somali lads fleeing from
the patrol, looking suspicious. As it was a crowded
market place the patrol couldn\'t pull out their
weapons and start shouting, so they approached the
men, the scout put his hand on one man\'s shoulder and
spun him around. The man shoved a Sterling
submachinegun into the Aussie\'s belly and pulled the
trigger. Click. It turned out later the round was
hardstruck (which happens to less than 1 in 100,000
rounds). Now the Aussie was perfectly justified within
the rules of engagement, aussie military and civilian
law, and basic common sense, in shooting this guy.
Instead, he buttstroked him with his rifle and
disarmed him.

"He was sensible, he used minimum force," you might
say. But bear in mind that this soldier\'s _training_
was to kill, and we went over there actually expecting
a conventional war, that\'s what we were briefed for.
But what this story demonstrates is that if given any
other option, most men will not kill.

Sorry to do anything to risk your pride in your
"elite" units, but I still think there would have been
a majority of non-firers. 

The proportion rose due to training methods from 10%
to 95% from WWII to Vietnam, and Grossman\'s thinking
is that this is the true cause of PTSD: not what has
been done to you, but what you have done.

ObTrav: this will be more so in the future, since the
intensity of operations will be greater, the
battlefiled larger, more dangerous, and louder than
before (the progression that has occurred throughout
the centuries). How does the Imperium treat its burned
out soldiers? Its retured soldiers? Once full-time
service appeared, nations ahd to provide pensions etc,
since a group of disgruntled ex-servicemen who only
know how to fight can be a problem....

