    'index' => 'eg221',
    'body' => 'Andrew wrote:
> With all due respect to Col. Grossman\'s work, it
> based on
> flawed research. Grossman\'s work is based mainly on
> the
> performance of the US army in the 2nd WW and Korea.

Not entirely. His exact, statistical evidence is based
on WWII/Korea, but apocryphal evidence from other wars
support his contention.

For example, the Prussian army tested its units\'
marksmanship in 1808. They found that a battalion
(1,000 men, then) would score 60% hits at 100 yards on
another battalion-sized target (ie a piece of wood 6
ft high and a couple hundred feet long). Since they
could fire a maximum of three round per minute each,
you\'d expect thus 1800 rounds per minute impacting on
the target battalion. And so, two battalions fighting
each-other should anhiliate each-other, or cause one
side to break and run, within a minute.

In fact, only one or two men every minute would fall
over.

"Well," you say, "men being fired on don\'t fire so
accurately, the noise of muskets, the scream of shot,
the cries of wounded and dying comrades all will make
you a worse shot." I agree. So, let\'s say the\'re only
one-tenth as good as on the firing range. No, let\'s
say they were drunk, too, and only 1% as good. Would
you agree with that? Is that too generous? You still
then get 18 shots per minute hitting... Instead, we
get at best one-tenth as many as that.

Yes, the training was off for WWII and Korea. Yes,
it\'s been improved now. What\'s happened is that armies
have faced the fact that it\'s difficult to persuade
men to kill, and have learned to train them to do it.
I\'d agree that modern-day Rangers do have almost 100%
firers. But other armies, not so many will fire,
because of their different training. This is why 100
rangers were able to hold off 1000 Somalis in 1994:
less than 100 of those Somalis were actually aiming at
the Americans.

There is something innate in man to make him fight,
but there is also something innate in man to make him
reluctant to kill.

=====
