ObTrav again, a friend of mine and I both read Grossman and spent some time
discussion the applications to sf gaming. Some not-to-serious thoughts.  

Grossman and others point out the "non-firers" situation does not apply to
aircraft or vehicle crews, as they are bombing/shooting at very long range
and/or destroying "hardware" or "structures" rather than people they can
see. Grossman also points out that most serious "non-firing" occurs when
you can see the face of your enemy. This is one reason why, especially in
pre-gunpowder battles, fleeing troops are massacred: it is easier to run
through or shoot an opponent in the back. (Of course, he\'s not defending,
which is another reason...)

In Traveller, troops often wear full-body combat armor or battledress.
They may also be using HUDs and fighting at night with thermal imaging or
Light intensification gear, HUDs, etc.  In short, they are watching a video
game and firing at faceless humanoid targets.  Would this increase "shoot
to kill" rates?

Testable issue:   do firing rates increase when humanoid troops engage
non-humanoids or robots?  

Not-so-serious thought:  Grossman\'s work obviously explains the situation
in STAR WARS.  Imperial Stormtroopers do not want to kill rebels, who are
obviously human, wearing either civilian dress or ordinary military
uniforms and open helmets.  On the other hand, rebels can easily kill
stormtroopers, who they can perceive as "faceless".  Stormtrooper accuracy
improves markedly when they are facing obviously non-human jawas or big
sandcrawlers...  Most Imperial Stormtroopers are simply firing into the air.

Ob-GURPS Trav issue:  Grossman\'s "natural warriors" are those who have the
Combat Reflexes advantage.  Anyone else should have 1/2 Acc bonus at best.
