    'body' => 'From: Juliean Galak <jg42@cornell.edu>


> AFAIK, the director of the movie was a well known RAH-hater and considered
> RAH to be a Nazi.  Why this guy was picked to make the movie, I have no
> idea....
>
> >That film is evil.
>
> True...

Sort of true. There is the matter of an interview he did for a Dutch
magazine in which the interviewer was apparently a Heinlein fan and was
indignant because she heard that Heinlein\'s work might be ruined. Verhoeven
responded in typical Verhoeven fashion, and eventually chased her away by
calling her (if I remember correctly) a Nazi lesbian. I think a translated
version of the interview was put up on the list during the initial American
release of Starship Troopers. I may be wrong, though.

One of the flashpoints in that interview was whether or not the book
presented a fascist ideology[1]. If I remember correctly, the interviewer
had become very indignant on this issue. Verhoeven trumped her by saying
that he grew up in Nazi occupied Holland and that he knew damn well what
fascism looks like. My memory may be poor, but that\'s how I remember it.

On the other hand, I have spoken with the fellow who did a series of
interviews for Starlog with the crew of the film, specifically with the
producer and screenwriter. They maintained that Verhoeven actually liked the
book.

This is purely anecdotal, your own mileage may vary.

[1] This is a point which bugs Heinlein fans to no end. Some will argue the
point that a fascist ideology was no represented, and perhaps they\'re right.
I\'m not going to tapdance on that alligator tonight. What is interesting
though is that some Heinlein fans will back away and say that "The Master"
is merely presenting an interesting society with no ideological claims. This
position is on rather shaky ground, as most people who have even a passing
familiarity with Heinlein\'s works can attest to.

There is a third option, though. This option is that the book is an
extremely complicated exercise in irony where the nature of the society is
one that is *supposed* to be unpalatable to a large degree to hammer home
the issue of classical civic duty. This could very well be the case, as
Heinlein, in other works, seems to be extremely interested in the concept of
civic duty.
