    'body' => 'From: Kyle Schuant <kyle3054@yahoo.com>


> Not quite! But a veteran of fighting... and I know
> that the one thing not shown in that movie, the one
> thing that no movie will _ever_ show because it drives
> a rusty salt-encrusted blad into the heart of all our
> myths of our warrior past, is that most soldiers never
> fire directly at the enemy. They do their damned best
> to avoid it.
>
> Instead of eight guys fighting, you would have had
> maybe two of them firing, another couple "Oh, I\'m just
> loading magazines for him," another couple pointing
> out targets, "quick, shoot him, Joe!", one patching up
> wounds, and another one running messages. But in this
> movie, they were all killers, except for the wimpy
> translator, who only shot an unarmed man, and his not
> killing was depicted as cowardice.

<snipped further information concerning the same point>

Okay, fair enough, and point taken. First a question, how accurately is this
model when applied to troops with special forces training, such as the ones
portrayed in Saving Private Ryan? Second a point, unless I saw a different
movie, there were very few sequences (the ending sequence specifically) when
the "resolution" of the film was sharp enough that the audience could really
see the members of the group fighting close up. The opening D-Day scene
didn\'t attain such a resolution until the end, when the Americans were
exterminating the Germans in trenches. From my own reading on the subject, I
came away with the impression that this is pretty much what did happen after
Americans began to break through. Until the last sequence, the combats we
see don\'t have the kind of resolution that detailing such a thing would be
required.

On the other hand, my take on Upham (the translator) was a little bit
different. Upham\'s character is way too complex to be summed up in the word
"coward".

> But non-firing will never be depicted in the movies
> except as cowardice. Such men are not cowards, they\'re
> simply human. They risk their lives to save comrades,
> they just don\'t want to take other lives. That\'s
> humanity, not cowardice. But this is rather too fine a
> distinction to make for most film-makers (note I don\'t
> say, "film-goers", I think makers underestimate the
> intelligence of film-goers.)

I so totally disagree that film-makers underestimate the intelligence of
film-goers. On one hand, the medium itself doesn\'t *lend* itself to
intelligence, but I\'ve already stated that once tonight. On the other hand,
I have had too many personal experiences with the American movie-going
public.

When I went to see Starship Troopers, one man stood up and commented, about
ten minutes into the movie and with *great* surprise, that the film was a
"...futuristic jaun" (Jaun: "joint", loose translation: thing, undertaking
or movie).

When I took my father to see Saving Private Ryan, there was a group of young
men seated in front of us. During the D-Day scene, they kept screaming, "Get
those f***in\' Japs! Get the Japs!" (my apologies for my uncouth language, no
offense is meant to anyone). At the end, one commented to his friends,
"Didn\'t I tell you it was a realistic movie about Vietnam?"

I kid you not.

When the Star Wars Special Edition came around, a friend of mine witnessed
one man stand, scream that it was "...the same *damn* movie," and storm out
of the theater.
