> am I missing?

My guess, and it\'s only a guess, because I do not have
the "Grand Survey" text in front of me is that you have
mis-read the case.  If you are subtracting the result of the
formula from the base temperature, then I don\'t see how
you came up with your figures.  If the formula you quoted
above is actually the night side temperature (which
seems more logical to me), the you are way off.  If your
base is 10 and the formula is (Base + 273) x 0.15, then
the result is 283 x 0.15 = 4.245 Kelvin.  That\'s over
269 degrees below zero on Mr. Celsius\'s scale.


> 2. I want a mean temp that\'s low enough that the "twilight band" will be
> uninhabitable.  Otherwise the inhabitants would just live at the north and
> south poles.  What\'s a good distance for this from an F9 VI?  Can I assume
> that the planet\'s mean temp will be found at the twilight band in general?
> Something tells me there\'s going to be a sinusoidal relationship that I\'m
> missing...

___________________________________________
I suspect that 10 degrees is too high.  Earth\'s average
temperature is only 15.  People can survive at
temperatures that are very low or very high, perhaps -25
to 50 degrees C.  However; most of us are most
comfortable at 20-22.

Earth has an average temp of 288.15 K (15 degrees C).
If you know the output of a F9 VI in comparison to Sol, the
formula you need is:
        R ^ 2 * 288.15 = (Base + 273.15)
where   R is the radius of the orbit of the planet in
            question in AU\'s
        Base is the average temperature of the planet in
            degrees C

Or put another way, R = sqrt((Base + 273.15) / 288.15).
- --
Jason
