    'topic' => 'Mass communication, the nobility and epistemology (LONG)',
    'index' => 'eg263',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'I feel the need to atone for my recent sin of idulgence in off-topic
postings. I will not make the excuse of "Everybody\'s* doing it," I will
merely flagellate myself with copies of Starship Troopers, both the book and
the film, while I *vroom* through space in my Chevy Nova.

With my soul cleansed of the worst of my transgressions, I will begin a new,
long, and considerably more on-topic post, in which I hope to continue some
ideas that have been brought up in other threads and tie some of them
together in strange ways.

Before I begin, I\'d like to dedicate this post to Glenn "cos 90" St-Germain,
as I keep neglecting to send him email in our chain of off-list
correspondence. My apologies Glenn.

Now, on with the geekocity, I\'ll begin by laying the groundwork:

Recently, I have been introduced to (and I have devoured) Neil Postman\'s
excellent "Amusing Ourselves to Death", which is an excellent book that
deals with the effect of television on society. It hardly breaks the surface
of this subject, but it is an interesting introduction. Postman puts forth
the theory that the dominant medium in a society decides the form that
public discourse, everywhere, will take. The dominant medium shapes that
society\'s epistemology; it decides how knowledge *itself* is attained,
perceived and used.

This is not exactly a new theory. Anyone who has taken a look at the changes
in, say, American politics between the 18th century and the present day has
had to at least suspect that this to be the case. Anyone who has had even a
little experience with McLuhan and his intellectual heirs probably has been
introduced to some version of this idea. This has turned into something of a
hot topic lately, and from what I understand, a large number of academic
types have been discussing, debating, analyzing and working over this very
concept.

A really coarse summary goes something like this:

In the beginning, the dominant medium of communication was speech. There are
certain things that speech is good for, and certain things that speech is
terrible for. Speech is not a fantastic medium for science, math and
philosophy, for example. Speech is a fantastic medium for persuasion,
polarized discussions, and engaging narratives. One of the examples that
Postman uses is our current understanding of pre-literate law: Two parties
are brought before the tribal chief, and he searches his internal library of
proverbs, and attempts to come up with one that fits the situation at hand.

Then, writing comes along, and changes everything. At this point, all kinds
of things are possible which were previously impossible: rudimentary
science, the codification of laws, mathematics. Although Postman doesn\'t use
this example specifically, it\'s obvious that a new understanding of law
emerges. Now, it\'s possible to have laws which are set in stone, literally,
and the very concept of law goes in a completely different direction: If a
party is guilty of x, the punishment is y.

With the advent of the printing press, things really begin to take off, for
a large number of reasons. Now it\'s possible to really get things rolling in
science, mathematics, philosophy, politics. One of the things that print is
really quite good at is reasoned discourse, and reasoned discourse appears
in spades. Hell, it ushers in the Enlightenment, aka the Age of Reason! To
continue with the law theme, print redefines law yet again: With the ability
to disseminate cases and decisions across a wide area, there\'s a strong
shift toward precedent in law (Glenn: is precedent the right concept, or am
I missing the mark here?)

Postman goes through three more stages, telegraphy, photography and radio
(at least to some degree) before arriving at television. It goes without
saying that television has redefined politics, education, religion, music,
everything. That\'s what a shift in epistomology does. Law, at least to some
degree, changes again. Postman, writing in 1984, didn\'t have the benefit of
hindsight with regard to Rodney King, O.J. Simpson and Bill Clinton.
However, I don\'t think he was surprised by the way that they were handled.
In the opinion of many, at least in those cases, the concept of law has been
redefined yet again toward emotivist public opinion.

I\'m not going to go into current events and opinion-mongering here beyond
saying that television is a *really* frightening change. The short version
is that our public discourse is taking the form of television commercials.
Even print media has been influenced greatly by television, in both form and
content.

(The above may apply in varying degrees to the various countries that fellow
Travellers call home. In other words, YMMV)

Yep, now you crotchety ol\' codgers who want to see Traveller return to the
style of the LBB\'s have an argument, at least on a philosophical level. Of
course the economic counter-argument is extremely compelling! Maybe wargames
were victims of this epistemological shift, who knows. Actually, now that I
think about it, the rise of collectable trading card games and story and
picture-heavy RPGs makes a hell of a lot of sense.

Still, I didn\'t type all that merely to spit out a punchline and offer
ersatz commentary on the state of gaming. In case anyone is willing to take
the bait:

What does public discourse in the Traveller universe look like? What is the
dominant medium? What changes might appear as a result? Is this general
decline in the political arena one of the reasons for the fall of the Second
Imperium, and for the rise of the nobility in the Third Imperium?

To shift gears a bit, toward the end of Eric Hobsbawm\'s "The Age of
Extremes: A History of the World, 1914-1991"[1] he comments that as the
century draws to a close, certain supra-national entities are appearing to
fill in where democratic leadership seems to be failing (the recent
headline-making World Trade Organization, for example, the IMF, even NAFTA
and the European Union have non-elected bodies which are capable of deciding
certain sorts of policies). Is this the same kind of idea that leads to the
rise of the new nobility in the Third Imperium?

To give my own take, and hopefully start something of a discussion on what I
hope others find interesting as well:

I think that this might be an interesting direction for those of you who
want to justify the Imperial nobility beyond the traditional Asimovian
rationale (which usually appears something like, "well, a system of nobility
is really very efficient"). Perhaps the Imperium is the direct descendant of
an organization along the lines of the WTO ( or maybe the um... ITO:
Intergalactic Trade Organization?).

Maybe, the Imperium only rules the space between the worlds. This tends to
change the concept of the Imperium in a number of ways (even though the
slogan itself *is* canon). Such organizations are already starting to rule
the trade space between sovereign nations on earth. Under this model, the
Imperium becomes extremely remote and extremely distant, to the point of
being nearly invisible, even to the majority of interstellar travellers.

Now that I think of it, that\'s an interesting take on the Imperium.

I\'m stumped on the epistemological concerns of new media, but it\'s largely
because Traveller has been "hands off" about what they are. The Xboat
system, in a sense, is a "new medium". It\'s kind of like a strange mixture
between the telegraph and "a slow boat to China". Holographic projection
pops up in canon frequently. Outside of Traveller, in sci-fi in general, has
holographic projection been superannuated by "virtual reality", either in
forms like Star Trek\'s holodeck, Gibson\'s matrix, or Sterling\'s net?

What might various science-fiction media be good at? What might they be bad
at? I would think that holography will be something like a super-TV, doing
what TV\'s good at better, and do what TV\'s bad at worse. Maybe not though. I
don\'t know, that\'s why I\'d like to see other people chime in.

Damn. It\'s late.
