    'index' => 'eg285',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => '> From: Loren Wiseman 
> The question has come up in house WRT GT Nobles: What does the fanbase
want
> to see. One suggestion is to do a collection of PCs (a la GURPS Wizards
or
> GURPS Warriors), but I find this unsatisfactory (although any such book
> will need to give the most important Imperial nobles as PCs). How much
> should e devoted to life at the Imperial court? What burning questions
> (about nobles) need to be addressed? How many angels can dance on a
> pinhead, and why does he put up with it at all?

I would like to see _some_ detailed characters.   In particular, I would
like to see some kind of factionalism within the nobility, with details of
faction heads and agents of theirs who can interact with Player Characters
as patrons.  For example, in the Spinward Marches, there could be rivalry
between Norris, and a faction around the Santanocheev family, or perhaps
the politics of the Ling Standard/Sternmetall Horizons rivalry could be
explored.  (The latter might be preferable, since it could be extended into
the Solomani Rim when that book comes out.)  Oh, and those pesky Tukera
people - total laser-meat.

It might actually be more useful to have details of life at subordinate
courts, rather than the Imperial one.  There wouldn\'t necessarily be all
that much difference, but it\'s rather more likely that Player Characters
would get involved with the Archducal court at Mora, or the equivalent in
the Solomani Rim (Dingir?) than the Imperial one at Capital.

Questions about Nobles?  How rich are they, really?  How do you meet them,
marry them, or become one of them?  After you do, who is going to try to
cut your throat, and why?

Oh, and why was that dimwit son of Baron hault-Oberlindes always needing to
be rescued?

More seriously - property and families are always good things for PCs to
have - it means they\'ve got something to lose, and they\'re a bit less
likely to disappear "off the map" - a problem that I often saw in the
Classic Traveller days, before "civilisation" started shrinking, and which
could be an issue in the GT setting too.

It\'s definitely 42 angels who can dance on a pinhead, and the pinhead
hasn\'t much choice about it - have you ever tried getting rid of an
infestation of angels?  (Insert plug for In Nomine here if you insist.... 
I\'ve never played it.)

Anyway, if it gives me lots of good excuses for PCs to shoot things, it\'s
fine.  

Alan Bradley
