    'topic' => 're:  Mass communication, the nobility and epistemology (LONG)',
    'body' => '> From: "Chris Seamans" <semo@pil.net>

At the moment, I have just a couple of comments on your intriguing and
thoughtful post.
 
> Recently, I have been introduced to (and I have devoured) Neil Postman\'s
> excellent "Amusing Ourselves to Death", which is an excellent book that

What a great title.  It\'s even better than Four Arguments for the
Elimination of Television (by Gerry Mander (his real name), written in
the early 1970s).


> To continue with the law theme, print redefines law yet again: With the
> ability to disseminate cases and decisions across a wide area, there\'s a strong
> shift toward precedent in law (Glenn: is precedent the right concept, or am
> I missing the mark here?)

You are missing the mark.  Precedent was widely used in European systems
before the development of the printing press.  (Even your hypothetical
of the tribal leader reviewing his internal library suggests that he may
have been thinking in part, "how did our ancestors handle this?")  The
court -- often a panel of noble judges -- would consider the situation
presented and confer among themselves about what the result had been in
similar cases in the past.  That is the essence of precedent.  It is a
concept intimately connected (historically, although not logically) to
the idea of judges making and developing the law.  

By the late 1700s, only Britain retained the concept of judge-made,
precedent-based law. I suspect that the rise of absolutist monarchies on
the continent (the result of continental monarchies\' victories in the
struggle with the nobles that the nobles and merchants won in the
English Civil War) has more to do with the decline in the power of
judges and the use of precedent than changes in technology.  Napoleon
instituted his Code Napoleon about 1800, and it has served as a model
for the civil law system in Europe (where he imposed it on whomever
France conquered) and much of the rest of the world to this day.  

The civil law system is typified by writing the rules in as much detail
as possible in a legal code, which rules are then applied to each
situation presented to the court, without regard to what other courts
have done in similar situations.  That really depends on an efficient
publication system to get copies of the code to all of the judges and
lawyers.

In the last 200 years, common law countries have been developing civil
codes, but keeping their reliance on judicial precedent to interpret
those codes.  The trend is definitely away from use of precedent,
however.  For example, administrative courts (like those of the SEC or
many state labor departments) don\'t rely on precedent set by other
administrative law judges.  

Today, much of the law in the United States at least is being put on the
internet. That is an important change, because it makes the text of the
law (both code and precedent) accessible to many more people than ever
before.  (Reason that is more accessible include the relative ease of
computer searching over index or key word research, and the physical
proximity of one\'s computer versus the law library.)  

> Postman goes through three more stages, telegraphy, photography and radio
> (at least to some degree) before arriving at television. It goes without
> saying that television has redefined politics, education, religion, music,
> everything. That\'s what a shift in epistomology does. Law, at least to some
> degree, changes again. Postman, writing in 1984, didn\'t have the benefit of
> hindsight with regard to Rodney King, O.J. Simpson and Bill Clinton.
> However, I don\'t think he was surprised by the way that they were handled.
> In the opinion of many, at least in those cases, the concept of law has
> been redefined yet again toward emotivist public opinion.

I don\'t think that the concept of law -- at least as actually practiced,
as opposed to perceived -- has changed significantly as a result of any
of these technologies.  None of them are well suited to reasoned
discourse, and that is still the essence of the modern practice of law. 
Sensational cases have always been with us, but they have only
tangential effects on the practice or development of the law.  Those
tangential effects are limited to legislative response to public
perception.  None of the cases you mentioned has had any effect on the
law itself.  

> What does public discourse in the Traveller universe look like? What is the
> dominant medium? What changes might appear as a result? Is this general
> decline in the political arena one of the reasons for the fall of the
> Second Imperium, and for the rise of the nobility in the Third Imperium?

This is really interesting problem, because, as you note,

> The Xboat system, in a sense, is a "new medium". It\'s kind of like a strange 
> mixture between the telegraph and "a slow boat to China". 

In the Far Future -- which is the present day as far as the Ziru Sirka
is concerned (I think Vilani scouts got our recent Mars probes) --
communication within a star system is essentially instantaneous for huge
volumes of information.  On the other hand, communication within an
interstellar polity takes weeks.  How does this affect public
discourse?  I\'m not sure, and I have to go back to work.

- --Glenn

P.S.  You wrote:
> Perhaps the Imperium is the direct descendant of an organization along 
> the lines of the WTO ( or maybe the um... ITO: Intergalactic Trade 
> Organization?).

"Intragalactic" maybe, but more likely "interstellar".
