How do people handle salvage rights?  For that matter, how do they work in the real world?

For example, our heroes come across a damaged, but basically intact ship adrift in the outer reaches of a remote system.  After checking
the ship for survivors they find it deserted.  Once they manage to get the power plant online, drives working and get the ship refuelled they
decide to leave a skeleton crew aboard, get her to civilisation and claim salvage rights. HOWEVER on further examination they discover this
multi-million credit Free Trader was financed with 30 years left to pay off.

The owner/operators are dead so does the ship belong to the bank? Is it like a mortgage where an insurance policy pays off the balance
of the finance leaving the ship to be inherited by the owners\\\' next of kin?  Or does it belong to the salvaging PCs?

I\\\'m guessing it\\\'s either insured and paid off, leaving the PCs with a legal claim to the ship which can be contested under Imperial
law by the next of kin, or title reverts to the bank, but they pay the salvagers a percentage of the market value of the ship.

How does it work in the real world, any legal eagles specialising in International Maritime Law on the list?  For that matter is this
covered by canon?

Just curious to find out before I run the scenario, because my guys WILL ask to keep it....

...until they find the guy just hanging on in emergency low berth with scant hours of battery power keeping him alive...*evil grin*

iSteve



		

