    'date' => 'Thu, 9 Dec 1999 08:30:34 +1300',
    'body' => 'On 8 Dec 99, at 8:39, Rick Stump wrote:

> I agree. Scouts use radios too much, company commanders use radios too
> much, and forward observers might as well just call me on a phone and
> *tell* me where they are. \'Course, I *liked* it that way. In the Persian
> Gulf I was briefing the 6th Light Armor (French) and asked how long they
> thought they could speak on the radio before an enemy could fix their
> position. The concensus was 15 seconds. When I told them that in 15
> seconds the rounds would already be in the air, they thought I was
> kidding. During the war the tactical elements were pretty quiet, but their
> commanders and support were often on for 1+ minute at a time. And most
> armies aren\'t any better. Commanders get \'addicted\' to information very
> quickly, especially in high-stress situations like combat. Generals \'need\'
> to know what is happening in that critical battalion, company commanders
> \'must have\' artillery support right now, etc. If you leave them alone for
> a time, they do what they are trained to do - trust the equipment. Then
> you kill them. 

As a straight Intell guy (transfered from being a grunt) I spend quite 
a lot of time carrying one of those things at platoon or section level 
(the NZ Army still uses PRC-77s at about 20lbs), and we used to avoid 
talking as much as possible. We were generally quite successful as long 
as we could talk the company OCs out of requiring full SitReps every 
hour (and often on the hour). Sometimes I wonder about the mentality of 
people who become officers. 

> ObTrav: Imperial Intelligence probably has a whole lotta\'
> electronic warfare stuff, ranging from deep space listening arrays to
> detect old radio signals from solar systems 3-4 light years away to \'tramp
> far traders\' that actually have tons of electronics in their bay and an
> extendable antenna in their air raft berth.

The old "Russian Trawler" trick, eh?



- --
Rupert Boleyn <paradise.net.nz>
Wellington, New Zealand

