I\'ve just been reading up on medieval villages, and their justice 
system was based almost entirely on precedent. The jury would hear the 
case and make a ruling based on custom (ie what happened last time this 
came up), and make a ruling. If there was no precedent they would make 
a ruling based on what seemed reasonable to them (often this was 
confirmed in the records as being the will of the village as a whole), 
and this would then become one of the customs of the manor. I would 
suggest that precedent as a way of making law predates any other system.


