>Subject: (Almost) Tidally Locked Worlds
>
>Hi all.
>
>I\'m working on a map/write-up for the world Velscur (1110 Egyrn/Trojan
>Reach, X374379-3 Ni 302 Na F9 VI) and I have some questions. I\'m picturing
>the world as approaching tidal lock, with a rotation period of several
>decades.  This means the locals have to keep moving to remain in the
>habitable zone, but they can manage it even with their primitive tech.
>So...
>
>1. How do I calculate temperatures on the surface of such a world?  I
>tried the formulae in "Grand Survey" for tidally locked worlds (same as in
>WBH, I believe) but they give me a "cold pole" temp of only -60 degrees
>Celcius or so, if I\'m doing it right.  The formula says maximum cooling
>due to night-time is (Base+273)  *.15 for this world, giving me something
>like -50 (assuming a Base mean temp of around 10).  Add the latitude
>change of about -20 and I\'ve got -70. If the planet\'s mean temp is 10 or
>so, I get only -60 for the pole that\'s spent 50 years in darkness.  What
>am I missing?
>


I get min temp of -32C (or -60C with latitude modifiers.) using Grand
Survey.
(Reduction of (10+273)*0.15 = 42C).  This formula is the reduction and not
the minimum temperature as someone suggested.  This situation is no use
anyway because the dayside temp is very hot so you would have problems
explaining the hydrographics.

The relatively small drop is because of the atmosphere - For a vacuum world
the formula for temp. drop is (10+273)*0.80 which would give a minumim temp
of -216C which is probably what you were expecting.

My suggestion is to have a base temperature of -194C.  This gives a max
dayside temp of 4C, increased to 16C with latitude modifiers.  This makes
both the nightside and twilight area completely uninhabitable.

An alternative would be to have a world with a very long \'year\' in an very
eccentric orbit (or possibly the effect of a binary star - Helliconia
anyone?).  The population would then have to migrate from the equator (in
winter) to the poles (in summer).  I would be a lot more confident with the
temperature calculations in this case than for a tidally locked world and
you can even have a normal day.

Mark.
