    'body' => 'At 10:03 AM 12/8/99 -0500, you wrote:

> >Recently, I have been introduced to (and I have devoured) Neil Postman\'s
> >excellent "Amusing Ourselves to Death", which is an excellent book that
> >deals with the effect of television on society.
>
>Postman... I\'m familiar with his work. A modern-day Luddite and
>technophobe. In one of his recent works (I don\'t remember which), he
>claimed that the rate of technological change was disorienting to
>people.

Technopoly, by Neil Postman, starts with an explanation how literacy is the 
downfall of memorization.  Makes you wonder how you are supposed to read 
the book.  :)

Seriously, I never saw Postman\'s work as a sign that we should stop being 
literate and destroy our toasters, rather just an interesting read on the 
markers and influences of our society.  He might be absolutely correct, 
however I enjoy reading books and toasting bread.  Given the number of 
writers that theorize everything under the sun, I am sure that someone has 
written a counter argument to Postman, and a counter-counter argument to 
that guy, and. . .


 >course the economic counter-argument is extremely compelling! Maybe wargames
> >were victims of this epistemological shift, who knows. Actually, now that I
> >think about it, the rise of collectable trading card games and story and
> >picture-heavy RPGs makes a hell of a lot of sense.
>
>Don\'t overestimate the collectible trading card game market. Back when
>Magic: The Gathering was at its peak, one CCG fan insisted that CCGs would
>displace RPGs the way RPGs displaced wargames. Hasn\'t happened. Won\'t happen.

True, but CCGs have seriously displaced where the money of roleplayers is 
going.  Wargames are still being played and created, but nothing like the 
scale how like they were before RPGs.  There definitely has been a vast 
shrinking of the roleplaying gaming "industry".  From the estimates I have 
heard, the industry is one twentieth the size it was ten years 
ago.  Personally, I am pointing my fingers at CRPGs, and not CCGs.

Of course, that doesn\'t stop me from playing Alpha Centauri.  So it goes.


> >What does public discourse in the Traveller universe look like? What is the
> >dominant medium? What changes might appear as a result? Is this general
> >decline in the political arena one of the reasons for the fall of the Second
> >Imperium, and for the rise of the nobility in the Third Imperium?
>
>The speed of communication will have an effect, no matter what the dominant
>medium is. I would suspect that there will be variations in the dominant
>media from place to place. Some high-tech cultures will be very much
>oriented to television, while other high-tech cultures will eschew TV
>entirely, getting their information from their version of the Internet.

Technology will seriously effect how information is transmitted.  Since 
there are a huge variety of tech levels in the Imperium, beyond Xboats, 
styles of communication will definately be a local or subsector phenomenon.

Planets V, W & X might have an immersive hologrid communications network 
that operates with a small fleet of Xboat-like communication couriers, 
Planet Y has telegraph and a postal service, while Planet Z has a system 
wide Internet ran via Windows5000 (Gov code is 1, unless Win5K crashes, and 
then it is a 0 until it reboots).


>(Speaking of which, since I got my cable modem 3 years ago, I tend to watch
>less TV...)

Ditto.  More time for the TML. ;)
