    'topic' => ' electronic warfare',
    'body' => 'At 08:30 AM 12/9/1999 +1300, you wrote:

>As a straight Intell guy (transfered from being a grunt) I spend quite 
>a lot of time carrying one of those things at platoon or section level 
>(the NZ Army still uses PRC-77s at about 20lbs), and we used to avoid 
>talking as much as possible. We were generally quite successful as long 
>as we could talk the company OCs out of requiring full SitReps every 
>hour (and often on the hour). Sometimes I wonder about the mentality of 
>people who become officers. 

This will be a limiting factor on the Imperial Army.  Even with tanks that
fly at 600mph and weapon ranges of over ten miles, the need to shield
communications from detection will shorten the front a unit can fight on.
The IA will live and die on its laser and meson com systems.

This makes for an obvious tactic: drop a lot of blackout and prism smoke.
The enemy can\'t send laser signals, and if he doesn\'t possess meson coms,
he\'s pretty screwed.  Now the Zhodani, they just make sure that one of
their "commissioned specialists" is riding along to provide uninterrupted
comms.

Oh, Rupert?  The prick-77 weighs about 20lbs at the *beginning* of the
movement.  After the first few miles, it starts to weigh on the order of
several tons.  As does the M-16, your helmet, your beard stubble...

*That\'s* the answer!  Bruce, the missing mass of the universe accumulates
in soldiers on road marches!  Woo-Hoo, Noble prize, here I come!



