I don\'t see comms as a limiting factor for high-tech troops. A combination
of even today\'s technology is pretty hard to beat (just not the man-portable
versions). If every MIB is communicating with a combination of stuff which
we understand today, like frequency hopping, direct-sequence spread
spectrum, etc, plus whatever stuff the advanced TLs bring, you will have a
very hard time stopping him from communicating. If you are ahead by a TL or
two, that\'s a different story. In that case, he will not have a prayer.

Obscuring line-of-sight comms may also be fairly difficult at advanced TLs.
Even today, we have systems (thermal imagers) which can see through smoke
and fog. (Ask the Iraqis how well these systems let you see through thick
black smoke.) With frequency-agile lasers at advanced TLs, you will be able
to adapt to any obscurants.

Exactly how do these prismatic aerosols work anyway? What is the effect
used? Is this even plausible? Are the effects caused by absorption?
Refraction? Scattering? Deus ex machina?

</rambling>
