    'month' => '12',
    'body' => '>From: isteve@outhere.f9.co.uk

>How do people handle salvage rights?  For that 
>matter, how do they work in the real world?

My understanding is as follows:  

To accomplish a salvage, you have to find a ship with
no living thing aboard (the rule is a little strange
in the real world, where the ship\'s dog counts as a
living thing, but the rats and any plant life do not)
and bring it back to civilization.  

In my Traveller universe, "no living thing" means "no
living sophont."  The ship\'s dog, as much as I love
dogs, doesn\'t count.

As the salvager, you get a lien on the ship, equal to
some percentage of its current fair market value.  I
think it\'s 10% today.  The owner of the ship must pay
that to you in order to get the ship back.  

Who is the owner of the ship now?  It depends.

If a corporation owned it before whatever happened, it
still owns it.  If all of the shareholders of the
corporation were the crew, see below.

If an individual or a partnership owns it, and the
individual or partners are all crew (and therefore
dead), then their estates own it, and there will be
probate litigation somewhere (jurisdiction is the
subject of another treatise that I\'ve been working
on).  

If a partnership owns it, and one or more partners
survived, they own it by right of survivorship -- no
probate, title just passes automatically.  The same is
true if a married couple owned it and one spouse
survived.  Bear in mind that "survived" probably means
that person wasn\'t aboard at all before whatever
happened happened, and may show up a long time later
(and false claims are also an issue -- "yeah, the
owner aboard was my wife, yeah, that\'s the ticket, my
wife, so I own it").  

If the owner refuses to pay your salvage fee, you may
foreclose the lien, have the ship sold by the Imperial
admiralty authorities, and take your percentage of the
sale price -- but see infra regarding lien priority.

If the ship is under financing, the lender has a lien
on the ship.  I don\'t whether it has priority over the
salvage lien under contemporary or Imperial law. 
Let\'s suppose that it does (prior in time is prior in
right, ordinarily).  If you foreclose your junior
salvage lien and sell the vessel, the buyer takes it
subject to the lender\'s senior lien.  

If the salvage lien has priority, foreclosing it would
also foreclose the lender\'s lien, so the buyer would
have to pay it off as well.  That doesn\'t make good
economic sense, so the salvage lien probably does not
have priority.

Another factor to consider is valuation.  Someone will
have to appraise the vessel to determine its fair
market value and, thus, the value of the salvage lien.
The appraiser may be competent or incompetent, corrupt
or not corrupt.  The owner of the vessel will want as
low an appraisal as possible (unless they are seeking
refinancing, in which case they will want as high a
value as possible), but the salvagers will want a high
value.  It\'s an opportunity for role playing.

>How does it work in the real world, any legal eagles 
>specialising in International Maritime Law on the 
>list?  

I don\'t specialize in maritime law (although many
years ago I did interview for a job doing it, and
thought it would have been fun).  

>For that matter is this covered by canon?

Not so far as I recall.

- --Glenn
