This is how I interpreted the book, and why I thought the movie was a fine
adaptation. I can see how the two seem very different, but one must remember
that a book and a movie have very different ways of communicating. Take Bram
Stokers Dracula, both the book and the movie. There are major differences in
the two, but I felt the movie was very true to the *feeling* of the book. It
took me a few times watching it, as I had an emotional revulsion to certain
bits in the movie that initially seemed contrary to the book, but the
intended audience is in a very different time period. This, and the "show,
don\'t tell" nature of film media are the main reasons for changes between
the two. ST the book was very serious in tone, ST the movie was a farce,
bordering on slapstick at times. I can see that raising hackles on Heinlein
fans, and I was disoriented myself on my first viewing. But it had been some
time since I had read the book, so I was able to experience the movie as a
separate work.
