[Great stuff deleted, all true in the real world, anyway.]

The only point I would add is that it\'s not clear what rights the Imperium
itself holds. In English common law (as I understand it) the Lord of the
Manor was entitled to take whatever washed up on his property. Since the
Imperium holds little real estate directly, but claims control of all
interplanetary and interstellar space, it may be that ships found derelict
and drifting belong first to the Imperium, while wrecks would fall under
planetary jurisdiction. It would be in the Emperor\'s interest to pay a
generous reward for salvage, though, because it discourages piracy.

>>How does it work in the real world, any legal eagles 
>>specialising in International Maritime Law on the 
>>list?  

"Salvage" actually covers any action taken to rescue a ship in distress,
even if the crew is still onboard. Depending on how difficult and dangerous
the assistance turns out to be, the salvors can be entitled to up to 50% of
the value of the salvaged vessel. The bottom line, though is: "No cure --
no pay."

Military vessels are immune to salvage liens.

Steve Daniels, our other lawyer, provided the following links in response
to a request for information from me:

>This looks like a nearly perfect site for you:
>
>http://www.safesea.com/salvage/salcon_89/salcon_89.html
>I\'m working my way through this -- it\'s good stuff.
>
>I think you could lift whole sections of this and adapt it to GT.
>
>It seems that a lot of companies use the Lloyd\'s Standard
>Form of Salvage Agreement, which requires that English
>law be applied.
>
>Here\'s the link to Lloyd\'s if you haven\'t seen it.
>http://www.lloyds.com/homepages/agencysalvage_hp.htm
>
>There you can download the form itself and see examples
>of it in action.  The form is governed by UK law, which
>explicitly uses the International Convention on Salvage as it is
>incorporated into UK law, in the Merchant Shipping Act.

>>For that matter is this covered by canon?

"Annic Nova," JTAS #1, p. 30, says:

"...this ship is allowed in imperial commerce under the salvage laws
provided the ship is registered with imperial authorities (typical
registration fee: Cr100,000)."

That text was not included in Dbl Adv 1, however.

Adv. 13 (Signal GK), p. 46, adds:

"The Imperial Navigation Act of 103 requires all vessels, whether military
or civilian, to respond to the GK, SOS, or Mayday signals, provided such
response does not endanger the ship and crew of the responding vessel."

This subject comes up briefly in GT: Far Trader (pp. 60-61, 71 & 114) and
GT: Starports, and will be covered in considerable detail in the
forthcoming GT: Starships.
 
