    'topic' => 'SEC: UNCLASSIFIED SAAB',
    'body' => 'The thing with SAAB was that it\'s initial season was really uneven, but it
should have been given a chance.  Every SF show, it seems, needs a season to
work out the kinks.  I tried watching B5 the first season and was repulsed.
Started watching again in the 3rd one and was totally hooked!  Same with
S:TNG. Not that it every got really good IMO, but it went from terrible to
okay by third season.
Back to SAAB Problems:
1.	It needed someone with military knowledge as an assistant director
(or maybe someone who had once read a book about the military, or who had
lived within a few miles of an army base or SOMETHING! :-) 
2.	The banking fighters were okay.  They were semi-realistic with the
rolling ability and stuff, but why not go all the way and do vector
movement?
3.	Some episodes were unwatchable due to bad acting and writing.  The
"Little tank that could" one was terrible and the "Flickering light as psych
weapon" one was beyond horrible. 

Having said that, I thought some episodes were brilliant: "Who Monitors the
Birds" was great!  I should\'ve been given some time to get its legs under
itself...
Lesson for SF TV writers:  Keep the number of characters small so you can
actually develop them a little!  Three main characters with 3 secondary
seems to be a winning formula (Think Kirk / Spock / McCoy with Scotty / Sulu
/ Chekov).
Charles C.

RANT BEGINS

Bad Charles, naughty Charles. 

I loved everything EVERYTHING about that show. IMHO I thought it was close
to Trav as a show could be (apart from FTL and quick jumps). The writing was
just friggin\' superb - what else could you expect from Wong and Morgan (if
there were publicity pics of those two, there would be some sort of shrine
in their honour) and whatever writers they brought on board. 

It kicked the living poop out of anything else I have ever EVER seen in the
Sci Fi world. And as for Marines/Pilots, everyone knows that\'s a plot
device. You can\'t have a show with just pilots - that\'d be as boring as
hell. There has to be justification for them being on the ground and being a
combo trained force is good enough for me. Geez, look at ST. Teleporters?
Just a way to get the protagonists into the action without boring screen
time wasting link scenes.  I never hated the writing, not once. 

Plus I loved the idea of Tanks (Nipple Necks), the AI\'s and the whole secret
within a secret within a secret that M&W are so very good at using - a layer
off every couple of episodes.

So I\'ll be god damned before I see people slagging off this magnificent
program <grinny grin grin> . . . . and curse the near-sighted dicks at FOX
that let it die.  


RANT ENDS

Oh yeah, 5-6 characters can work and work well. IMO it did in SAAB. Each
character had excellent motivation or overlying stresses which came out time
and time again.

As for favourite episode - Cooper Hawke\'s origin. They way they interspersed
the present (where he was stalking chigs - no dialogue whatsoever) with the
flashbacks to his past, to date is the finest sci-fi episode of anything I
have ever seen.

Bravo - many hats into air. 


