    'date' => 'Wed, 8 Dec 1999 17:16:00  0800 (PST)',
    'body' => 'Chris Seamans asked:
> So a question for the folks who have read Grossman:
> Does he take the
> socialization route, or does he take the more direct
> "cause and effect"
> route? I am putting some books on my Christmas wish
> list, and this one might
> go on it.

Well, the most important point he makes is that the
methods the army uses to make it easier for men to
kill - desensitisation to blood, guts and suffering,
firing automatically when a "target" (person) appears,
making the targets appear human, instead of just
bullseyes - are all things that are happening to kids
with their movies, tv shows, and shoot \'em up video
games. In "Time Crisis" and so on, kids take a plastic
gun with a laser beam that goes "bang!" and has a
slight recoil when they pull the trigger, and fire
directly at figures as lifelike as the computers can
make it. In the army, we did something similar, where
there was a film from first-person perspective of a
grunt patrolling through the jungle, when you saw an
"enemy" you had to shoot him, your plastic gun with
its pretend recoil and laser beam shooting him down.

I\'ll note also that in these video games, censorship
regulations mean that the figures after ebign shot
evapourate. You\'re not allowed to show blood and guts
and screaming and guys taking hours to die, crying for
their mothers, crapping in their pants, etc. Thus, the
shooting is without unpleasant consequences.

As I see it, Grossman takes the socialisation view. Of
course, if there were no guns then no-one could be
killed with guns; whether this is practical, possible,
or desirable we\'ll leave aside, but simply put, if you
ain\'t got it, you can\'t use it. The retort that there
are still knives, baseball bats etc around so the
murder rate won\'t drop doesn\'t hold water, since
people, not just soldiers, find it easier to kill if
there is a physical distance between them and their
victim. Grossman points out that the simplest way to
kill a person is to stick your thumb in their eye and
slush it about through their brain, but that he\'s
never heard of anyone doing this.

But I think for him the socialisation is more
important. The means to kill are available to anybody
who is not a paraplegic, but the desire, and, in the
end, the "guts" to do so, are a different matter. And
these games and movies are giving our kids the "guts"
to kill.

