    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'eg379',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> How do people handle salvage rights?  For that matter, how do they work in 
> the real world?
>
> For example, our heroes come across a damaged, but basically intact ship 
> adrift in the outer reaches of a remote system.  After checking
> the ship for survivors they find it deserted.  Once they manage to get the 
> power plant online, drives working and get the ship refuelled they
> decide to leave a skeleton crew aboard, get her to civilisation and claim 
> salvage rights. HOWEVER on further examination they discover this
> multi-million credit Free Trader was financed with 30 years left to pay off.

Ok, as I understand real world salvage laws, if you bring an
*abandoned* vessel into port or salvage the cargo, the owners have
first dibs at buying it from you. If you don\'t like the offer, you can
take the matter before an "admiralty court". They are likely to award
you the *market value* of the vessel and cargo, plus a reasonable
amount for what it cost you to salvage the ship/cargo. And there\'s
essentially no appeal.

So it behooves the owners to either make a *good* offer, or just let
you *have* the shp/cargo. They may offer you *somewhat* less than the
admiralty court would award on the basis of "we can give you this
*now*, rather than having to wait for the court decision". 

Players may go for this. On the other hand, they can also arrange to
have a lawyer or their "business agent" handle the matter for them.
They\'d give a deposition and be able to leave. If there are questions,
the court can usually put things on hold long enough for you to return
to that planet and clear things up. Just don\'t dawdle around getting
there. They understand about having to finish a cargo run. They won\'t
look kindly on the matter if they find out that you got word of the
problem, and *then* took a contract that sent you elsewhere.

It may also be possible to have local officials take a sworn statement
regarding whatever the court had questions about. But most of the time
they\'d rather question you themselves.

Now if the vessel you salvaged *wasn\'t* abandoned (for example, at
least one of the crew was aboard and alive) things get messier.
Basicly, this means that that crewmember is still acting as an "agent"
for the owners, and all you will get is an award for "assisting" in
getting the ship back to port. Again, smart ship owners don\'t try to be
miserly about such awards, because you can appeal them to the admiralty
court, and they generally hand out reasonable rewards. 

Finally, if the ship/cargo has been abandoned long enough (20 years? 50
years? 100 years? I don\'t recall), it belongs to whoever can salvage
it. 

> The owner/operators are dead so does the ship belong to the bank?

The bank owns the portion that wasn\'t paid for. In your example, 30
years out of 40 had been paid off, so we\'ll say that the bank owned
25%, the "owner" owned 75% (in actuality, mortages pay off more slowly
than that, until quite close to the end most of your payments go
against *interest*, not the principal).

Anyway, that gives bank 25%, heirs of the "owner(s)" 75%. 

> Is it like a mortgage where an insurance policy pays off the balance
> of the finance leaving the ship to be inherited by the owners\' next
> of kin?

Depends. If there\'s that sort of insurance, then the bank gets paid
off and the heirs "own" it, subject to the legitimate salvage claims
like I listed above. 

If it has a more common sort of insurance, the *insurance* company may
wind up owning the bank\'s share, and even that of the heirs. Especially
if they\'ve been paid by the insurance company for the loss. 

>  Or does it belong to the salvaging PCs?

Sort of. See my comments above.

