    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'For an interesting discussion of just how many ships
are needed for instellar trade.

No-one seems to have agreed on even the order of
magnitude of citizens of the Imperium, but S. John
Ross in the article reckons a settled world with a
healthy economy will have a shipping traffic of two
tons (one export, one import, talking short tons, not
displacemt tons here) per person per year. 

Now I\'m figuring a few things here:
1) At least half the galctic paopulation lives on
"settled worlds with a healthy economy" (since mining
worlds, barren worlds and the like will have far elss
people)
2) There\'s at least 1 dton of ship for every 14 tons
(ie short tons) of cargo (that is, half the ship\'s
bulk is cargo
3) Less than 1% of such cargo is carried by PC-style
"free traders."

This gives us a formula for calcuating the tonnage of
PC-style ships in the Imperium:
Td = P/28/12 x 0.01 = p x 0.0233
   Td = Tonnage (dtons)
   P= Population
   /28 because of displ. tons to short tons
conversion, times 2 for import/export
   /12 because ships make on average one round trip a
month
   x 0.01 because only 1% of traffic is free trader
traffic

Even if you population is on the down estimate side,
(say, 650 billion: a hundred million per each of half
the 11,000 worlds, forgetting Alsan, Hivers etc) you
get pretty huge numbers of free traders running around
out there; divide this dtonnage number by, say, 500,
to get the number of ships. (You get from this 1300
million)

_This_ is why I say, mortgages don\'t work so well in
traveller. Too easy to just fly a long way away. Think
of debts on cars - so long as you don\'t mind leaving
the country forever, it\'s easy to skip out. Most
people, of course, don\'t want to leave their home
forever. But then, most people aren\'t Travellers <grin>

