> distiguish between craft recovered by civilians vs. craft
> recovered by the military?

IMHO/IMTU:

The term "prizes" refers to ships and/or cargo _seized_ through
legitimate means.  Thus, military vessels engaged in commerce raiding,
privateers, patrol ships performing customs duties, and civilian vessels
that defeat would-be pirates all can claim their vanquished foes as
"prizes."  Neither the original owner of the prize ship or cargo, nor
any creditors of the prize ship\'s or cargo\'s owner, have any claim to
the prize.

Note that pirates often refer to their victims as "prizes."  This in no
way confers any legal rights to the pirates, as piracy is not a
"legitimate" activity.

"Salvage rights", OTOH, refers to the right of a civilian ship\'s captain
and crew to monetary gain in exchange for _finding_ a ship or cargo in
distress, and assisting that ship and/or cargo in reaching a safe port. 
The original owner of the ship or cargo, as well as any creditors of the
ship or cargo in question, may have rights, in accordance with Admiralty
law.  Generally speaking, special Admiralty courts will adjudicate and
enforce the rights of the various parties involved.

