    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> I agree. Scouts use radios too much, company commanders use radios too much, 
> and forward observers might as well just call me on a phone and *tell* me 
> where they are. \'Course, I *liked* it that way.

One of Marc Steigler\'s early books has a weapons system that uses that
sort of info to locate company, regimental or even battalion command
centers (forgive me if I got that ranking out of order). Then it pounds
them flat. 

Sort of an infantry version of the "kill the command tank" bit that
anti-tank folks are so fond of. 

> In the Persian Gulf I was briefing the 6th Light Armor (French) and asked 
> how long they thought they could speak on the radio before an enemy could 
> fix their position. The concensus was 15 seconds. When I told them that in 
> 15 seconds the rounds would already be in the air, they thought I was 
> kidding. During the war the tactical elements were pretty quiet, but their 
> commanders and support were often on for 1+ minute at a time. And most 
> armies aren\'t any better. Commanders get \'addicted\' to information very 
> quickly, especially in high-stress situations like combat. Generals \'need\' 
> to know what is happening in that critical battalion, company commanders 
> \'must have\' artillery support right now, etc. If you leave them alone for a 
> time, they do what they are trained to do - trust the equipment.
> Then you kill them.


Which is why my idea of the "best" "simple invention that chages the
world beyond recognition" is a communications device that is
*inherently* untappable. You "tune" to a receiver, and if it is "free"
you connect and can exchange info. If someone else is connected, you
can\'t "connect" and in neither case can you determine *where* the
receiver is. Range, maybe. Bearing? Nope!

So you can\'t triangulate and you can\'t intercept. Nor can you "jam" a
unit unless they drop the link. So everybody\'d just leave it up. Or
leave it turned off until they needed it.

First it\'d drive "spooks" nuts, because they unless they actually
*locate* a spy\'s comm gear they can\'t tell if he\'s got any!

Next it\'d ELINT types crazy, because there\'d be no intercepts. 

Then comes the fun when folks start using it for stuff like remotely
piloted vehicles.

> ObTrav: Imperial Intelligence probably has a whole lotta\' electronic warfare 
> stuff, ranging from deep space listening arrays to detect old radio signals 
> from solar systems 3-4 light years away to \'tramp far traders\' that actually 
> have tons of electronics in their bay and an extendable antenna in their air 
> raft berth

Or the stunt I\'ve described many a time. 

Pop into a system well out of the ecliptic, and several AU from any of
the planets. Monitor to your heart\'s content for 5 days or so, then
jump back to base with the info. 

As long as you vary the location, there\'s not a *damn* thing the
