  {
    'body' => 'How about this for a way to prevent skipping? Every time you make the
payment on your ship, you get some sort of update to your ship\'s
identification transponder. Without the update, your transponder will not
function, or it still functions, but  you will be identified as one of
*those* people to the authorities. The updating is done using high TL
cryptography, so any sophisticated attempt to bypass the security will cost
more to mount than the ship is worth. There is some sort of grace period,
say 90 days, before the transponder stops functioning normally. Or the grace
period may be configurable, so that with permission (that is advance
payments made) from the lienholder you can go on extended journeys. I
envision this service being performed by a trusted third party, neither the
bank nor the ship owner. Probably a service which some sort of government
provides. Planetary? Imperial?

Just in case anyone is curious, a number of companies today are developing
the technology to use cryptographic techniques to limit access to goods or
services to paying customers.  You can create digital music which you need
to pay per listening for, and so forth. By advanced TLs, this will be a very
advanced technology. I assume that some of the really dangerous toys (FGMPs,
Battle Dress, nuclear weapons, etc) will have some sort of advanced
technology preventing unauthorized use. You can steal it, but you can\'t use
it.

You might even have civilian shipboard weapons locked up in a very secure
way, so that strict licensing requirements for their operation can be
enforced. For example, in peaceful regions of space it may be illegal to
have weapons unlocked. When you travel to the more dangerous places, you
apply for a license for the use of your weapons. A suitable government
representative performs the unlocking for you, which is only valid for a
preset interval.

Another application is to shipboard software. You use a cryptographic
technique of some sort to activate the software. This way you can\'t just
make a copy of that Predict-12 program for your friends to use.

</rambling>
