(273 + 10) * 0.15 = 283 K * 0.15 = 4.245 K

> Hmm, I hadn\'t considered that the units might be Kelvin, but it seems odd
> to mix units like that, no?  Anyway, I\'ll check tonite to see if that
> works out.  Also, I\'m pretty sure the formula I gave was the effect of
> nighttime cooling.  So the 42.45 degrees is subtracted from the base temp,
> giving an even warmer cold pole at around -30 C.

Actually, the "size" of a Kelvin and a degree Celcius are
identical.  Converting from one scale to the other is a
matter of adding or subtracting 273.15 of those units.  I\'m
guessing that the author(s) of the text you are working
from rounded this down to 273 (a common practice for
approximations).  So, they aren\'t mixing them, the
addition of 273 is a conversion factor.  The result (4.245)
is a Kelvin measure, so you don\'t subtract it from the
base.  That would only give you a cold pole temp of less
than 6 deg. C.  I believe the correct temp would be
slightly less than -269 deg. C.

