>
>It has been written by the heretic Keith Jackson:

Excuse me as I find some MIB\'s to kick down your door and drag you away for 
"reeducation".  ;)


>One twentieth? Somehow that doesn\'t seem right. I say,
>thank the CCGs, for they have done a service and taken
>the Rule Lawyers from our games. Rule Lawyers never
>roleplayed, they just wanted to know all the rules so
>that they could prevent their set of statistics on the
>character sheet all being reduced to zero. Rules
>Lawyers for this reason were also a source of
>munchkinism. But most of them have gone to CCGs, since
>CCGs are nothing but rules, no imagination required.
>For this reason, I always have a pack of cards, magic,
>or whatever\'s the cheapest, in case some new player
>turns out to be a Rules Lawyer or munchkin. I hand him
>that (him ain\'t sexist, never met a female gamer who
>was a rules lawyer or munchkin) and we\'re all happy.

Ironically, I know of several people who were very good roleplayers who 
switched to playing nothing but CCGs simply because all of their gaming 
buddies were also spending cash on CCGs, and not RPGs.  They didn\'t have to 
worry about the gamers flaking an cancelling at the last minute, what time 
the game started or ends, or if the plot was going to get boring or 
not.  Get anyone who plays the game together, pull out your decks, and you 
are set for about an hour or two.  The thing that made me stop buying CCGs 
wasn\'t the fact that there were wasn\'t roleplaying potential for it, rather 
if your buddy has more money invested in having the rare ultra cool cards, 
odds were against you winning.

Regardless, any chunk of the RPG market (including Rules Lawyers) who stop 
buying games and start up another hobby, hurts the industry.


>If RPGs are declining so much, why are there so bloody
>many? The dream of GURPS has been realised, you can
>roleplay anything, even a cowboy hunting undead, for
>god\'s sake.

It was clunky as all hell, but I could do that back when I first bought 
Champions.  On the other hand, Hero Games, is a company that seems to be on 
life support right now.

I personally believe that the industry is getting stronger.  It took 
several *serious* hits in the last few years, and things were shaken up 
pretty severely.  However, I don\'t believe that there are more *active* 
companies right now than there were in the past.  IMHO, the strongest 
companies are consolidating their hold of the industry and churning out 
tons and tons of supplements.  In between the big guys are a few companies 
making a decent showing, and a lot of fly by night operations that flare 
momentarily and then vanish into obscurity.  As far as I can tell, the 
entire market isn\'t even remotely the size it was during the late eighties 
or early nineties, however it is improving dramatically.

I think that there are a lot of games on the shelves, simply because to 
sell a game, you need to hook someone and then pump out supplement after 
supplement to feed their addiction and pay your bills.  Just take a look at 
how huge the White Wolf, TSR, SJ Games, and Palladium Games sections of 
your game store is compared to say, Holistic Design or Dream Pod 9.  A lot 
of supplements of a few companies, a smattering of rare games, products of 
terminally ill/dead companies and obscure games tend to fill up the 
retailers shelves.

The few major companies put out tons of material.  They are trying to win 
back the market by being aggressive.  Supplements = 
advertising.  Supplements don\'t sell as well as the core rulebooks, but the 
money you lose on them are made up by sales of the core rulebooks. Those 
major companies, like it or not, tend to be the lifeblood of the industry, 
since they draw the majority of the gamers into the store in the first 
place.  Retailers stock up on those supplements, even though they don\'t 
sell nearly as well as the core rulesbooks.  The end result is that you 
have huge shelf spaces taken up by Vampire Clanbooks, GURPS Genrebooks and 
AD&D\'s Complete Book of Fill-In-The-Blanks.  Most likely, some of those 
books will be sitting on those shelves for a long long time, simply because 
no one in your area has a desire to pick up the Euthanatos Tradition Book, 
while the Tzimisce Clanbook is flying off the shelves.

Medium sized companies make enough to pay the bills with a very small 
staff, and thus the rate new books that are released is significantly 
different compared to, say, SJ Games.  They have enough loyal customers to 
make a retailer stock them, however they don\'t fly off the shelves like the 
major companies.  DP9\'s Southern Republic Leaguebook is going to have a 
much longer shelf life than the Ravnos Clanbook will.  Where these games 
thrive the most is on the internet, and online stores, where Heavy Gear 
fans scattered over the globe can get the latest fix of life on Terra 
Nova.  Odds are their local game store doesn\'t have racks of DP9 books, and 
if they do, I bet they don\'t have racks of Fading Suns, or Star Trek, or ...

The smaller companies don\'t tend to put much out at all.  A book here, a 
book there.  The interest for a relatively small game isn\'t that 
stimulated, and so the books aren\'t flying off the shelves.  Thus, they 
make less money back, and it takes longer for them to put out another 
book.  Usually, when you see their book in the game store, it\'s the same 
book you saw last week.  Not only that, but the company might have gone out 
of business a few years ago, and the book is still sitting on the shelves.

With all that said, I believe that the sales of RPGs are steadily getting 
better and better.  The major companies have generally revamped their 
systems and poured new lifeblood into their books.  White Wolf, for 
example, has cut out a lot of the crap they did in their previous works, 
and focused on fine tuning their game system and stimulated the interest of 
players by making a more interesting and engaging setting.  Most players 
are flocking to the store to buy one of the major companies products, and 
then from their they branch out into other games.  Vampire fans become Mage 
fans, which become Fading Suns or Over the Edge fans.


>There has been a decline, I agree, but not _that_ much.

While I agree that 1/20th sounds pretty crazy, the people quoting it are 
the ones with their fingers on the pulse of the industry.  Now, since the 
sampling of how well games sell is not even remotely exact, I have no doubt 
that that figure is off a bit.  Game companies and distributors don\'t 
exactly share their financial data, and any sampling will be bound to be 
inaccurate.  How much, and in what direction, I have no clue.

Personally, I\'m not that suprised with that figure.  Remember Hero Games, 
Iron Crown, R. Talsorian or West End Games?  They aren\'t dead, but they 
certainly aren\'t moving very fast.  :(
