A very good point.  Here in the uSA, most folks believe
the perception and don\'t bother to learn the truth.  The
united States Constitution is still the supreme law of the
land and each state has a constitution and that
constitution is still the supreme law of that state.  If you
understand our legal system, you will find that most of the
codes in fact do not apply to you unless you allow them
to.  Most of the codes are blatantly unconstitution, except
for one little thing.  Legally speaking, "shall" and "must"
means "may."  So, where the code says something like,
"In order to use public hiways and roads, a driver must be
licenced by the D.M.V."  What it really means is, "In order
to use public hiways and roads, a driver may be licenced
by the D.M.V."

I tried to explain to someone why I don\'t have a driver\'s
licence and he just wouldn\'t understand.  In spite of the
spin doctors press to the contrary, we still live in a
republic and those who are willing can still live as free
solvereigns.  The right to travel is still guarenteed by the
uS Constitution (9th Ammendment) and I still have the
right to travel without interferance by anyone, including
people in costume who claim to be public servants
provided I don\'t break the law (and I don\'t mean the
code, most of which does not apply to me anyway).

I tried to explain that getting a licence would obligate me
in ways that I didn\'t want to be obligated and that I could
avoid, just by not having a drivers licence.  I explained
that I didn\'t drive and he said that he had seen me driving.
I told him that legally speaking, I no longer drove, which is
a commercial activity, but he just couldn\'t or wouldn\'t
understand.  But, that okay, he doesn\'t have to as long as
I do.  And I guarentee you that the judges understand it
quite well.

Ob Trav:  I suggested adding a little ethical spice to a
senario offered a few days ago that is based upon this
very idea.
