    'body' => '>How do people handle salvage rights?  For that matter, how do they work in 
>the real world?

Assuming all ships in your Traveller Universe are registered with a central 
authority and have a Transponder. It should be possible to trace the legal 
owner of any vessel. If the owner was killed when whatever happened to the 
vessel happened then the vessel register should also contain the next of 
kin.

But what if theres outstanding finance?
If there was money outstanding on the vessel that has not been paid then the 
ship may have been reposessed by the bank in which case the ship register 
will have changed to show the banks ownership. If it hasn\'t been reposessed 
then the next of kin will inherit a large debt and a wrecked ship.

Insurance?
If you have found someone insane enough to insure a vessel, and they pay out 
on the policy, the ship now belongs to them and is probably listed on their 
accounts as an asset. But again they would now be listed as the legal owner 
on in the ship register.

So nearly all ships have a legal owner, so whats the point in salvaging. 
Well for some ships it may be impossible to trace the owners in which case 
the ship could become the property of the salvager after a period of time. 
Ships from outside the imperium are eligible for salvage (eg, the Annic Nova 
in DA1). Ships that the issurance companies eventually write off are 
salvageable and if your feeling kind you could allow the salvagers to take 
ownership of any cargo on recovered ships even if an owner is found.

This way the PC\'s can make some money out of salvage but not so much that 
they have fleets of ships.

J.

