	I like the Captain Cook model myself.  Sure there is risk to
	the officer who has cost a lot to train, but there is also
	a risk in letting a less-trained officer make first contact
	with a new civilization.  Of course, not all landing parties
	involve first contact, but the judgement of the senior
	officer aboard may be valuable in a lot of ways.

	Also remember that the captain may just want to see the world
	for her/himself (that may be why they signed up in the first
	place).  The captain may also be itching to get off the ship
	after long periods in relatively cramped quarters.  Every
	officer is different, of course, but unless regulations
	prohibit such actions some captains may insist on getting
	their hands dirty (some may even find a way around certain
	regulations).

	Finally, there is the fun factor.  Wherever possible, I like
	to have the PCs in charge.  If there is a commanding officer,
	I almost always want it to be a PC.  If that PC prefers to
	stay out of the action, that\'s OK, but if they want to go
	down with the first landing party, that\'s great.  I don\'t
	really think that a totally realistic universe would be all
	that fun to RPG in (see the Real World (tm)), so I don\'t mind
	allowing the PCs a little latitude in this regard.

