    'body' => 'From: cos 90 <cos90@powersurfr.com>


> What, he argues *against* quality television shows???

It depends on what you mean by "quality". If you mean, say, shows that tell
a compelling story through picture and sound (what television is good at),
then no, he doesn\'t argue against quality television. In fact, he makes the
claim that television doesn\'t take that job seriously enough. If, on the
other hand, you mean "quality" in the sense of programs with marginal
educational content, or some sort of lasting informational content, then
yes, he does argue against quality television.

When people make claims that there is too much crap on television, they
usually mean that "good" programs will be educational in nature. In this
sense, Sesame Street would be good, while, say Power Rangers would be bad.
He\'s not arguing against a better Power Rangers, he\'s arguing against any
sort of Sesame Street at all.

That doesn\'t mean that he\'s arguing that kids shouldn\'t be educated, just
that giving them something which kind of resembles an education through a
series of unconnected, commercial length vignettes may not be such a great
idea. It is his argument that perhaps education should not be the domain of
*entertainment*, and specifically an entertainment medium in which short and
non-challenging segments are absolute requirements. To support

In the same vein, but on a different topic, he argues that the American
political process has been changed fundamentally, for the worse, by the
integration of television into the political process, for the same reason.
The coarse version of his argument is: Perhaps our candidates should not be
selected on the basis of how photogenic they are, or how well they can spit
out one-line soundbites.

This is the direction that television goes *naturally*, because this is what
television is best at.

> "Beneficial to society as a whole", from the perspective of what *he*
>deems valuable in a society, which may or may not be what others
>find valuable.

One can argue, convincingly, that the "game of marbles" style of politics
that has been standard in America since the advent of television is *not*
beneficial to society as a whole, as one example.

To move away from Postman now, I\'ll inject my own comments:

Your claim is that the youth of today are reacting appropriately to new
technologies as they appear. I hope that\'s a fair characterization. I would
disagree with this wholeheartedly. I\'m a *huge* movie buff. I go to see lots
of new movies. I suspect you\'ve gathered that much already from our offlist
correspondence. My moviegoing experience has changed since the advent of the
beeper, but even moreso since the advent of the cellphone. Now it\'s
extremely common to hear one or more people in the audience receive a
cellphone call or a page. It\'s also common for people nearby to call their
friends to tell them how cool the scene they just saw was, or how they got
suckered into going to see a terrible movie. Don\'t even get me started on
laser pointers... you haven\'t lived until you\'ve seen a stylized hand with
an extended middle finger superimposed over Keanu Reeves\'s face in The
Matrix, or a dinosaur head superimposed devouring Will Smith in Enemy of the
State. Then there is that growing segment of people, kids and older folks
alike, who treat the movie-going experience as if they were watching a
really big screen TV at home, chatting throughout the entire movie.

I\'ll admit, I haven\'t done a study on this or anything, but I do know that
even in my relatively short experience as a movie freak, that the experience
of going to the movies has deteriorated immensely as a result of the
inappropriate integration of technology into everyday life... even *if* you
remove the chatting in movie theaters, which may be controversial and it
might be argued was always with us. I would disagree, personally, simply
because there was a lot less of it when I was growing up.

Having been the recipient of email bombs sent by kids who don\'t like to have
their points argued against on Usenet (points which, coincidentally, smacked
of television slogan-mongering). Having been in a class where a student,
upon receiving a cellphone call, argued with the teacher that he was a
paying customer, and as such had some sort of moral right to receive calls
whenever they came in, whether or not those calls were distracting to the
class.

I will continue to maintain that there *are* inappropriate responses to
technology, and the ones I\'ve illustrated exist purely on a personal level.
I don\'t even want to begin to speculate on what the impact of these
technologies are on a broader level. For example, television networks have
been taking it upon themselves to define (or perhaps redefine) American
morality through commercial length snippets. In these little "morality"
commercials, you will frequently hear comments such as, "...violence is
*never* the solution to *any* problem." There are also frequent
exhortations, frequently aimed at children, to talk to a counselor or
therapist.

Which brings us back to the point that I raised in my first post on the
subject, the thread which resulted has now strayed off topic. I can bring it
back on topic, and indeed would like to. Unfortunately, in just over two
hours I will be battling (to the death, I might add) with Impressionism,
Expressionism, German Expressionism and Non-Objective Art in my Art History
final.

My interest is not purely academic, as I have the hefty sum of one American
dollar riding on whether or not Cezanne\'s "The Great Bathers" ends up
projected on the wall during our exam.

