    'topic' => 're: Well guys, there goes our salvage...',
    'body' => '>From: Dan Roseberry <rosebee@troi.csw.net>

>Here\'s a question thats confused me:  How would the
3I
>characterize the difference between \'salvage rights\' 
>and \'prizes\'? Do the terms overlap, or are they meant

>to distiguish between craft recovered by civilians 
>vs. craft recovered by the military?

Close.  It doesn\'t matter (much) whether the
recovering party is civilian or military; rather, the
distinction hinges on the recovered ship.

A prize is ship captured during wartime.  Either a
civilian or a naval ship may be a prize.  

A salvage is a lost, derelict, or distressed ship that
has been recovered or rescued.  Only civilian ships
may become salvage; naval ships remain the property of
their government, free of lien, although most
governments will give a reward for recovery and
return.

If a civilian ship has become derelict, etc., because
of enemy action in wartime it will become a prize if
recovered by the enemy; salvage if recovered by a
non-belligerent; and what I call "quasi-salvage" if
recovered by its own side.  

If someone from the same side recovers the ship during
or conceivably after the war, they may not be entitled
to full salvage rights, or their rights may be
deferred until the end of hostilities, to the extent
that salvage rights conflict with war aims or
expedience.  

- --Glenn
