    'topic' => 're: Well guys, there goes our salvage...',
    'body' => '>From: Walter Smith <SmithW@HARTWICK.EDU>

>Black ICE wrote:>>>>>>>>>
>>The term "prizes" refers to ships and/or cargo 
>>_seized_ through legitimate means.  
[deletion]
>Wait a minute. If Sunbeard steals my company\'s Patrol
> Cruiser, and your merchant crew gets lucky and wins 
>his boarding action against you, you now own my ship 
>outright?

Maybe; it depends.  If that the result, the law is
simply penalizing your company for letting a pirate
get control of the ship.  That\'s not necessarily a bad
result.  (Self-defense could be a legitimate means of
seizure, to use Black Ice\'s terms, so the merchant is
taking the patrol cruiser as a prize.)  

The bank\'s security interest in the ship and the loan
that it secures would be unaffected. 

It\'s more likely, however, that the merchant will be
deemed to have salvaged the patrol cruiser, and will
have a salvor\'s lien, but your company will still have
title.  That would happen in my Traveller universe,
where prizes may only be taken in wartime by
belligerents from belligerents.  Piracy is simply
criminal activity, not the making of war by a
sovereign against a sovereign, so no prizes may be
taken.

This reminds me of rhetoric that I\'ve read from 16th
and 17th Century pirates living in the Caribbean and
Madagascar.  Some considered themselves sovereign
states at war with the rest of the world, entitled to
take any ship as a prize.  That argument won\'t fly in
an Imperial Admiralty Court any better than it did in
the London admiralty court.  

>If the Captain of such a new ship breaks a bad 
> smuggling law and his ship gets seized, does the 
>bank lose all their interest in the ship as well?

Worlds that seize ships without good reason will find
themselves de facto interdicted, and TAS at least will
give them a red zone classification.  Ships just won\'t
go there.  

Worlds that seize ships and don\'t provide some means
for the financing parties to get compensated will also
find themselves de facto interdicted, because the
banks won\'t lend to companies whose business plans
call for travel to that world.

>Or does the mortgage contract have a clause that, if 
>the Captain ever uses his ship in a fashion that will

>get it seized, he is immediately considered to be in 
>breach of contract, and *no longer* the legitimate
>owner of the vessel? 

The captain is not necessarily the owner, anyway -- 
it\'s usually some corporation like Al Morai or Tukera,
or even Jamison Factors -- and it doesn\'t make any
difference.  

The financing contract is between the owner and the
lender.  If the owner\'s employees (i.e., captain and
crew) become pirates, the owner still owes the lender.
 The contract probably does provide that, if the ship
is being used for the commission of a crime (and crime
may be defined quite specifically in the contract),
the borrower is in breach, the lender may declare all
payments due immediately, and take any lawful action
(including self-help) to repossess the ship.  

- --Glenn
