I\'m speaking only from hear say but here goes...

Acording to what I understand about maritime law a ship can be claimed as
salvage if not in the possesion of \'some persons\' for a given period of
time.  After that time it is considered abandoned and is fair game to be
claimed by anyone.  Possesion is the tricky part.  If it is part on land
belonging to the ships owner it is in his possesion.  If on the land of a
third party the third party has claim to it after the time has expired.  If
on the high seas (space) or under them it\'s up for grabs BUT the first
person there can claim it for a curtain period of time without actually
moving it.

All of this can get real sticky if the salvage is in someones territorial
waters and wants to make an issue of it but if the finders get it out of
there fast enough most other countries will honor their claims.  Just don\'t
ever plan to return to that country!

Take this with a grain of salt though.  It\'s from a half remembered book on
treasure hunters trying to claim sunken treasure.  Many of them lost most or
all of the goods to the local government including our US of A and the IR of
S. (Grin)

