    'index' => 'eg481',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => '>> So, where can I go to get the correct formulas for calculating what damage
>> a falling rock will do from space and a piece of "streamlined" deadfall
>> ordnance.

I tried doing this for GT a while back, with some drastic simplifying
assumptions:

1) No energy lost on re-entry.

2) No energy _except_ gravitational potential energy. (Ie. just the energy
from dropping the rock, nothing added for orbital velocity, rotation of
location on planet, etc.)

I\'m not at all convinced I\'m right in these assumptions. (OK, I know they
are off, but I don\'t know if it\'s a significant inaccuracy or not.  The
most useful thing about this post (I think) is the formula for computing
damage, based on altitude and world information.

Leonard, feel free to improve the formula. I know you can do it :-)


============================

I\'ve been playing around with deadfall ordinance. I started out with the
assumption that DO is essentially a mass driver (electromag gun) that spits
out shells from orbit. I may be totally off base here, but figured that at
least I\'d start the ball rolling.

Quoting from Striker II (p.36):

"Bombs and missiles dropped from orbit are actually fired at the planetary
surface with a respectable initial velocity (in the order of 800 to 1200
km/h), but still take time to reach the planetary surface from high orbit."
[The actual delay is size code x 5 minutes.]

I designed a series of very short electromag guns (which seem to have the
right muzzle velocity, assuming that the KE damage from missiles and the KE
damage from shells is equivalent). I put the gun(s) in a bay, along with
two roomy crewstations and a power plant slice, and filled teh rest of the
bay with ammo. Here\'s what I got for a 250mm gun. (Note: I used tabs, so
you may have to play a bit with the formatting.)

250mm	EMass	LMass	Volume	Cost	Magazine
GTL9 (1 gun battery)	239	1,620	100	94.71	5531 rounds
GTL10 (4 gun battery)	200	2,019	100	21.33	6891 rounds
GTL11 (4 gun battery)	200	2,019	100	11.96	6891 rounds


The rounds themselves are, other than the solid shot, quite expensive. Cost
would be only 1/4 if these were regular rounds, not electromag. At GTL9 the
power plant slice is so large I can see the ships using conventional
cannons (just like in "Space Viking"!).

KE multiplier should be inserted into the following equation to determine
actual KE damage dice:

KE = KE Multiplier x Sqrt(ghR/(h+R))

where: g = gravity (Earth=1), h = altitude (miles), and R = planetary
radius (miles).

This models the conversion of potential energy to kinetic energy, then uses
that velocity with the missile KE damage equation to get GURPS damage dice.
This approach ignores frictional braking (which would depend on atmosphere
anyway), but is probably a valid first approximation.


