    'index' => 'eg490',
    'body' => 'From: Eric Henry <ehenry@newberlin.org>


> Moral Dilemna.  When i first joined this tangent i said i wondered
>about a sport ( paintball ) where you have to point a gun at
>somebody and pull a trigger.  I am not comfortable with that and
>that\'s why i haven\'t played in five years.  However, can a case be
>made that a paintball is so clearly different from a regular firearm
>that it doesn\'t matter if i point it at somebody and shoot him?  I don\'t
>know.  Barring an answer i won\'t play again.

Well, yes, a paintball gun *is* clearly different from a real gun, no two
ways about it. I\'ve seen some at least one response in this thread, which
tries to answer your question by posing the same question to fencing.

I\'m not going to take that route myself. The "answer", as it were, is very
simple:

It goes without saying that the end result of being shot with each type of
gun is quite different. Shooting someone, who is properly attired and
expecting the possibility that they might be splattered with paint, with a
paintball pellet poses no *real* moral dilemma. I\'m not trying to trivialize
your concerns, but the two are very different. Shooting somebody with a
bullet is hazardous to life and limb, while shooting somebody with a
paintball pellet is not really all that dangerous.

> Now that i\'ve left the ranks of the lurkers i hope this answers some
> questions.

Welcome to the land of the speaking! ;)
