them in. Let them play the wiscracking noble, or the party healer, or some
other supporting character who\'s likely to be protected, important, and not
a combat monster, and most of them will slowly start to roleplay. IME, it
takes about a year to get such a NGSO to become at least a part time gamer.

Coax them gently, and they tend to come around. The stubbornest I\'ve met,
however, was a man who was the non-gamer to his avid-gamer wife. He became
a rules lawyer from HELL. So bad, in fact, that no one wants to game with
him. And he\'ll only play AD&D 2nd, and only FR or DL settings, and won\'t
tolerate even the minorest of house rules, deviations from print, or
interpretations which conflict with his (unless backed up in Dragon).

Ob Trav, I find Traveller to be a wonderful means of training
roleplaying... the CT setting allows for much non-combat-oriented
adventuring. Lots of Noblesse Amour and intrigue will get most of the
romance reading gaming widows interested.

