    'body' => '>Now, how about when two private parties are involved, rather than a
>bank vs a planetary (or Imperial) government? Sunbeard steals my ship,
>you capture it when he attacks you, have you seized a prize that is
>yours free and clear, or have you recovered my stolen property?
>
IMTU, it all depends.

See, if you find a ship with no living sophonts, and tow it in, you can
claim it as a salvaged hull. You must re-register the vessel at your own
expense. you must establish the claim before the local admirality court.

If you defeat a ship which attacked you, and take it,you MAY get to claim
it as a prize. If you hold a letter of marque which applies, you probably
will. If you hold a repossession authorization for it, you definitely get
to claim it as a prize on behalf of the issuing title/lien holder.

If you attacked first, you may not claim it as prize unless you hold a repo
auth or a letter of marque; in either case, you must also have notified
them of your desire for their surrender BEFORE firing.

If you take a ship wich you did not fight, and it was operational but
unooccupied, the owners get 1 year to claim it, they you may ask for it to
be awarded to you.

If you assist a vessel in need and it turns out to still have any living
sophonts with valid legal claim to it, you may only secure a lien against
it for the cost of the rescue efforts, including standard charter rates.

All such claims go to the local admirality court, comprised of the local
noble or his representative subordinate noble, the planetary Navy\'s AiC or
his assigned subordinate, and an assigned jag officer from the IN, and if
they exists, the sector navy and subsecotr navy, plus one rep from the
IISS.

They review your claim, verify from all available records that you did not
deny or refuse succor, demand title from surviving owners aboard, violate
imperial laws of space traffic, or misrepresent your role or claim.

In the case of a vessel which has been stolen, but was taken as legitamate
prize, the 3 month probate on vessels IMTU applies; The lien holders or
owners may reclaim the ship within three months of it\'s recovery, assuming
the theft was within one year prior to recovery. If they do, they must pay
fair salvage value (10% of fair market value at time of theft) plus costs
(Charter fees plus food, fuel and ammo expenses) as a finder\'s fee. And the
theft report to the local admirality at point of discovery of the theft
must accompany such claims.

Also, onne may not strip a prize or salvage until the ship clears probate,
except to save lives.

This leads to the multiple roles of Pirates IMTU...  including skip
tracing, capturing stolen vessels, serving as starmercs (both defensive and
offensive), searching outsystems for salvage hulls, and when need be,
serving as legitamate merchants. IMTU, it is a valid career, more properly
known as a Corsair... but when times get too hard, and opportunity strikes,
well some will turn pirate. Definitely not a "Gentleman\'s Career", but also
not for the romantic swashbuckler, either. Hard-bitten, frequently dour and
grim, the average corsair officer is one part buisinessman, one part grim
optomist, and one part adrenaline junkie. Many go legit when the need for
adrenaline (or the ability to continue on the sporadic crew-shares) wanes.

