>yes, he does argue against quality television.

To rephrase, in hopes of aiding clarity:

It\'s all relative, y\'see.  Too many people, seeing something that\'s NOT AS
stupid as the rest of what\'s on television, accept that as their standard
of "intelligent."  If one believes that television is not the best medium
for presenting educational or informative/news content, to do so anyway
reduces the level of discourse to what it *is* capable of (i.e.,
commercials and sound bites).

TV presents the *illusion* of real quality.  Much like the modern electoral
college presents the *illusion* of real choice.  (Oops, veering into
another rant.)

>I will continue to maintain that there *are* inappropriate responses to
>technology, and the ones I\'ve illustrated exist purely on a personal level.
>I don\'t even want to begin to speculate on what the impact of these
>technologies are on a broader level.

Earlier this year, I read an article in _Smithsonian_ magazine (there, I\'ve
defined my source, so caveat reader) on the Amish.  Like many people, I had
believed that their society had a simple blanket prohibition against all
technology invented after, say, 1900.  The truth is both more complex and
more interesting.

From memory:  any given technology is judged, and the decision made to
adopt it or not (and if so, in what form), based on criteria like:  will
this make a task *too* easy, devaluing the work and making the user lazy?
Will it result in an intrusion on one\'s privacy?  Will it damage the
cohesion of the family, or the community?

As an example, many Amish communities have a telephone shack, much like an
outhouse.  Thus, one goes to the shack with the specific purpose of making
or receiving a telephone call.  The shack has no heat and few concessions
to comfort, so one is not tempted to just sit there on the phone and
chatter about nothing.  And unwanted callers cannot metaphorically break
down your door and invite themselves in to sell you something, even during
dinner or prayer, as is the case for most of us with phones inside our
houses.  Having been woken up this morning by a telemarketer for MCI, I
must admit I see the appeal...

To bring this back on topic:  clearly, the Amish and other deliberately
"backward" societies believe that there ARE negative consequences to
blindly embracing every new gadget to come down the pike.  I suspect that
this debate will become more and more important in every society as
technology becomes more pervasive.  As cell-phones, telecommuting, on-line
shopping, etc continue to erode the boundaries of our daily activities,
concepts like "family time" and "vacation" are on the endangered-species
list.  We all have to draw the line somewhere.

ObTrav:  PCs with wearable computers and headsets or, better yet, implants.
 24-hour-a-day head spam.  Need I say more?


