    'topic' => ' Well guys, there goes our salvage...',
    'body' => 'On 12/09/99 at 09:02 PM,  isteve@outhere.f9.co.uk said:

>How do people handle salvage rights?  For that matter, how do they
>work in the real world?

>For example, our heroes come across a damaged, but basically intact
>ship adrift in the outer reaches of a remote system.  After checking
>the ship for survivors they find it deserted.  Once they manage to
>get the power plant online, drives working and get the ship refuelled
>they decide to leave a skeleton crew aboard, get her to civilisation
>and claim salvage rights. HOWEVER on further examination they
>discover this multi-million credit Free Trader was financed with 30
>years left to pay off.

>The owner/operators are dead so does the ship belong to the bank? Is
>it like a mortgage where an insurance policy pays off the balance of
>the finance leaving the ship to be inherited by the owners\\\' next of
>kin?  Or does it belong to the salvaging PCs?

IMTU, it varies from polity to polity, but in general the salvage
crew has *a* claim, but not necessarily the only or best claim to
the ship.  If the ship has an outstanding mortgage then the mortgage
holder (usually a bank) also has a claim.  If the ship is insured
and the insurance has paid off the mortgage and/or heirs then the
insurance company has a claim.  If the insurance has been paid off
and the insurance company has written the policy off their taxes,
then the ship belongs to the taxing government.  The case will wind
up in court, variously called Salvage Court, Claims Court, or
Maritime and Space Court.

In almost every case the PC\'s are going to end up with a percentage
of the ship\'s worth and not the ship itself.  The PC\'s aren\'t going
to get to keep the ship.  The only time the salvagers will get the
ship is when it isn\'t considered to be worth much.

This is during peacetime.

During war, if a ship is captured by a licensed privateer *and* that
side isn\'t soundly defeated <G> then the ship will be retitled and
retained by those that captured it.  In some cases this will be the
government that licensed the privateer, but in others it will be the
private parties themselves.  IMTU, that\'s the big reason someone
would want a Letter of Marque, the possibility of grabbing a few
ships.

In my PBEM, the Mae Lee started life as a merchant ship belonging to
a Zeristu megacorp.  It was captured by Akus Moby while he had a
Letter of Marque during the First Zeristu war, refitted and turned
into an exploratory trader.  The Zeristu corp have been trying
legally (and otherwise) to get their ship back for 30 plus years.
As long as it stays out of Zeristu space the odds are very slim they
will succeed...legally.  Of course, if they could get that ship back
into a Zeristu port then the weight of the law might shift. <g>

Eris
