> Here\'s a question thats confused me:  How would the 3I
> characterize the difference between \'salvage rights\' and
> \'prizes\'? Do the terms overlap, or are they meant to
> distiguish between craft recovered by civilians vs. craft
> recovered by the military?

"Salvage" applies to abandoned vessels, and to crewed vessels in need
of assistance. Other posts have gone into salvage law extensively.

A "prize" is a vessel belonging to the enemy and taken by force of arms
by either a military vessel or a licensed privateer. The value of the
prizedetermined by selling it at auction (though it may be "bought in"
by the Navy). 

Everything below is from practices during the Naploeonic era, since
taking of prizes pretty much quit after that (and privateers became
illegal). To the best of my knowledge that last time anyone took a
prize was during WWII, when Commander Gallery and his men took a German
submarine as a prize (it\'s now on display in Chicago). They only did it
because we needed the codebooks and encryption gear.

The prize money goes 100% to a privateer operating alone. I believe
there\'s a standard formula for how the money gets divided between the
owners, officers and crew.

If a naval vessel made the capture, the admiral of the fleet gets a
cut. So do any vessels in sight at the time of the capture (it is
assumed their presence aided in the capture).

Again, there\'s a formula as to how the captain, officers and crew get
shares of the money. I think the British used something like 1/4th to
the captain, another 1/4th split among the officers, and another 1/4th
split among the crew. The remaining 1/4th was what the admiral and
"supporting ships" got. 

*Don\'t* use my figures. Look them up. Especially since there may be
versions that include adjusting shares according to rank and seniority.

