> mutinies,  spaces the ship owner, then gets themselves killed trying to 
> pirate a supply shuttle, the bank loses their entire interest in the
> Far Trader?

The insurance company will pay the original owners. After all, once
word gets out that the ship has been seized by pirates, it\'s value to
the bank or to the heirs of the owner is essentially *nil*. For one
thing, getting it back intact is both unlikely and apt to take a *long*
time. 

The insurance company might have a claim against the ship. But
government policy could easily be that the insurance company gets to
"write off" the loss (a tax break) and the people who captured the
vessels back from the pirates get to keep it.

This costs the government little, doesn\'t really hurt the insurance
company (and also encourages people to *have* insurance!) and gives
folks another reason to fight back against pirates, in that if they
win, they get the value of whatever the pirates had.

> Here\'s a thought:
> If the Captain of such a new ship breaks a bad smuggling law and his ship 
> gets seized, does the bank lose all their interest in the ship as well?
> Or does the mortgage contract have a clause that, if the Captain ever
> uses his ship in a fashion that will get it seized, he is immediately 
> considered to be in breach of contract, and *no longer* the legitimate
> owner of the vessel? His possession of it could then be considered
> illegitimate, and the seized ship ight have to be returned to the rightful
> owner (the bank) as recovered stolen property used in the commission
> of a crime, rather than retained by the seizing government. 

Nope. Check the way customs laws work. The smuggling vessel is
*forfeit* if the "owners" were involved. Period. 

If the owners weren\'t involved, then the ship *usually* isn\'t seized.
But it\'s up to the government whose laws wewre violated.

Life isn\'t fair. If a government "nationalizes" the factories a company
built, the company is pretty much out of luck. Which is why banks are
kinda picky about *where* you are building when they go to loan you
money. 

Of course this backfires. Some banks went ahead and loaned money to
buld factories in country X, reasoning that since they\'d made large
loans to the government of X, they could use that as pressure.
Sometimes it just meant the country was *more* willing to write off the
loans, since nationalizing the factories got the bank mad at them
anyway. 

If the bank has the clout to get the country (planet) boycotted, then
the government will sometimes relent and pay the bank back. If the bank
can\'t bring enough pressure to bear, too bad.

> The bank would love this, but I could see some governments claiming that 
> the bank had hired the Captain to do just this kind of thing. Especially
> if the exact same Far Trader gets snagged two months from now, with
> a different Captain, and the bank\'s lawyers primed and ready with the
> same arguments.

And if they seize the ship, the bank is SOL. 

That\'s life. 

*Most* of the time countries don\'t want to get banks and big companies
upset at them. But not always.

