This is one of those oft argumented questions with child psychologists.
I\'ll state now I am not qualified and for Chris, I can\'t provide links,
bibliographies, etc., but my wife has studied in her childcare work for the
last several years (always continuing with it!), has brought to light many
facets of "human nature."

One set of studies revolved about various childplay control by parents over
several years.  There was no way that mum was going to let little Johnny
play with guns, swords, etc. until he was over 8-years old (her arbitrary
setting), nor could he view violent content children shows.  While he was a
toddler, he was using sticks and his sister\'s Barbie dolls as knives and
guns!  By 5, his mother caved and allowed friends to gift him toy guns
because he played cowboys and indians, cops and robbers, and soldiers, etc.
off his own back.  The resulting theory was that it is a genetic thing with
males (and certain females that are born with an abundance of male hormones)
to learn quickly and accurately, hunting and killing skills for the care and
protection of their family.

Thus, little Johnny only sees guns in commercials and on the news, yet takes
instinctively to using them (it was amusing to see him bend Barbies legs and
arms perpendicular to her body and using it as an SMG... arms and legs as
pistol- and fore-grips!).  The theory also went on to say that in medieval
times, warring was natural and men could easily stand toe to toe and hack
each other down with swords and implements, as it was a more primal urge
that was propagated by the thinking of the time.  Now days, boys are losing
out to this because the touted idea is to be more human, and with better and
widespread education, the warriors of tomorrow are learning it is natural to
"not kill"... but this is only coming at an age where it can be taught with
maturity.  In the old days, men didn\'t have a clue about "their feminine
side" let alone practicing it.

Perhaps it\'s the times in which we live, with private instincts being
"unlearned" as we grow, then relearn\'t by those in military occupations?

