    'index' => 'eg526',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'Some interesting ideas in this thread ; let\'s combine them.
Control of bits of the electromagnetic spectrum is going to be critical
in near and future-tech wars (until everyone relies on meson
communicators and remote gravitic or neutrino sensing, or psionics?).

	Mesoscale sensors, relying on aperture synthesis techniques, are
deployed above (geosync orbit?) and on the battlefield.
	The battlefield based sensors have a dual role - the obvious one and
also to provide a baseline radiofrequency spectrum for descendants of
systems like LockMart\'s \'Silent Sentry\'[1].
	Another possible avenue of attack is to target the enemy\'s electronics
(is it possible to perform TEMPEST type surveillance at a range of
several hundred metres, or even further?).
	Other possibilities include orbital infrared surveillance (low depth
ground penetrating systems are currently being evaluated), and
sophisticated optical sensors to track submarines by bioluminescence
from dinoflagellates disturbed by the vehicle\'s passage ; or, using
models of oceanic circulation to detect variances in wave patterns
caused by marine traffic(!).
	Use of such advanced \'sigint\' may partly explain the enormous fire
advantages higher-TL forces enjoy over their less well-equipped
counterparts.


[1] \'Silent Sentry\' relies on aircraft flying through an airspace
through which commercial TV, etc. are being broadcast - the reflected
signals can be used to localise things. Current test runs have
successfully detected objects less than 10m2 at up to 190km, with a 3m X
8m antenna.

Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
