    'topic' => 'Length of Jumps',
    'body' => 'I was looking through the Bits book 101 starships last night
(Nice book shame it doesn\'t have HG stats for the ships).

Not having bought GT I didn\'t realise that it allowed fractional 
acceleration (eg 0.9G). Then a strange though occured to me (probably caused 
buy not enough sleep/too much Guinness) Why not have fractional jump 
numbers. Then I had a fit of common sense and notice how all the systems are 
in the middle of hex\'s and so jumping 5.5 hex\'s would leave you in the 
middle of nowhere, or does it?.......

(this next bit requires a non-proportional font)
    _   _   _   _
   /1\\_/ \\_/ \\_/3\\
   \\_/ \\_/ \\_/ \\_/
   / \\_/ \\_/ \\_/ \\
   \\_/ \\_/ \\_/ \\_/
   / \\_/ \\_/ \\_/ \\
   \\_/ \\_/ \\_/ \\_/
   / \\_/ \\_/ \\_/2\\
   \\_/ \\_/ \\_/ \\_/

From hex 1 to hex 2 is a jump 6, and from hex 1 to hex 3 is also jump 6. But 
if you measure it in a straight line it\'s only jump 5. Try it with a ruler.

Does this mean we should be measuring exact distances on our already 
inaccurate sector maps? Or should I just drink more/less Guinness, get some 
more sleep and forget about it?

J.

