    'date' => 'Fri, 10 Dec 1999 22:41:20 +1000',
    'body' => '> From: "William F. Hostman" 
> >What is a munchkin?
> 
> IME, it\'s applied to those whose motto tends to be "I can do more
> mega-damage than you can", as well as demanding "More pay for less play"
> for their characters. They also tends to do 3 hour analyses of their
> GURPS or Hero system characters looking for the ultimate point saving
> ballance.

<snicker>

I used to play Hero system games (mostly Champions) a lot.  I could write
down point-optimised characters straight off the top of my head, because I
knew the rules, and had done the analysis in non-play time.

The resulting characters weren\'t quite the most powerful possible, because
I had tuned them down to make them roleplayable, rather than just being
combat monsters, but they were tough enough.  Of course, they did all tend
to look a lot like each other...

Knowing the combat rules helped, as did actually having been involved in
enough (gamed) combats to have developed some tactical skill.

Of course I can\'t do that with GURPS, but given that I would most likely be
playing GT, or something strange like Atomic Horror, I doubt it would
matter that much.  The munchkins would have their Scout/Commando
battledress, and I would simply attempt to avoid being in the area when
they get themselves killed....

I\'ve got a TNE game starting after New Year, the collapse of civilisation
as we know it permitting.  I\'ve been talking Traveller to the high-school
kids who will provide most of the group over the last month.  I\'ve been
getting all kinds of flashes of "Oops!  These people actually care about
the stats of the guns they will be using", and other things I rarely pay
much attention to.  

I may just kit them out with some standard gear supplied by their patron,
and not let them select their stuff.  That way, they will get lots of
spiffy ACRs and things (maybe even combat armour, or at least combat
environment suits), but I won\'t have to worry about them stressing over the
urgency of owning a gauss pistol, or wearing battledress everytime they
walk down the street.  

Of course, they won\'t be freelance adventurers, but will be picked agents
of the Generic Star Empire, so I will have them pretty tightly on a string
anyway.  This is to make it easy for me to introduce them to the setting,
and the scenarios I\'ve set up for them, which will lead on to them having
greater freedom to make decisions once they know what kind of decisions
they will need to make.

Alan Bradley
alanb@elf.brisnet.org.au
