>What is a munchkin?

Is this a rhetorical question, or a serious request for a definition?

From the TML FAQ:

"Munchkin - Derogatory term referring to RPG players who is interested in
minimising their disadavantages, maximising their advantages and having the
coolest weapons and equipment. Role playing skills are not to the forefront
here."
- ----

That sounds more like a powergamer to me.

To my mind a munchkin differs from a powergamer in that a powergamer works
within the framework of the applicable rule system to create the most
powerful character they can. Munchkins will ignore rules they don\'t
like/understand.

Thus munchkins end up wielding +10 "Holy Vorpal Avengers of Sharpness"
Bastard Swords in both hands, or have several disadvantages in Gurps that
add up to 150pts (or more... *shudder*) at start etc.

Munckins also tend to be young or newbies, and usually progress to being
powergamers as they \'mature\' in game experience, as that tends to suit their
style of play.

Munchkins will take a \'broken\' ship or NPC design and use it to justify
their own interpretation of reality in the game. ie will point to the
character sheet of the \'young\' Conan in the back of Gurps:Conan, as an
example of a \'realistic\' starting character for a barbarian warrior, even
though at age 16 Conan is a 217.5pt character with 119 pts of
disadvantages... eeek! (note: by the time Conan is at the height of his
power, as King of Aquilonia, he\'s a 859.5pt character with 106pts of
disadvantages....).

A powergamer will stick to the rules (eg in Gurps no more than 40 pt\'s of
disadvantages unless you have only one for more than 40pts) but will aim to
become as powerful as Conan / Strephon / Darth Vader etc during the game.

Matt
