>
>>There has been a decline, I agree, but not _that_ much.
>
>While I agree that 1/20th sounds pretty crazy, the people quoting it are
>the ones with their fingers on the pulse of the industry.  Now, since the
>sampling of how well games sell is not even remotely exact, I have no doubt
>that that figure is off a bit.  Game companies and distributors don\'t
>exactly share their financial data, and any sampling will be bound to be
>inaccurate.  How much, and in what direction, I have no clue.

From my view-point, as a player/GM/collector in one of the strong bastions
of "Roleplaying Is Life" cities (Anchorage AK tends to NEED such
diversions).... About 1/3rd of the players have been LOST to CCG\'s. ABout
1/6 have been lost to Computer Games... (I just can\'t bring myself to call
it Roleplaying). The average age of people doing roleplaying is climbing
here. When I was a kid, the average was about 18; now the average age is
about 25,with more andd more over 40\'s, and somewhat fewer under 20\'s...
This is purely guestimation based upon local conventions, tournaments, etc.

I do know that many of the wargame companies that had one or two
"roleplaying products" (TFG, as case in point, AH for another) have dropped
off the face of the planet, at least as far as name recognition goes. AH
had RuneQuest 3rd, and TFtFV; TFG had Prime Directive, Crime Fighter, and
Delta Force RPGs. AH, as we all know, was bought by hasbro. TFG lost their
cash cow, ADB\'s Star Fleet Battles, and along with it went PD.

WOTC spent a lot of money consolidating the market. They found good ideas,
bought them. Ars Magica. Talislanta. TSR.

Almost everybody now plays one of the following, at least part time: D&D,
Palladium Games, GURPS, Hero, WW-Storyteller. Idicators of a market
correction. The market was getting too broad, and the die-off is a sign
that the industry is HEALTHY, since the companies that  died made room for
better ones, like DP9.

 Linking Trav to one of the Survivors of the industry die-off insures it
will survive. Much as *I* may think GURPS mechanics are Dated, annoying,
and counter intuitive, it has the 3rd largest representation in stores of
any line of RPG materials I\'ve seen; GT therefore is a guarantee of
Traveller surviving in some form for a long while.

