    'topic' => ' There goes our salvage... and car!',
    'body' => '>From: "Jason T. Barnabas" <cybernaut@netzero.net>

>Can Walt recover his money from the dealer who 
>didn\'t do his homework?

Sure, at least if the deal took place in the United
States.  Here, under the Uniform Commercial Code, the
seller of goods gives an implied warranty of title. 
That is, unless seller specifically discloses that
seller does not have or does not know if he has title
to the item, he is deemed to be promising that he does
have title. 

When it turns out that the car was stolen from some
third party, it becomes clear that the seller never
acquired title, so could never pass title to Walt.  So
the true owner gets his car back from Walt.  

Walt now has remedies against the seller.  He can sue
for damages for breach of contract, arguing that the
seller failed to perform on his promise to deliver
ownership as well as mere possession of the car.  In
the alternative, he can sue for rescission, an
equitable remedy that puts the parties back where they
were as if the contract had never been made; the
argument there is that the consideration for the
contract -- ownership of the car -- failed.  

In this case, there is no practical difference between
the two remedies.  Walt\'s damages for breach are the
purchase price.  Walt\'s remedy in rescission is to get
restitution of the purchase price.  

- --Glenn
