    'topic' => ' OT/Flamebait: Starship Troopers revisited',
    'body' => '>From: Michel Vaillancourt
<misha@empire.atlantic-online.ns.ca>

>You\'re 100% right, and the distinction is *lost* on 
>civvies sometimes...  I used to paint-ball with a few

>lads in the Canadian Militia...  all us Forces types 
>would get creamed when up against a pure civvies 
>team...  why?  We\'d try not to take casualties;  we 
>had a healthy disinterest in getting "killed".  

That\'s game-playing versus simulation.  The military
people are simulating a battle, and the civilians are
playing a game.  Winning a battle is very different
than winning a game; you can say that they have
different victory conditions.  

For example, you win the game by getting possession of
the other side\'s flag more often than the other side
gets possession of yours.  You win a battle by (1)
achieving your tactical objective of getting
possession of the other side\'s flag, and (2) taking
few enough casualties that your side didn\'t break and
run and is not tactically compromised by lack of
manpower, and (3) not having so many of your side run
away that you\'re not tactically compromised.   

- --Glenn
