>Comments, Keith?

My response boils down to, YMMV.  Remember that different games sell better 
or worse in different locations.  In the Bay Area, where I live, the sales 
of GURPS is definitely below average.  On the other hand, I have had a lot 
conversations with retailers across the country and quite a few of them 
said that GURPS is one of their most reliable and constant sellers.

The bottom line is this: ignoring the local scope and in the terms of raw 
sales, GURPS is usually in the top four systems when it comes to game 
products sold (next to AD&D, Vampire and Palladium).  GURPS has always been 
fluctuating around in the top ten, but in the last few years it has been 
solidly in the top five.  The "consistant three" (AD&D, Vampire, 
Palladium), even though they regularly change position between who sold 
more products, were almost always selling on the top three.  This year has 
seen GURPS take the #3 position and bump Palladium to #4.

My personal belief as to why GURPS is claiming more of the market is 
because the layout quality of the books have increased dramatically 
(without a reduction of the quality of the text) and the addition of 
Traveller *as a line* (rather than a conversion book) to the lineup.  Not 
only does GURPS Traveller pull in the "old school" CT diehards, but more 
importantly it gives a constant stream of products around a central 
setting.  Like I said before, selling a steady stream supplements is what 
helps pay the bills.  SJ Games had climbed up to the top five selling RPG 
lines without an officially supported game setting.  With the addition of 
the Traveller line, and potentially additional Technomancer books, I have 
no doubts that GURPS will stay in the top three position for a long time.


>Which supplements do your distributors say are most in demand?

Magic, Psionics, and the Tech books are big and consistent sellers.  We 
have also had tremendous success with books like Technomancer, Black Ops, 
and of course, Traveller.  Keep in mind that I don\'t really deal with 
distributors or pay that much attention to sales.  Our sales people could 
answer that question much better than a webmonkey like myself.  :)

