>>2) No energy _except_ gravitational potential energy. (Ie. just the energy
>>from dropping the rock, nothing added for orbital velocity, rotation of
>>location on planet, etc.)

> This is a weaker assumption - almost all trajectories will retain a
> lot of its orbital velocity, much higher than the GPE.

As I recall...

GPE = 0.5 * M * (Ve(orbit) - Ve(surface))^2

Where Ve is escape velocity. Unless that\'s one *high* orbit, "surface
orbital velocity" is going to be much higher than that "difference of
escape velocities" used to figure GPE.

And "surface orbital velocity" is a good "first approximation" at
impact velocity for something launched at a ground target from orbit. 

More likely the object will impacy\\t at the velocity of the orbit it
started from *plus* the difference in escape velocity between that
altitude and the surface. 

Objects launched from something orbiting the *star* rather than the
planet will impact at (at least) the difference in orbital velocities
around the star plus the difference in *system* escape velocity for the
two orbits. If one object was orbiting in the opposite direction, then
you *add* the orbital velocities.

