    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> "Munchkin - Derogatory term referring to RPG players who is interested in
> minimising their disadavantages, maximising their advantages and having the
> coolest weapons and equipment. Role playing skills are not to the forefront
> here."
> ----
>
> That sounds more like a powergamer to me.
>
> To my mind a munchkin differs from a powergamer in that a powergamer works
> within the framework of the applicable rule system to create the most
> powerful character they can. Munchkins will ignore rules they don\'t
> like/understand.

My experience is that "powergamers" work *within* the rules. Munchikins
work *in spite of* the rules. 

My knack for being able to remember even trivial rules well enough to
find them in a minute or less in rulebooks I\'m familiar with meant that
munchkins tended to not get started in my games. Or even games I was a
player in. Y\'see I had this bad habit of listening to a would-be
munchkin trying to tell the ref how XX says he can do this, and digging
out the appropriate rulebook/supplement and handing it to the GM while
pointing at the paragraph that says XX doesn\'t let the munichkin
do it that way. 

"Yes, I see that the rule *does* say XX. But I also see that it says
only left handed elves get that bonus. Since you are neither left
handed, nor an elf...."

The best solution to folks who get carried away with "powergaming"
(assuming they\'ve become a problem) is generally to expose them to some
players who *really* role play their characters. That usually gets to
them because it\'s obviously more fun and looks easier.

