    'from' => 'Leonard Erickson',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Gallery wrote a book about his wartime experiences including the
> capture of the U-505. I don\'t recall the name of it but it\'s got a few
> giggles in it.

Given the way the one piece of his "fiction" I\'ve read ("Now Hear
This") reads, I wouldn\'t be a bit surprized.

> The ObTrav. Do IN intelligence officers cringe whenever a hotshot
> Cruiser captain drags a prize into base? Or is the time lag between
> Losing a ship and finding out you\'ve lost the ship make it unlikely
> that encryption procedures can be changed quickly enough? Or
> do Navies asume that ciphers will be compromised quickly anyway
> and change codes on a monthly or quicker basis? Is that even possible
> considering distances and travel times?

Well, WWII drove home the lesson that you *have* to assume that the
*only* thing about your ciphers that the enemy *doesn\'t* know is the
current key. So nobody will be going after *equipment*, just the
storage media containing the code keys. 

These will be set up for easy self-destruct (try reading a CD that\'s
had a thermite charge set off on top of it :-). But it\'s still
*possible* to capture them as you want to wait until it\'s pretty
certain that you\'ll be taken before you destroy them. 

The size of the Imperium makes distributing code keys a real problem.
On the other hand, ship-to ship comm may be mostly by what Weber refers
to as "laser whiskers". This nor only means that you can get away with
fairly simple codes, but also that it\'s harder to spot you from comm
traffic. 

And then, of course, there\'s the question of whether or not public key
ciphers will endure the test of time. If they do, the situation changes
*greatly*. There\'s little *need* to change keys. All that capturing a
ship will give you is the ship\'s "private key" and those of the
officers and crew. Which means you can decode messages *to* them, and
fake messages *from* them. Which isn\'t really all that useful.

