  {
    'body' => 'James Lindsay wrote:
>>>>>>>>>>>>
> Anybody who tries *that* level of "rules lawyering" in a campaign *I* 
> am running will get shown the section of the rules that states the GM 
> is free to alter or interpret rules any way he chooses. If that doesn\'t 
> work, he or she will be shown the door. 

Question: Why don\'t rules lawyers ever remember *those* particular rules? 
Selective memory, I would think. 
>>>>>>>>>>>>>
I think it\'s appropriate for a player to take the rules as written,
until the GM tells her otherwise. Yes, the "GM has final say" rule
trumps any other text in the book, but a player can\'t make *any*
character or piece of equipment without being able to trust the 
applicable rules. Now, if the GM hasn\'t been clear about which
particular rules are applicable...

Writing that, I\'ve seen GM\'s who never even let a player *see* the
rulebook, much less allowed them to make something rule-tweaky with
it. "How can I get a faster starship?" <roll, roll, roll> - "You
ask Feldzarr the Engineer NPC, he says your ship is as fast as you
can get." "Why?" <roll, roll, roll> - "Your character blows his
Engineering roll, you don\'t know why."

It\'s a matter of expectations, of course. I recall seeing a Champions
(superhero RPG) campaign planning sheet, which gave new players a
combination of hard & fast character creation rules ("no one can
have defenses that make their hero perfectly immune to normal bullets")
and campaign expectations ("the heroes will be relatively unknown
vigilantes in a city where corruption and crime are rife, morality
of the stories will be in shades of grey..."). I really liked that
idea, and stole (er, "expanded") it for use with other kinds of
campaigns as well.

Walt Smith
