    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> James Lindsay wrote:
>>>>>>>>>>>>>
>> Anybody who tries *that* level of "rules lawyering" in a campaign *I* 
>> am running will get shown the section of the rules that states the GM 
>> is free to alter or interpret rules any way he chooses. If that doesn\'t 
>> work, he or she will be shown the door. 
>
> Question: Why don\'t rules lawyers ever remember *those* particular rules? 
> Selective memory, I would think. 
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
> I think it\'s appropriate for a player to take the rules as written,
> until the GM tells her otherwise. Yes, the "GM has final say" rule
> trumps any other text in the book, but a player can\'t make *any*
> character or piece of equipment without being able to trust the 
> applicable rules. Now, if the GM hasn\'t been clear about which
> particular rules are applicable...

True. Though usually, it was someone trying to tell me (or the GM if I
was a player) that some rules clearly indicate as "optional" or
"unofficial" *had* to be used. 

Beyond that, *I* try to keep people aprised of "house rules". And I\'m
not too proud to start a game by telling the players "Ok, X is getting
to be a *real* problem. If it isn\'t toned down, it\'s going to really
screw up the campaign. So I\'ve altered the rules governing it a bit.
Here\'s the way it works now. Any questions?"

And that *usually* works. Sometimes folks will suggest handling the
problem a bit differently. Sometimes I\'ll agree. Sometimes I won\'t. But
once we are done discussing it *that\'s it*. We have a new rule. Only
somebody who wasn\'t at the session gets to argue about it. 

BTW, it\'s odd, but I can\'t *ever* recall the *players* telling a GM
that a rule  or power or gadget needed to be "toned down". Funny how
that works...:-)

> Writing that, I\'ve seen GM\'s who never even let a player *see* the
> rulebook, much less allowed them to make something rule-tweaky with
> it. "How can I get a faster starship?" <roll, roll, roll> - "You
> ask Feldzarr the Engineer NPC, he says your ship is as fast as you
> can get." "Why?" <roll, roll, roll> - "Your character blows his
> Engineering roll, you don\'t know why."

I know a couple of people who can run a good *interesting* campaign
*without* a rulebook. Both are natural story tellers and really fair
about things. And they started doing this in the early 80s, long before
the "story teller" type games arrived on the scene. 

