One thing that works is to use some "canned" scenarios from supplements
or magazines as a way to let people get familar with the system and
background. Sure, this means the first week or three will be devoted to
the scenario. But once they\'ve been through that, and you\'ve cleared up
any worries ("Yeah, I *know* the setup in the enemy HQ was *stupid*,
but that\'s the way the scenario was set up and I didn\'t want to waste
time rewriting everything. Don\'t worry, I\'ll be sneakier." :-) *then*
you can start them generating their characters.

Or let them borrow rule books between sessions of the "training
scenario" to let them try to design something and have you look it over
next session.

