    'subj' => 'Re: Velocity/Vector',
    'from' => 'Leonard Erickson',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Hello.
> This is probably considered an easy question: Does any ship maintain its
> original velocity and vector when exiting jumpspace?

Actually, it\'s the source of a lot of arguments, because the rules
don\'t *say*, and Mark Miller gets a bit vague about details when we
ask. :-)

Personally, I say yes. You maintain your velocity as determined by
refernce to whatever object you used before the jump. Both magnitude
and direction.

Others say it keeps the vector *relative* to the local star. That is
you enter jump with a certain vector relative to the star you are
jumping from and leave jump with the same magnitude and direction
vector, but relative to the *destination* star. My question is, that\'s
fine for velocity towards or away from the star, but if you\'ve got any
"sideways" velocity, what determines what direction *it* is in? 

And then there are those who point out that the rules seem to suggest
that it\'s preferable to have a "low velocity" when entering jump, and
then say you enter jump at rest, and leave it at rest. And of course, I
come back with "at rest relative to *what*?"

Retaining your original vector does the least damage to physics, and
with a typical Traveller ship, it doesn\'t take all the long to kill
even 200 km/sec relative velocity carried over from the previous
system. 

It also gives a reason for ships to prefer certain "lanes" depending on
their planned destination. Make a run to jump such that it helps match
your velocity vector to that of your destination. That means that from
any given planet, and any given time, there\'s a "preferred" direction
to boost in on your way to the 100 diameter limit. Going in any other
direction means there will be a bigger mismatch in velocities when you
arrive and thus, higher fuel consumption.

It\'s not *critical*, but it makes a difference. Sort of like modern jet
airliners preferring altitudes where they\'ll have a tail wind over ones
where they\'ll have a headwind. It\'s not that they can\'t make the trip
even against a headwind. It\'s just that they\'ll save a *lot* of fuel if
they get the tailwind. :-)

- -- 
Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
 shadow@        <--preferred
leonard@     <--last resort
