    'month' => '12',
    'topic' => ' Munchkins',
    'body' => 'From: Alan Bradley <alanb@elf.brisnet.org.au>


> How do people deal with that?  I don\'t really care what game you are
> playing:  how do you go about introducing new people to a complex,
>and unfamiliar setting?  I have to admit that I originally used to just
>wing it, but the games I tended to run weren\'t particularly coherent,
>and this time I\'m trying to focus on a small astrographical area and a
>very intense power struggle.

I\'m a huge fan of handouts. I like giving the players handouts, no matter
what game we\'re playing. To prepare them for a recent Traveller campaign, I
wrote up a movie review for an anti-Solomani action movie, and a piece on
the music scene (both are available at my site: http://www.pil.net/~semo ).
I also gave them other bits I had written, which are also on the site.

In my own experience, handouts work very well, especially handouts which
have little bearing on the rules, but which help to establish the
background. I\'m a handout nut though. In one traveller campaign five years
ago or so (geez, it\'s been that long?) I made a tape of a repeating distress
signal from an ancient alien ship, which worked extremely well at setting
the mood for the players during the session in which they encountered the
vessel.

Your own mileage may vary, of course.
