I said PLAY, not PURCHASE. I know a lot of Champions 4th ed players (It\'s
easily more popular than GURPS locally, as far as numbers of players goes,
about 3:2 vs GURPS). What people PLAY is indicative of the market
correction. L5R, Deadlands, and others really are not THAT common to play...

One of the things that has been a problem with Hero\'s sales is that they
are aimed at GM\'s. In a typical Hero group, IME, one or two players have
the base book, and only the GM has anything more, for a group of 5-7
players.

GURPS, most of the players will have the base book (Same sized group,
abnout 3 copies plus the GM\'s copy), and many of the supplements have
materials very clearly presented to the players, but this is not so clearly
defined as in the Hero layouts.

AD&D2 (and soon D&D3) has a one-book for players, 3 for GM mentality; when
running events at boscos, I could count on every player having a PH. If I
was running Ravenloft, at least one would have the RL book. Similer for the
other settings.

Palladium sells. Mostly to munchkins. Many of whom really are under 16. For
many more, they are intellectually but not physically under 16. Most
Palladium groups I\'ve seen or heard of a re munchkins on parade, out on a
killing spree.

>>  Linking Trav to one of the Survivors of the industry die-off insures it
>>will survive. Much as *I* may think GURPS mechanics are Dated, annoying,
>>and counter intuitive, it has the 3rd largest representation in stores of
>>any line of RPG materials I\'ve seen; GT therefore is a guarantee of
>>Traveller surviving in some form for a long while.
>
>I disagree with your comment on the mechanics of GURPS, but everything else
>I am in complete agreement with.

Hmmm. I\'ve been picking up gurps since MTM. I was an avid TFT player. GURPS
mechanics are firmly grounded in the early 80\'s. No real concessions to
standardized difficulties, a concept that began to flourish in the late
80\'s (CF StarWars, T2300/2300AD, T2K 1stEd, MT). Huge list of narrow
skills, vs the later approach of broader skills with specializations. 3d6
based mechanics, which finally started to cease being the industry standard
in the mid to late 80\'s, with the above system; almost every game from the
early 80\'s and late 70\'s uses the classic 3d6 or 3-18 attribute ranges;
Just to name a few that kept this standard: Mechwarrior (1e), Palladium,
The Arcanum, V&V, S&S, D&D, GURPS, Space Opera, Jorune, and even T2300, T2K
1e, Star Patrol, and almost anything by FGU...... Traveller was distinctive
by using 2d6 for attributes; later period games began getting away fromthe
3-18 model in the mid 80\'s: Talislanta (0-normed), Shadowrun (1-6 range for
humans), Ars Magica (0 normed), Mechwarrior 2e (1-6)[early 90\'s, IIRC],
Star Wars (ratings in Dice)[86-87], Torg (log based atts, 5-12, norm of 8).
The 90\'s have seen much more experimentation with attribute ranges and
basises, not to mention mechanics.

I\'m not saying the GURPS rules are unplayable, but I find them to show very
clearly their age of origin, plus they show their TFT roots. I also find
many of the bits in GURPS counter intuitive, but I find the same about
Mechwarrior 1st Ed, Palladium\'ss rifts-compatable series of games, Jorune,
and Space Opera. They are all games I found I needed to have the rules in
my lap to run the game (I don\'t play at tables, but in the living room).
Traveller, D&D, Star Wars, Ars Magica, and Storyteller, they are designed
so that the mechanics are easy to memorize, easy to run, and only 2-3 pages
of tables  MIGHT crop up in play.

Then again, I think the best effort I\'ve seen in the last 10 years on any
game was DragonLance Fifth Age. I love it as a GM. Slick, Well presented,
easy to teach and to run, and card based. Getting players to understand the
following has been the problem, though: "The cards are effectively like
having four dice, already rolled, sitting in frount of you, and getting to
choose which one you will use as it sits. Once used, you reroll it."

William F. Hostman  |  "Smith & Wesson: THe original Point and Click
interface!"
