>> within three months of it\'s recovery, assuming the theft
>> was within one year prior to recovery. If they do, they must
>> pay fair salvage value (10% of fair market value at time of
>> theft) plus costs (Charter fees plus food, fuel and ammo
>> expenses) as a finder\'s fee. And the theft report to the
>> local admirality at point of discovery of the theft must
>> accompany such claims.
>
>That assumes that stolen velssels have the information sent
>through the x-boat network and would be a good time frame
>in that light. However, while three months is enough to find out
>if it was stolen, it is not always enough time for the owners
>to get there to reclaim the property. That depends on how
>far away they are as well as how long ago the vessel was stolen
>and should be taken into account by the Admiralty in setting the
>probate time frame.

Take a look at the maritime salvage laws in the international treaties... A
ship is a ship, and, stolen or not, if taken while *abandoned* on the high
sees, may be claimed as salvage. It is advisable, however, not to reflag it
for the same country, so as to avoid THEIR salvage laws or property
reclamation laws.... IMTU, I assume that the interested parties in a
multi-million credit starship WILL spend the 1KCr for the message to
propagate to 16 months range. IMTU, the admiralty courts have a lot of
authority to re-posess ships. So you notify all the admiralty courts in
range within the time/distance range, and they will automatically assume
the claim as filed shoudl the ship turn up.

Since ship ownership is a matter very important for trade, so IMTU, the
laws regulating it are Reserved to the Imperium; local worlds may not
interfere (at least IMTU). Yes, a world need not allow you to register, but
once you find a world that will, and so do, it is in imperial matter. The
restriction on stolen ships recovery times is to force insurance companies
to either trace or pay off within 16 months. Admiralty courts which suspect
an individual is tryign to claim a ship he/she stole, well, they can refuse
the claim, and even return the ship elsewhere, or auction it off, and send
the proceeds to the last listed owner, etc.

