here in alaska, they can get the dealer on selling stolen merchandise, in
itself a crime. Many places in the rest of the US have statutes covering
reciveing stolen property and selling stolen property.  Locally, Vehicles
must have a valid title IN HAND at time of sale. The actual transfer is the
signing of the back of the title (in the right spots), but it is not legal
until either the sold again (only room for 2 sales on an alaskan issued
title), or taken to DMV and a replacement title is issued to the recipient
signature on the back.

A dealer is only likely to take 1st signature titles, and they are supposed
to check id\'s. The state, upon title issue, checks for theft claims,
bank/mechanic/storage liens, etc, and won\'t issue if there is a known lien.

IMTU, ships have a more complex problem. Selling a ship takes action by the
local admiralty, the admirality court of the registation site, and possibly
of the new registration site, if it differs. Until they all agree, the
title is in probate. And any of them can take actions upon finding out
about liens against the ship or it\'s Sellers. So, unless you\'re buying new,
expect at least a few months lag time for probat to clear on PURCHASING a
ship.

