    'body' => '>Question: How do you feel about fencing? As a sport, that is? And how is
>paintball different in it\'s moral implications.


Fencing is a great sport!  It\'s also good to know that you only need remove
the
rubber ball from the end of the sword to use it as a real one if the need
ever
manifested itself (at least for the Epee).  It\'s also interesting to note
that most
cities, at least in the USA don\'t have ordinances against openly carrying
swords (course here in Florida, you can wear a revolver openly on your hip
and not be arrested as well.  Just don\'t pull the trigger.).

On a separate point, I understand that carrying an unconcealed weapon in
Florida is perfectly legal, but that if you \'brandish\' it you can be
charged.  This
isn\'t necessarily true, though.  We once had a very bad neighbor who openly
threatened their landlord with a pistol, which falls under the \'brandishing\'
law, and they weren\'t charged by the police.  The woman in question even
did this with the police there!  They said that they couldn\'t do anything
until she pulled the trigger.  After that incident I decided that if I heard
shooting
there again, I\'d simply start shooting back (there had been multiple
drive by shootings at that point).  It\'s also an interesting thing to point
out that in that town, at midnight of any holiday of note, say the 4th of
July or
New Years, that you would hear not just firecrackers but firearms as well.
One
night sticks in my mind in particular because of the distinctive sound of an
AK-47 going of in burst mode.  All I could think at the times this happened
was
f****** idiots!

So, yes Virginia there are reasons to keep your weapons oiled, and loaded
with
HydraShock rounds.



Eric
