    'from' => 'cos 90 cos90@powersurfr.com',
    'body' => '>I\'m a huge fan of handouts. I like giving the players handouts, no matter
>what game we\'re playing. To prepare them for a recent Traveller campaign, I
>wrote up a movie review for an anti-Solomani action movie, and a piece on
>the music scene (both are available at my site: http://www.pil.net/~semo ).
>I also gave them other bits I had written, which are also on the site.

I\'ve used handouts as a prop in the past. Most recent example, the last
session of my Traveller campaign (now on hiatus until January), the plot
involved a missing woman who was being hunted by some Bad People. There
were posters with her picture and a reward, "Have you seen this woman?",
that sort of thing. So I made up a poster, complete with photo of the
woman (I used a pic of Angie Harmon from Law & Order), and handed it to
the players as an example of the posters they\'re seeing all over the
starport... It gave them something tangible for the plot hook.

>ago or so (geez, it\'s been that long?) I made a tape of a repeating distress
>signal from an ancient alien ship, which worked extremely well at setting
>the mood for the players during the session in which they encountered the
>vessel.

Sounds like a Space Opera campaign I was in years and years and years ago
(circa 1982) -- one adventure, we the players found a derelict ship. When
we found the ship\'s log entries, the GM played a tape he and his roommate
(who was not in the game) had prepared, complete with appripriate background
sound effects (think of the background sounds on the bridge in the original
Star Trek series) -- and the sounds of explosions and people screaming and
whatnot when the ship was being attacked... It added something to the
ambience.

