>> whole lot of "stuff" out there, and it takes a long time to assimilate. 
>> Because I\'ve got my new game starting soon, I\'m trying to work out what is
>> necessary for people to know to make sensible decisions about character
>> generation, and so on.
>>
>> How do people deal with that?  I don\'t really care what game you are
>> playing:  how do you go about introducing new people to a complex, and
>> unfamiliar setting?  I have to admit that I originally used to just wing
>> it, but the games I tended to run weren\'t particularly coherent, and this
>> time I\'m trying to focus on a small astrographical area and a very intense
>> power struggle.

>One thing that works is to use some "canned" scenarios from
>supplements or magazines as a way to let people get familar with the
>system and background. 

I\'d go further with newbies.  Give them pre-generated characters
with included background material, and run them through one, two or
more set piece scenarios.  Maybe after the first session have them
modify their character and after the second create one of their own
to try out.  The idea is to get them familar with the game setting,
mechanics and character creation before you lock them into a complex
and intense situation.

Eris
