    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>Hello.
>>This is probably considered an easy question:
>
> no, one with many complex answers.
>
>> Does any ship maintain its
>>original velocity and vector when exiting jumpspace?
>>
> According to TNE, yes. But I don\'t recall ever any of the rules mentioning
> what that vector is in relation to. Several articles referenced this
> tendancy also, without specifying frames of reference.

That\'s probably because (in the real world) your velocity is
*different* in different frames of reference. And it is conserved in
*all* of them. Really. 

Therefore if you use the *same* reference frame (ie the same *object*,
not "an object or objects of similar type" as you propose below), the
velocity vector will *automatically* be the same in all the *other*
reference frames.

> IMTU, that vector is rtained in relation to the two most gravitationally
> significant bodies, in the manner of vector angle to ray S1->S2 at jump
> out, and the vector at jump in will be the same in relation to ray
> S1\'->S2\'. Note that S1 is the most significant gravity well, and S2 is the
> second most significant. Generally, this will be the star and planet, or
> planet and moon. IMTU, ships leaving Terra/Sol tend to choose where to jump
> based upon lunal vs solar significance, and how it will affect their vector
> at jump-in. Also, case in point problem If you jump from earth (S1= Earth,
> S2=Luna) to mars orbit, S1 becomes mars, and S2 is Sol. However, if you
> instead jump to mercury, S1 is sol, and S2 is Mercury. If however, you jump
> from nearer Luna than earth,  you might get a reciprical course from what
> you expect. also note that I use the orbital plane of the S1-S2 pair to
> determine 3d referents; if you appear to hold S1 still, and S2 moves
> clockwise around it, you\'re looking "Down". (Even if S2 is the orbital
> center, as in a two body calculation either one may be the "Stable point"
> for viewing.)

Slight problem. There are *two* possible vectors that satisfy your
conditions in some cases. Consider two bodies of equal mass orbiting
about their common center of mass. And even in the cases where the
masses differ, something about your using the "orbital direction" to
define "up & down" bothers me.

Also, you need to define "gravitionally significant". Acceleration due
to gravity? Tidal force (the rate at which the accel *changes*)? Or
something else. 

In the first case S1 is Earth and S2 is the *Sun* (do the
calculations). In the second, S1 is Earth and S2 is the moon (most of
the time).

> Some persons have it retain relative to the galaxay, but then the vectors
> can become days of decelleration. to match with local system speeds.

Huh? That\'d be one *very* unusual star. *One* day of acceleration at 1
g is 864 km/sec. That\'s *way* outside the "normal" range for
relative velocities of stars. As I recall (Bruce, want to check this?)
"normal" values are 50 to 100 km/sec (with 100 km/sec) being *high*.

100 km/sec takes all of 2:46:40 (hh:mm:ss) to kill at 1 g. And consider
that the orbital velocity of Earth is around 30 km/sec.

To put this in perspective, here\'s a table of velocity versus time to
travel one parsec (ie how long before the star would be in a different
hex!) 

v (km/s)  years/parsec    (parsec=3.09e13 km, year=3.15e7 sec)
- ----  ----
100       9809
1000      981
10,000    98.1

So at 1000 km/sec (which only takes about a day to kill), a star will
have moved *several* hexes during the recorded history of the Traveller
universe!

At 100 km/sec, the motion is pretty trivial to kill (see above) and is
mostly significant in figuring jump coordinates, and (if you keep
*original* vectors) makes certain "run to jump" directions preferable
for certain destinations.

At 50 km/sec (a figure I seem to recall Bruce mentioning) it takes only
an hour or so at 1 g to kill the velocity difference. Assuming the
planet\'s motion in its orbit doesn\'t kill most of the difference during
part of the year)

