  {
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> At 11:42 -0500 11/12/99,  shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) wrote:
>> > Hmm. A CJ Cherryh Alliance/Union sourcebook for GURPS - now that 
>>I would buy!
>>
>>I\'d rather have one for the area the Chanur stories take place!
>
> Well, it\'s the same Universe, so we could have both.

Yeah, but so are the Mri (Faded Sun trilogy), and a whole bunch of
other cultures/species all of which really need their *own* sourcebook.

Frankly, I\'m not sure I\'d classify the Union (they\'re the ones with
Azi, right?) as *human*. 

BTW, there\'s a filk song set in Cherryh\'s Union/Alliance universe that
as far as I know *isn\'t* based on a printed story. Alas, it\'s not
easily fitted to the Traveller universe. But I\'m going to have to try
anyway, if only as a song the players hear in a "spacer bar". 

It\'s a mother and her nearly grown child, alternating parts. They are
onboard a "small" ship. It was a sublight probe sent out to survey
systems for jump points. The crew had been in cold sleep, and the ship
was supposed to boost up to near c, then decelerate in the target area
and wake of the crew.

It woke them up all right. Only the computer had glitched and the ship
had never carried out the turnover manuever. Instead it\'d kept on
boosting. So the crew awoke to find a ship cruising along at a hair
under c, and no way to slow it down. 

They were able to survive for years (good recycling) and two of them
(the crew was two men and a woman) even had a kid. Over the years the
men died and the child has grown. Now it\'s just the mother and her son.
And the ship\'s systems are starting to fail and the mother is old and
tired. 

So the song is the mother going back over this (as a sort of lullaby no
less!), and the kid not really understanding all the references to
worlds and stars (to him, stars are something you see on a screen, the
ship is the world).

And in the last verse you find out that she\'s fed herself and her son a
painless poison...

This description really doesn\'t do it justice. It\'s a peaceful melody,
and that just makes the tragedy/horror sneak up on you better. 

Anybody that doesn\'t get choked up hearing this needs to be taken out
and buried. They\'re dead already. 

But it\'s a great example of "filk songs" as "legends that haven\'t
happened yet". 

Besides being a nice bit of background music (the whole tape it\'s on is
pretty good for Traveller, but I think it\'s out of print), it\'s
something that you could ask the players to listen to while you deal
with the latest unexpected curve they thru you (like jumping to the one
system you *hadn\'t* detailed :-)

For extra credit, after they\'ve heard it is a *great* time to misjump
them into an empty hex. Of course they\'ll *kill* you, but it\'ll be
worth it. :-)

Or you can file off the serial numbers and have it be speculation based
on the loss of an early pre-jump ship. Note that even if it\'s "about" a
"real" ship, there\'s no way to rescue them with anything short of
Grandfather\'s tech. And besides, as noted in the song, while that kid
was growing up at near c, folks at "normal" speeds have had enough time
for the human race to go extinct and new races to develop. 

AHA! (Inspiration strikes!)

*This* is how to have some of Grandfather\'s kids survive. He wote them
off after he saw that the ship didn\'t make turnover. 200,000 years for
the rest of the universe has been a decade or so for them... 

Only problem is that they\'ll be about 200,000 light years (something
over 61,000 parsecs) away.

