> >> as legitamate prize, the 3 month probate on vessels IMTU
> >> applies; The lien holders or owners may reclaim the ship
> >> within three months of it\'s recovery, assuming the theft
> >> was within one year prior to recovery. If they do, they must
> >> pay fair salvage value (10% of fair market value at time of
> >> theft) plus costs (Charter fees plus food, fuel and ammo
> >> expenses) as a finder\'s fee. And the theft report to the
> >> local admirality at point of discovery of the theft must
> >> accompany such claims.
> >
> >That assumes that stolen velssels have the information sent
> >through the x-boat network and would be a good time frame
> >in that light. However, while three months is enough to find out
> >if it was stolen, it is not always enough time for the owners
> >to get there to reclaim the property. That depends on how
> >far away they are as well as how long ago the vessel was stolen
> >and should be taken into account by the Admiralty in setting the
> >probate time frame.
> 
> Take a look at the maritime salvage laws in the international
> treaties... A
> ship is a ship, and, stolen or not, if taken while *abandoned* on the
> high
> sees, may be claimed as salvage. It is advisable, however, not to
> reflag it
> for the same country, so as to avoid THEIR salvage laws or property
> reclamation laws.... IMTU, I assume that the interested parties in a
> multi-million credit starship WILL spend the 1KCr for the message to
> propagate to 16 months range. IMTU, the admiralty courts have a lot
> of
> authority to re-posess ships. So you notify all the admiralty courts
> in
> range within the time/distance range, and they will automatically
> assume
> the claim as filed shoudl the ship turn up.

I can understand how our maritime salvage laws are different. Unlike 
in our world where, I suppose, they were negotiated between the 
different naval power in the Imperium they would be set out by 
a single government that is very trade concious. So the laws 
that apply in the space between worlds being that of the Imperium, 
I cannot see that they would fail to return the property that 
has been reported stolen. YMMV.
 
> Since ship ownership is a matter very important for trade, so IMTU,
> the
> laws regulating it are Reserved to the Imperium; local worlds may not
> interfere (at least IMTU). Yes, a world need not allow you to
> register, but
> once you find a world that will, and so do, it is in imperial matter.
> The
> restriction on stolen ships recovery times is to force insurance
> companies
> to either trace or pay off within 16 months. Admiralty courts which
> suspect
> an individual is tryign to claim a ship he/she stole, well, they can
> refuse
> the claim, and even return the ship elsewhere, or auction it off, and
> send
> the proceeds to the last listed owner, etc.
 
I agree, at this point, that the times should be restricted. All I 
was saying is that If it is known that the ship was stolen, even if 
it more than 16 months away, then the law should allow for enough 
time for the owner to get there. I would think that the fact a ship 
had been stolen would not be something the owner would pay for. It 
would be disminiated by the Imperium to all starports along the jump 
routes and then as ships went elsewhere, they would take it to 
the ports off the routes. Again, YMMV.

Terry
